afComment: Laird's always been a natural scorer, averaging over 96 for five seasons straight as a defender before making the switch to the midfield in mid-2020. Since then (a 48-game sample), he's averaged 115 and finished 2022 the clear number one man in Fantasy. It's hard to see him slowing down, given his age (still under 30), his elite tackling numbers (number two in the comp), ability to avoid the tag (teams opted to tag the more damaging Dawson when playing the Crows), consistency (lowest score of 90 last year with 12 games over 120) and the fact the Crows have opted to recruit players outside the midfield in recent years, meaning his full time midfield role should remain. He's the early favourite for the number one scorer again this season, so if you're someone who likes locking in a captain option from Round 1, he's a safe bet for a top score. However, no winning team has started with a player priced over 116 since 2018, so my philosophies say to pick someone priced below this mark who you think can perform in line with the top players for the first few weeks and grab them when they come down a bit in price. This doesn't always work mind you, as 2018 was the year the top priced Tom Mitchell started with 156, 137 and 148 when priced at 127 and if you didn't own him, you were left behind.
afShort: Averaged 115 since midfield move and hard to see that changing

afComment: Brayshaw's career trajectory has been linear - 70, 96, 104 and then 113 last season. It's mirrored his CBA% increase where he finally became a full-time inside midfielder in 2022, which saw him not just become a star in Fantasy but also in real life. His elite mix of tackling in the inside and then bobbing up for marks on the outside give him the ability to go really big, as shown by his 10 games over 120 and a high of 181. However, with Fyfe injury prone and Mundy retiring, Brayshaw's clearly Fremantle's best midfielder. This means he's subject to a tag most weeks. And when his game is built on uncontested possessions (32% contested, average of the top 8 mids is 47%), he can be restricted, which we saw last season with 5 games under 90. He's 23, they've added O'Meara and his TOG should increase a bit, so there's every chance Brayshaw will improve again. However, I'd be playing the odds that he has a sub-90 score or two in the first month or so and try to get him when he's a bit cheaper.
afShort: Elite mark/tackle combo give him the tools to be the best player in Fantasy, only thing stopping him is the weekly tag threat

afComment: Oliver is my type of Fantasy midfielder. High game time (86%), high CBAs (87%) and always around the ball (averaged over 31 touches per game in 2021 and 32 in 2022). The knock on him is his low kick-to-handball ratio and this is what stops him from being a 120 averaging uber premium. However, he's got the consistency to always be above the 110 mark, which he's done the majority of his career. Before last season, opposition teams put more attention into Petracca, which meant Oliver avoided the tag. However, the pendulum shifted in 2022 and Oliver copped his fair share of opposition attention. His elite tackle rate and contested game means he can still score fine with a tag, but at that price there's a good chance we'll see him come in cheaper during the season.
afShort: Consistent stud with the high TOG/CBA combo

afComment: Like Brayshaw, Mills possesses the marks/tackle combo we crave in Fantasy. He lays more tackles and takes more marks that the top 8 mids from 2022. This generally leads to sustainable scoring and ability to go big on any given day - as seen by his 8 scores over 120 and a high of 162. However, Mills is so good defensively and his versatility becomes a burden in Fantasy. There were many occasions last season when he was shifted to be loose man in defence or to a wing and play behind the ball. His CBAs dropped (65% pre bye and 42% post) which coincided with a decrease in scoring (114 to 108). He has the attributes to be the best player in Fantasy, but I'd want to be confident of him sustaining 65%+ CBAs before taking the jump.
afShort: Marks/tackles tick! Versatility and potential to be push behind the ball the concern

afComment: Steele had a disappointing Fantasy season after coming in as one of the two million-dollar players. He averaged an absurd 134 post bye in 2021, meaning a lot of coaches paid up thinking he was worth the $1m. However, he started the season 'slow', averaging 110 in his first 8 games and dropped $89k. This is the risk of paying top dollar in your starting squad, the price changes in the first few weeks are enhanced as the magic number stabilises. Unfortunately, things got worse for owners as Steele hurt his AC joint in Round 9, limiting him to a 77. He returned after missing five games and looked more like the Steele of old, averaging 115 the rest of the way, including an uncharacteristic 65 in Round 22. Steele's rise to the Fantasy elite coincided with Ratten taking over as coach and relinquishing him of his tagging duties. It will be interesting to see what role Ross Lyon has for him, but it is hard to see Steele not being their primary inside midfielder again. Of all the top priced midfielders, I've got him outperforming his price and we should see him produce at least the 115 he did to finish the year.
afShort: 115 post injury should be the least he can do, as long as the new coach keeps him in his role

afComment: Docherty's return in 2021 was one of the stories of the year. Fantasy-wise, he went from looking like not playing at all to the clear number 1 defender, averaging 110 points per game. His scoring ability isn't a shock, considering he has a career best year of 117 pre knee injuries and stretches of 115+ post. His issues in the past from a Fantasy perspective have been his health and attention from opposition players. If last year was anything to go by, he looks in full fitness and teams opted to tag Saad more than Docherty, which is great for Docherty's Fantasy prospects. He finished the season playing as an inside mid, purely due to the injuries to Carlton's regular midfielders, but this is something to watch for as he showed a tackle and ball winning ability that suggest he could be in the Laird/Mills mould of Fantasy defenders turned midfielders. It's more likely he'll return to defence where he'll still likely be the number 1 defender in Fantasy again.
afShort: Full health and Saad taking the attention means he'll likely be the number 1 defender again

afComment: Miller's progression in the last three seasons is pretty remarkable. Played as a defensive mid in 2020, to an offensive mid in 2021 to then the mid who got tagged in 2022. That explains the 12 point drop from his league leading 122 points per game in 2021 to 110 in 2022. There is no harder working midfielder in the comp, so he managed to still put up some decent scores when tagged, thanks to his 6 tackles per game. The hope is that Anderson and Rowell take the next step in 2023 which might see Miller avoid the tag, however I still believe he'll be locked down at times. Priced at 110, he should still have this covered, which will lock him into a top 8 mid for the 3rd year in a row. He just might not be able reach the heights of 2021.
afShort: Gets more attention these days, but lock to be a top 8 mid for the third year in a row as the hardest working mid in the comp

afComment: We know Dunkley can score as well as any player in Fantasy. He averaged 118 in the last five games of 2018, 127 in the last half of 2019 and 116 in the first half of 2021. However, he's just never put together a full season, largely due to Bevo taking him out of the midfield. He managed to match his career high of 110 in 2022 from just 51% CBAs, which is the clearly the lowest of any player with a 110 average. Two things have gone in Dunkley's favour for 2023. First, he played enough forward to be gifted forward status in Fantasy. The second is he's been traded to the Lions, where it's expected he'll take up a full-time midfield role. So while he comes into the season as the most expensive forward available, he certainly has some upside on his price and will very likely be the number 1 forward for the season.
afShort: Forward status + Brisbane trade makes him clearly the number 1 forward as he can score as well as any in Fantasy

afComment: Merrett's 107 average in 2022 made it 6 107+ seasons in just nine years in the comp, making him one of the best Fantasy players of the past decade. However, he didn't look like making that milestone midway through the season when he was averaging just 99 and took a while to get into gear from his early syndesmosis return. He had a role change where he started a lot of centre bounces at half forward and worked up to the ball. This saw his CBAs drop from 80% in 2021 to 61% at the bye in 2022. Not sure whether it was a planned switch or forced given Parish went down injured, but Merrett returned to Essendon's prime centre bounce mid post byes, bumping his CBAs up to 72%. He's always been subject and vulnerable to a tag, but when playing inside he's an automatic 110+. This means he's slightly underpriced heading into 2023 and assuming Brad Scott keeps him as an inside mid, he's a starting M1 option.
afShort: 113 post bye when his CBAs returned to normal

afComment: Neale came into 2022 as an underpriced premium following a 2021 season where nothing went right (calf, back and ankle injuries). It was an easy selection and looked like a great one, when he averaged 116 in the first half of the season and showed 2020 was no fluke. The issue with Neale is that he is clearly Brisbane's most damaging midfielder and teams quickly learnt that if they shut down Neale, they would shut down the Lions. This saw him average a very mediocre 95 for the second half of the season. This is the concern with Neale and while he has the ability to average 120 and be the best Fantasy mid in the comp, he'll come with the tag risk every week. The recruitment of Josh Dunkley should improve the Lions' midfield depth and we might see Neale run free more in 2023, however I doubt it will happen enough for him to return to his 2020 heights.
afShort: The 'shut down Neale, beat Brisbane' makes it hard for him to average 110+

afComment: Crouch's 2022 numbers were a surprise. He finished the season as a top eight midfielder yet I doubt anyone had him in their 'rolling 22'. He was a point-per-minute stud at his time in Adelaide, going at 142 and 137 points per 100% game time in 2017 and 2019. For context, Andy Brayshaw went at 141 last year, Oliver 131, Mills 130 and Miller 127. However, he struggled for a constant inside role at the Saints given their midfield mix are all very similar and one paced, which saw Crouch often pushed out and spend less than ideal CBA for a Fantasy midfielder (62% in 2022). However, this didn't matter and he managed to return to be a Fantasy gun in the limited role. I like my Fantasy mids to have high TOG and CBAs, which rules Crouch out if he remains at 62%. It will be interesting to see what changes Ross Lyon will make, so the St Kilda CBAs will be worth monitoring in the preseason.
afShort: A surprising top 10 mid in 2022, hard to see that repeating if his CBAs remain at 62%

afComment: After 9 rounds in 2022, Bailey Smith was the best player in Fantasy. He was playing an unprecedented time on ground while getting decent CBAs in a stacked Bulldog midfield and used his elite run to average 118. His season then derailed after being suspended for headbutting Zach Tuohy and then a club-imposed suspension saw him miss 5 of the next 6 weeks. He never hit the early season heights when he returned, averaging 93 post bye. I'm happy to give him a pass given everything that was going on and take his first half of the season as a more realistic measure of his Fantasy prospects. Dunkley leaving could open up more inside opportunities for Smith and if he can get those CBAs up to 70%, alongside his TOG of 90%, then he's a real shot at being a top 8 midfielder this season. Keep an eye on his role in the preseason.
afShort: I'm more of a believer in his first half of the season than the second, and that TOG and CBA combo could land him as a top 8 mid

afComment: Macrae has been the most prolific Fantasy scorer of the last five years, however you wouldn't think that after watching him in 2022. When he's up and about and in the right role, there are few better. He averaged 130 in the second half of 2019 when he moved off the wing to pure inside mid. 123 in the first half of 2021 when his CBAs were at 80%. However, when he doesn't get the role he wants, he looks a shadow of himself. Unfortunately, it was this way for the majority of 2022. The Dogs' midfield is stacked and Macrae saw a 5 year low 64% CBAs, which explains his 3rd lowest average in 10 seasons in the league. At 28, typically the peak age for Fantasy, he should be producing career high numbers. Dunkley leaving opens up an obvious spot in the midfield. However, the Dogs' preferred midfield mix has been Libba, Bont and Smith, so Macrae's not certain to pick up the extra inside minutes. He's a big preseason watch and if he gets his CBAs back to the mid-70s, he could be the perfect discount uber premium we are hunting for as our M1/M2. However, if he takes Hunter's spot on a wing, we can no longer count him as a safe 110 midfielder.
afShort: Coming off his 3rd lowest average in 10 seasons with low CBAs, if he gets Dunkley's extra mid time he could be the ideal discounted uber premium

afComment: After bursting onto the scene 4 years ago, averaging 92, 97 and 109, Walsh finally had his first underwhelming season, averaging 103. There were a few factors for the regression. He returned early from a preseason syndesmosis injury where he was initially meant to miss the first 4 games and, like we saw with Zach Merrett, took a while to look back to his best. He also lost inside minutes following the recruitment of George Hewett and Adam Cerra, down from 67% CBAs in 2021 to 55% in 2022. A full preseason should fix the first issue, however Carlton still have a stacked midfield and Walsh is more suited to the wing than Cripps, Hewett and Matt Kennedy. There's enough proof over the past 5 years that to be an elite Fantasy midfielder, the CBAs need to be above 65%, so Walsh's role in the preseason will be a big watch for me. If he looks like their first-choice on-baller with 70% CBAs, he's a shot to break through the 110 barrier and become a top 8 mid. If he stays on the wing, I don't think he'll get the tackle opportunities to get the big scores needed from your gun mids (only 1 game over 120 in 2022, 0 over 130). He's now had offseason surgery and will miss the start of the season, ruling him out of calculations.
afShort: Preseason syndesmosis and extra mids saw him regress for the first time in 2022, will need to bump his CBAs to 70%+ to get more 120s and push the top 8

afComment: Gawn has been on a steady Fantasy decline since averaging 124 in 2020, dropping 13 points in 2021 and a further 8 points in 2022. It's been a mixture of a few things. He's still been the number 1 ruck in Fantasy during this time, so it has a lot to do with the ruck role with the reduced stoppages and ruck influence since the introduction of the stand rule. He's also given up CBAs to up-and-coming ruck, Luke Jackson, from 93% in 2020 to just 66% in 2022. The good news is Jackson is gone. The bad news is Melbourne now have the fellow best Fantasy ruck of the last decade, Brodie Grundy. This makes Gawn (and Grundy's) Fantasy prospects incredibly difficult to predict. Regardless, it's hard to see him bumping his CBAs up much from the 66% and despite being priced as cheap as he's been in 5 seasons, I'd need to see a few rounds of the Gawn/Grundy combination before being sure he's going to be the number 1 ruck in Fantasy again.
afShort: Need to see what his role is with Grundy before being sure he's going to be the number 1 ruck in Fantasy again

afComment: We don't often come across a 8th year breakout, but Jack Sinclair did just that in 2022. He moved to the half back role in 2021 and caught the eye with a 112 in the preseason. However, he managed just 79 for the season and it appeared the role change wasn't going to bring him Fantasy relevance. However, he took greater rebounding responsibilities in 2022 and increased his average by a massive 24 points to 103, making him the second-best defender in Fantasy and earning All Australian honours. He scoring appears sustainable, with a nice blend of intercept possessions, kick-ins (64% in the last 5) and general play. The only times he looked vulnerable were when the tag came, which happened a bit in the second half of the season, reducing his average to 93 in the last 5 games. There was a clear direction and desire to get the ball in his hands and this is a risk given there has been a change of coach. However from what I saw last year I find it hard to see him not scoring enough to be a top 6 defender again, regardless of the role Ross Lyon gives him.
afShort: An 8th season breakout and despite the risk of a new coach, it's hard to see him not being a top 3 defender again

afComment: I had been waiting to see what McCluggage would produce Fantasy wise once moved inside from his customary wing role, given he played inside when he was in juniors and averaged more points than Tim Taranto and Andrew McGrath. We saw that in 2022 with a career high 55% CBAs, however it didn't reflect in his scoring, averaging just 1 point more than when he was 24% in 2021. I've got a rule that I want my Fantasy midfielders to take the bulk of the CBAs, and McCluggage doesn't fit that bill, even with the increase of CBAs. If anything, it's likely he'll reduce again and move back to a wing following the recruitment of Josh Dunkley and the Lions' want to give Zac Bailey and Cam Rayner more of a run in there. At age 25, he should be reaching his peak and there's still natural improvement in him, however, it's hard to see McCluggage improving to the 110 mark which you'd need him to do to be a worthwhile pick at his price in Fantasy.
afShort: Increased CBAs didn't spell more points and if anything, the CBAs will reduce again with Dunkley arriving

afComment: Petracca crashed back to earth after a dominant 2021, which saw him finish as a top 8 midfielder. He had excuses, none greater than his 10-possession game in Round 11 where he scored just 40 points after having the flu all week. He was said to have carried a sore knee for the majority of the season and was tagged in a few matches. While there is upside if he can have a healthy season, the tag threat will always be there and it's the reason I typically favour the blue-collar midfielders (those less flashy who avoid the tag) over the genuine real-life stars in my Fantasy midfield. The reduced CBAs as the season went on also isn't good news for his prospects, however he might be a DPP watch if this continues in 2023. As a pure mid though, he's not on my radar.
afShort: Had excuses last season which explained the drop but he'll always get the extra attention which makes it hard to see him being a top 8 again

afComment: Cripps' 2022 season is exactly what we're trying to look for in our starting squad and what you need to contend. Came in priced at 82 after battling back and groin issues in 2021 and well down from his career high 109 in 2018. He looked back to his best in the preseason with a 141 in the AAMI and delivered for owners, averaging 102 for the season and 105 excluding his injured game. He displayed an outside game and spread that we hadn't seen before and looked a 110-guy for stretches of the season. However, he's now priced at 102 and unless he does average 110, he's not worth selecting in your starting squad this time around.
afShort: Averaged 105 excluding his injured game which still wouldn't make him a top 8 mid, despite his stretches of going 110

afComment: After a disappointing 2021 when he spent far too much time forward (50%) and sharing the ruck role with Stef Martin, English broke out in 2022 and returned to his trajectory of the great Fantasy rucks in the game. In his 4th season, English averaged 91. At the same stage of their careers, Gawn (92) and Grundy (101) were around a similar mark. In their 7th season, Gawn averaged 111 and Grundy 122. Heading into his 7th season and with Stef Martin retired, everything is set for English to improve again. The fact we don't know how Gawn and Grundy will work together means he's the safest pick to be the number 1 ruck in Fantasy this season. And if he can boost his average up to the 110 mark, which he showed he could do early in 2022, then he'll prove a great starting R1 option.
afShort: An early choice for the number 1 ruck with Stef gone and Gawn playing with Grundy

afComment: After romping home in 2021 averaging 111 in the second half of the season from 64% CBAs (from 33% in the first half), I had Kelly pegged to potentially be the ideal starting squad premium mid in 2022, that being someone priced around the 100 mark who can score in line with the most expensive players. The risk that was flagged was how deep the Giants were in their midfield, with Hopper, Ward, Taranto, Kelly, Green and Coniglio all demanding time. He was a victim of this and he saw his CBAs reduce to 46% for the season and 35% post bye (c'mon Leon). However, I haven't given up hope and maybe we were just a year early. Leon is now gone so hopefully we'll see more consistency in the Giants' midfield rotation and with Hopper and Taranto also gone, there are less mouths to feed. Their starting midfield should be Green, Kelly and Coniglio and if this is the case in the preseason and we see Kelly hit 65%+ CBAs (something that hasn't happened since CBAs have been public) then I'd be keen on starting with him.
afShort: No Leon, Hopper or Taranto which gives hope of seeing Kelly hit 65%+ CBAs and the 110 average we know he can produce in the right role

afComment: Dawson arrived at Adelaide having shown glimpses of being a Fantasy stud, including averaging 116 in the NEAFL and 97 in the second half of 2021, including a 158 late in the year. However, he took his game to another level at the Crows, averaging 101 for the season and being a clear top 3 defender. He was equally impressive in real life, using his damaging kicking skills, versatility and running power to great effect. He was so impactful that he regularly received some attention from opposition forwards. This is the only risk with Dawson heading into 2023, however his versatility meant he was thrown around a bit when tagged and there was no better effort than his 10 tackle effort in Round 17 when tagged by Maginness. It's my only hesitation starting with him as there's a chance he comes in cheaper after a tag-affected game, but it's hard to see him not being a top 3 defender again and a safe starting pick.
afShort: Watch for more attention following a brilliant 2022, but hard to see him not being a top 3 defender again

afComment: For years, the Bont - like other star players of the comp such as Fyfe and Dusty - was far better in real life than he was in Fantasy. However, this all changed midway through 2020 when he went on a rampage to average 124 points in the second half of the season. He spent the majority of his time playing as an inside midfielder rather than splitting his time forward as he did earlier in his career. However, the Dogs are stacked in their midfield has meant he hasn't replicated that 2020 role nor form. With the Dogs' stacked midfield, Bruce out and an adductor concern, Bont saw more forward time again in 2022, enough to see him gain forward status during the season and his CBAs dropped to 58%. However, Dunkley leaving and Bruce back could open up more inside minutes for Bont in 2023. He's not cheap enough for me to take the punt as a starting squad selection, but he'll stay on the radar in case he happens to hit the 81% CBA figure he was at when he averaged 124 in the second half of 2020.
afShort: A stacked midfield and sore adductor kept him to 58% CBAs in 2022 but with no Dunkley he could get back to the 80% he averaged in the back half of 2022 to be a gun Fantasy mid

afComment: After a breakout 2021, Parish had a disappointing 2022 which saw him play just 16 games due to calf issues. He started the season strong, averaging 108 to go with the 113 he averaged in the first half of 2021, but averaged just 82 post bye as the calf issues kicked in. I've seen enough from those positive stretches to be confident Parish has the attributes to be a top-line Fantasy asset when fully fit and in the right role. There is always a risk of the magnets changing when a new coach comes in and we've seen in 2020 (82 from 48% CBAs) and the second half of 2022 (82 from 68% CBAs) that Parish needs to have 80% CBAs to score. If it's looking that way in the preseason, then he's a valid starting option and I doubt his ownership will be much more than 5%.
afShort: Hampered by calf issues in 2022, if Scott keeps him at 80% CBAs he could be a unique top 8 mid

afComment: I don't think there's been a more up and down performer in Fantasy than Angus Brayshaw. He averaged 116 in the second half of 2018 to be one of the best scorers in the comp. Then after scoring 145 in the preseason, he was pushed out of the midfield for the likes of Viney, Oliver and Petracca. He reduced his average by 33 across 3 seasons and found himself averaging 69 in a defensive wing role for their premiership side. Despite his low possession game, the importance of his role was highlighted by many Dees' players and fans and I was certain that this non-relevant Fantasy role would continue. However, he found himself playing in defence in 2022 following Salem's injury and excelled, averaging around the 100 mark in that role. He was then thrusted into the midfield towards the end of the season, with 53% CBAs in the last 5 and a 110 average. He comes into 2023 with defender status, which immediately makes him relevant even if he returns to the half-back role. But if he can get some CBAs in the preseason, he has 10 points upside on his price. All about role, so keep on the preseason watch.
afShort: 110 in last 5 when back in the midfield but even his 100 he averaged prior to that makes him a top 6 defender, preseason role watch

afComment: His 99 average doesn't reflect it, but Luke Parker had a very good season in 2022. He was given forward status during the season which made him even more relevant and he proved to be a top 6 forward in the run home. However, he's now just a mid-only, and while he's still going as hard as ever at age 30, he's not likely to boost his score by the 10 points required to be a good starting pick at that price. Let's hope he gets forward status again during the year.
afShort: Now just mid-only and not likely to boost his score by the 10 points required to be a good starting pick at that price

afComment: Cogs returned to the midfield and form in 2022, following a disappointing 2021 where he averaged 61 from just 36% CBAs. He's still yet to recapture his absolute best form, which saw him average 111 twice (in 2018 and 2019 if you exclude his injured score of 0). The drop in form could be put down to a number of things: added pressure from captaincy, less stoppages where he used to rely on high tackle numbers and the depth of the Giants' midfield group, forcing Cogs to spend a lot more time forward. With the departure of Hopper and Taranto, the 3rd reason will hopefully be fixed and we'll see Cogs return to a 70%+ CBA midfielder. The concern is the new coach as we don't know what role Cogs will play and how fantasy-friendly the game-style will be. If Tigers are anything to go by, we might see less high-possession football from the Giants in 2023. The fact Cogs has forward status this season means he's always going to be on the radar, but I'd want confirmation of CBAs and game style before taking the punt on him, so he's not a starting option for me.
afShort: Forward status is handy, as is Hopper and Taranto leaving, I just need to see confirmation of role and new game-style under Kingsley

afComment: A key opportunity for a breakout is when a player moves clubs and is both reinvigorated and plays in a new role. Hewett did just that in 2022 where he relished his role as Carlton's pure inside mid, seeing 73% CBAs compared to the 28% and 33% he was at Sydney the prior 2 seasons. He had a career best 98, well up from his prior PB of 76. Now he's a mid-only, he's not an attractive prospect. Best case he might match his 2022 output and at his price, you'd need him to beat it again by 10 points which I can't see him doing.
afShort: Hard to see him improving again, as good as his 2022 season was

afComment: Drafted as a pure outside wingman, Anderson was introduced to the CBAs at the end of 2020 and increased ever since, attending a career high 72% of Gold Coast's stoppages across the season. This saw him average 98 and be amongst the large group of midfielders with that output. Players with an outside background who move inside prove great Fantasy prototypes, as they know how to spread and win the ball in space and learn to tackle and add extra disposals to boost their score. I think he has the ability to break away from the pack and become a 110-averaging midfielder. If that’s this year, then he would be a great starting selection priced less than 100. The 104 he averaged post-bye last year should be the least he can produce, so he’s certainly a viable starting option.
afShort: Has the attributes to average 110 with the inside/outside blend and could prove a great starting pick

afComment: A philosophy I live by is more CBAs = more Fantasy points. This certainly wasn't the case with Short who was moved into the Tigers' midfield in Round 7. Up until then, he was averaging 107. After Round 7, he averaged 93. The designated kicker lost a lot of the easy +6s he relied on when playing half back plus the extra kick-ins. The Richmond style forward of centre is to move it forward at all costs, which didn't suit Short's game. He's now only available as a midfielder and there's no chance of him producing scores to be a relevant midfield option. With the additions of Hopper and Taranto, I'd be very surprised if he doesn't return to half back and be available as a defender at one point. We know he can produce top 6 defender numbers. But until then, he doesn't make a good starting midfield pick.
afShort: More CBAs doesn't = more Fantasy points for Short and unless he moves back to defence, he's unlikely to feature in Fantasy teams this year

afComment: Wines had a disappointing 2022, dropping 14 points per game from his Brownlow winning 2021. Looking at his history, it may appear that 2021 was an outlier and that Wines is just a 90s guy in Fantasy. This was the case early in his career as he was so 'inside' he lacked the easy marks and possessions to be a 110 Fantasy mid. However, this changed in the backend of 2020 when he appeared to spread more for marks and averaged 112 in his last five games. Player splits are one of my favourite metrics for projecting future scoring and Wines' 2021 season showcased this perfectly, averaging 112 for the full season. That's enough of a sample size to know he can be a 110 player. He did have excuses in 2022, none more so that the game he got subbed out prior to half time on 36. With Butters and Rozee improving and seeing more mid-time, Wines' 110 days may be over, but the 106 he averaged in his last 5 games is a better representation of what he's capable of.
afShort: No longer the main man with Butters and Rozee improving but he 106 he averaged in his last 5 games is a better representation than his 2022 average

afComment: After a breakout 2021, Keays looks like he was going to continue being a premium Fantasy midfielder when he averaged 106 in the first half of the season from 80% CBAs (the same amount as 2021 when he averaged 108). He ticked a lot of boxes - high CBAs, avoided the tag and did all the hard things. However, there was a clear role change midseason and Keays spent a lot of time forward, often as a negating forward, reducing his CBAs to 55% and 34% in the last 5 games. His scoring suffered, reducing his average to 87 and 73 respectively. It coincided with Sam Berry's increase in the middle, up from 52% in the first half to 76% in the second and 83% in the last 5. Berry has been earmarked as the Crows' future star midfielder and I expect Berry to keep his prominent onball position. This means Keays' role is uncertain and while we know he can produce 108+ in the right role, I'm not confident enough in that role happening.
afShort: Sam Berry took his inside role post bye and reduced Keays to 34% CBAs and 73 points in the last 5 games. That might continue in 2023.

afComment: Amon finds himself at the Hawks after back-to-back 97+ seasons playing on a wing at Port. His shows a great ceiling, surpassing 120 8 times over the last 2 seasons. However, like all wingmen, he lacked the consistency and went sub 90 18 times. I need my Fantasy mids to get 65%+ CBAs to help with that consistency and unless Amon plays as that for his new team (which I doubt), he won't be on my radar.
afShort: 8 x over 120 and 18 x under 90 is the inconsistency that comes with wingmen and you want your mids to see more than 65% CBAs

afComment: Treloar has been a Fantasy stud over the journey and has one of the best career Fantasy averages in the league, but he's been restricted by soft tissue injuries for a few years now. He only missed the one game in 2022, after missing 19 the two years prior, but was subbed out of another one and never looked his explosive best. He used to have the perfect balance on inside and outside where he would win the ball in the contest and spread hard outside for easy marks to be that 110 player we crave. I feel like that is now behind him and he's more of a 100-guy. What may impact that is role, as Treloar was used through the midfield, forward and in defence in 2022, even taking kick-ins at the end of the season. If he's available anywhere outside the midfield then he'll be in consideration given he's been one of the best ball winners in the comp for a few years now, but as a mid-only, I think there are safer options with greater upside.
afShort: Soft tissue concerns for over 4 years now and seems to be more off a 95/100-guy than the 110 stud of the past

afComment: Viney is a pure inside midfielder and a gun in real life, but doesn't get enough easy ball which explains why his career best Fantasy season is 101. That's not enough to consider.
afShort: Too inside to ever be much more than a 100-guy

afComment: If it weren't for Docherty, Sicily's 2022 would be the story of the year. After missing 2021 with an ACL, Sicily had a career best season, averaging 96 points per game. He proved a bargain buy given his 30% discount for missing the full season and a good learning experience to know that with modern sports science, players can return at an elite level following an ACL (we saw the same with Witts last season). The Hawks are in total development mode which means a few things for Sicily's 2023 prospects. They aren't going to win many games, meaning the ball will be in the backline a lot, with plenty of kick-in opportunities. Sicily averaged 98 in losses compared to 95 in wins, so the team performance shouldn't impact his output. However, with Sam Mitchell's eye on the future, they could do some experimenting, which we saw towards the end of 2022 when Sicily went from the preferred kick-out player (31%) to at times actively not looking to take the kick-ins, giving them up to the youngsters in Day and Bramble. He was even thrown into some centre bounces. Those things combined makes me think we'll see similar output again and he'll be knocking on the door of the top 6 defenders. In terms of a starting pick, I'd rather someone with more upside on their starting price.
afShort: Averaged 98 in losses which is positive given Hawks will likely lose a lot and unless Mitchell goes full experimental mode, he should be around that mark again

afComment: Of current players, Tom Mitchell has been the best Fantasy player of all. He was in his own league in 2017 and 2018, averaging 127 and 128 before missing the entire 2019 season with a broken leg. Since then, he's yet to have a decent run of it. He started slow in 2020 (100) as you would expect coming off a broken leg and then averaged 116 in the second half. His 2021 season was also interrupted with preseason shoulder surgery, seeing him again start the year slow (104) but finish with 126 in the second half. 2022 he was a lock in many sides during the preseason, however missed the AAMI game with groin soreness which is never a good sign. That, combined with Sam Mitchell's desire to fast-track Hawthorn's rebuild and experiment with younger players through the midfield (53% CBAs compared to 70%+ in prior years) saw Tom Mitchell have his lowest Fantasy average since his second season in the comp. He now finds himself at Collingwood which is a massive win for his prospects, given they are contending and will certainly use Mitchell as a fulltime onballer. The only concern is the style Collingwood play (fast, low possession, move it forward) isn't conducive to high Fantasy scoring. However, Mitchell can score in any environment if healthy and in the right role, so if he has an uninterrupted preseason, he becomes one of the early locks in Fantasy.
afShort: The move to a contender should see Mitchell return to being an elite Fantasy player, making him an early lock at that price

afComment: Guthrie turned himself from a role player to low-key gun Fantasy scorer over the past few years, averaging 105 across 2020 and 2021. He fit the mould of the best Fantasy mids in the comp - tough, uncompromising and not a household 'star' name, meaning he never got any attention. However, where he doesn't pass the test is age (30) and team (Geelong). Geelong notoriously rest their players, particularly those over 30, and we saw that more than ever in 2022 with Guthrie playing a crazy low 69% game time. He rates 4th amongst midfielders on a points-per-minute basis, however I can't trust that the minutes and matches are always going to be there to do it.
afShort: Ranked 4th amongst midfielders on a points-per-minute basis in just 69% game-time, however I can't trust that the minutes and matches are always going to be there knowing what Geelong do with their 30-year-olds

afComment: It's hard to know what to make of Simpkin in Fantasy. After a breakout season in 2020 which saw him increase his average by 22 points per game, he improved again in 2021 by another 7 points to 95 points per game and 105 post bye. However, he stagnated in 2022, not increasing his average despite no Cunnington and increased CBAs minutes. A lot of that might have been due to how bad the Kangaroos were as scores are generally lower for losing teams and the Roos are that more often than not. The rise of LDU also took some ball off him, however long term this should be a good thing for Simpkins' prospects given LDU is now the Roos' best player and commands the oppositions' attention. I've seen enough from Simpkin to know that he can average 105-110 in a season, which would make him a great selection at that price if it were to be this year. He's just harder to trust than others around this mark (8 games sub-90, 3 sub-70).
afShort: Was trending to be an elite Fantasy midfielder of the comp before stagnating last year with the Roos' struggles

afComment: Insert Josh Dunkley comment here. New club + forward status = tick. In six seasons, Tim Taranto has established himself as a Fantasy stud with a career average over 100 since his debut season. He's got all the attributes you want - tackles hard and often, yet not afraid to pick up an easy plus six around the ground. The only thing holding him back was the competition for midfield minutes at the Giants, which saw him bottom out at 44% CBAs last season. In 2021, Taranto spent more than 50% of the game in the middle for 13 matches and averaged 115. For the 10 with less than 50%, he averaged 88. In 2022 he had over 50% in just 8 games (never hit 60%), yet scored over 120 twice in that time. He now finds himself at Richmond, who despite having a great team, aren't that deep in the midfield. Taranto should step into their preferred on-ball rotation and see his CBAs at 60%+ each week. If his preseason time trial is anything to go by, he's in for a big season and a 110 average is on the cards. Hard to split him and Dunkley on scoring ability, but Taranto's cheaper price gives him the nod.
afShort: New club + forward status = 110+ on the cards

afComment: Another who needed a new club to bring career best form and he proved a gem for Fantasy coaches who started with him in the forward line priced at 46. He averaged 94 from just 69% game time, so the upside would be an increased TOG from added fitness and Mundy retiring. However, he's now lost his forward status and nice price tag, and while he should continue in the inside role at Freo, I doubt he's going to improve on his price nor score enough to be a relevant starting selection this season in Fantasy.
afShort: Lost his forward status and nice price tag from last season meaning the 2022 hero shouldn't be in calculations this year

afComment: Witherden has had a great Fantasy game about him since day one, averaging 89 in his first season in the comp and appeared he was going to be a Fantasy jet for years to come. However, he fell out of favour at the Lions and found himself at West Coast where he has also struggled for regular opportunity. His 2022 summed up his career to date, scoring great when he had the opportunity (5 scores over 100 from 12 games), but in and out of the side, playing just 12 games for a team who was easy to get games for. It’s not a good sign and even if he scores well in the preseason, it’s hard to trust his job security for a player priced in the 90s.
afShort: Just 12 games for the struggling Eagles in 2022 so despite his scoring ability, it’s hard to trust his job security

afComment: If anyone has defied the 'players don't improve after 30' rule of mine, it's Trav Boak. 3 of his best 4 years in his career have come since turning 30. He prepares as well and works as hard as anyone, so it doesn't come as a complete surprise. However, his scoring in the last 2 seasons suggest he's starting to slow down. He dropped to 95 last year and slowed as the year went on. His CBAs hit a low of 54% in this last 5 games, well down from his role of the past 5 years. With Butters and Rozee only increasing their midfield usage, I imagine Boak will reduce again. Could be relevant if given forward status during the season, but as a starting squad selection he's not a good option.
afShort: Likely to reduce again after a low of 54% CBAs in final 5 games to average 82 as Butters and Rozee took over

afComment: Stewart had been on the verge of the top six defenders for multiple seasons and looked like finally breaking through in 2022. He averaged 114 between rounds 4-11, including a 157 and 169, then it all went wrong. He was concussed in Round 12 just after quarter time when on 44 and on track to get 150 again. He returned with a low score, not uncommon for players returning from concussion and then bounced back with a 106, however got himself suspended for 4 weeks in doing so. He never returned the same player, averaging 79 in the last 5 and 71 in the finals, often receiving a heavy tag from opposition forwards. When Cats were at their best, which they were over that time, they played on and moved the ball quick. This doesn't play into the hands of Stewart, who when on a tear, does it through multiple marks at will. It's hard to predict Stewarts' prospects for 2023. On one hand, there's the fact he gets a lot of opposition attention (not ideal for a Fantasy defender), he's now 30 in a team who notoriously rests their older players and that the Cats' style has evolved and they don't take as many marks. However, on the other hand you can get a player capable of a 114 average over a long stretch in your defence priced at 91. I'm leaning to the second camp and believe he's a very decent starting option at that price.
afShort: Rollercoaster 2022 saw him average 114 for 8 weeks, concussed, suspended then tagged to 79 in last 5 makes it hard to read but priced at 91, he's still one of the premium defenders in Fantasy

afComment: Crisp became a full-time midfielder under McRae's first season, attending 58% CBAs and rotating forward rather than the half back role he had been accustomed to for the majority of his career. He was tested as a midfielder in the years prior and unconventionally scored lower when his CBAs were higher. This was the case in 2022, where Crisp went from a reliable 100 scoring defender to averaging 81 post bye and 78 in his last 5 games. While being incredibly frustrating for his Fantasy owners, he was still apparently doing his role for the team, winning Collingwood’s best and fairest. He had a strong finals series, averaging 102 which was in line with what he scored in the first half of the season. If have a feeling he was carrying something in the second half of the season which explained the low scoring and low 100s is about where he should be in that midfield role. As a midfield only option though, that's nowhere near enough to consider as a starting option. He may come relevant if switched back to defence with Taylor Adams back and the arrival of Tom Mitchell, but given he won their B&F in the midfield role, it's hard to see that changing.
afShort: Incredibly frustrating for owners last year with 81 post-bye and while he should score closer to 100, the loss of defender status makes him not an option this time round, unless he picks up DPP during the season

afComment: Developed into a handy player with a nice Fantasy game. His season high of 122 was from 76% CBAs when Carlton were missing their first choice mids, but as a mid-only option, he's not going to get enough of those opportunities to be a successful Fantasy asset.
afShort: Developed into a handy player but not attractive as a mid-only option

afComment: Grundy has been on a steady decline - in real life and in Fantasy - since 2019 when he was the number 1 Fantasy player in the comp. He now finds himself in a very unlikely scenario, playing alongside the best ruckman in the AFL, Max Gawn, after being pushed out of Collingwood. He's going to have a point to prove, it's just hard to see him getting enough opportunity in the middle to put up a score worthy of starting him. So despite his 30 point discount to his career best season, I'd need to see how the Dees use Gawn and Grundy before having either in my side.
afShort: Despite his 30 point discount to his career best season, I'd need to see how the Dees use Gawn and Grundy before having either in my side

afComment: Hurn is playing as well as ever, averaging a career high 93 in his 17th season. However, he's never pushed his average high enough to challenge the top six defenders. Add that to the fact he's turning 36, he's not a great option.
afShort: Coming off a career high but can't pick a soon-to-be 36 year old

afComment: Moore had a terrific 2022, firstly playing in his customary small forward role, where he managed to average 88 despite playing as a pure forward, and then when he was introduced into the midfield rotation and averaged 101 post bye from 42% CBAs. He was brilliant there and showed enough to suggest that role will continue into 2023. The chances are only enhanced following the departures of midfield regulars Mitchell and O'Merea. Looking at his consistency numbers, in his games less than 90 (10 of 22), he averaged 5% CBAs and over 100 (8 of 22) was 33% - a clear sign that in the midfield role, he's a solid 100 player. With forward status, this is the type of player we're looking for in our starting sides, as long as those midfield minutes are there. His ownership will likely be low on name alone, but I like him as a discounted option with a chance to push the top 6.
afShort: The midfield move post bye netted 101 on 42% CBAs and is hopefully a sign of things to come which would put him in line to be a top 6 forward

afComment: O'Brien still hasn't reached the heights of 2020 that saw him emerge as one of the league's best ruckmen. He averaged 123 in his last 5 games of that season and caught the eye of Fantasy coaches. Since then, he's regressed, which is rare for a ruckman of his age, to a point where he was dropped during last season. He scored 171 in the SANFL, showing he still has it, and returned to the senior team to average 100 for the rest of the season, including 3 scores over 120. However, there's enough evidence since Nicks took over as coach the Crows don't rely on O'Brien as much and certainly don't use him around the ground as they once did. He'll likely be a mid-90s ruckman going forward so he'll be a handy Draft option, but there's not much value there in Classic.
afShort: He'll likely be a mid-90s ruckman going forward so he'll be a handy Draft option, but there's not much value there in Classic

afComment: LDU broke out in 2022 in both real life and Fantasy. The former number 4 pick increased his average from 82 in 2021 to 93 in 2022, including 106 post bye, highlighted by an elite clearance game on 82% CBAs. After seeing how good he was around stoppages, it makes you wonder what Noble was thinking giving him just 59% CBAs pre bye. He's been a slow build since debuting, increasing his average by 13, 17, 11 and 11 points per game. His post-bye form suggest he's in for another 10+ point increase and may begin to knock on the door of the top 8 mids. The only thing that I see holding him back is the potential for opposition attention as he's now become the Roos' number 1 mid, surpassing Simpkin who has had to deal with the tag the last few seasons. If he avoids the tag enough and continues his post bye form (106), he'll prove a great starting selection priced at 93.
afShort: If he avoids the tag enough and continues his post bye form (106), he'll prove a great starting selection priced at 93.

afComment: For the majority of his career, Mitch Duncan has been one of the few outside midfielders who are capable of scoring 110+ in Fantasy. He takes above average for marks (8.4 a game) and has a high kick to handball ratio of 2. Being a high mark player and playing at Geelong used to be a recipe for success, however they have changed their style so much in the last 12 months that there is less emphasis on a kick-mark game. Duncan finished the season playing in the backline and comes into 2023 with defender status, meaning he’ll be Fantasy relevant throughout. The risk with Duncan is that he's now over 30 and had his share of soft tissue injuries in the past. We know Geelong aren't afraid to rest players, even if named. So you'll have nervous moments with him in 2023. For that reason, I’d prefer to start with safer options in defence, but he’d be an upgrade target given his likely top 6 status.
afShort: Capable of being a top 6 defender, but over 30 in Geelong always comes with risk

afComment: After teasing as a midfielder in 2020, Houston has been a mainstay in Port's defence. He's shown a high ceiling for a number of seasons now, scoring over 120 5 times in 2022 including a 150. However, he's also shown inconsistency, going sub-90 10 times. High ceilings are nice, but we need consistency in Fantasy and over the full length of the season, I expect him to average around where he's been the past four years.
afShort: High ceiling but lacks the consistency needed to be a safe top 6 defender

afComment: Lyons' regression from a top 3 Fantasy mid in 2021 was one many saw coming. The Lions' midfield was criticised for be being a tad one paced, and they were forced to shake a few things up in 2022, with young guns McCluggage, Bailey and Rayner getting more midfield minutes. This saw Lyons reduce his CBAs from 80% in 2021 to 65% in 2022, including 53% in the last 5 games. It has come out that Lyons was dealing with OP in 2022 which may be a reason for the role and scoring drop off, however I feel like it was more to do with the need to inject youth and speed and the acquisition of Dunkley doesn't bode well for Lyons, who might find it hard remaining in the team, let alone the midfield rotation.
afShort: The acquisition of Dunkley doesn't bode well for Lyons, who might find it hard remaining in the team, let alone the midfield rotation.

afComment: After averaging 99 in just his third season, the recruitment of Paddy Ryder to share ruck duties put a stop to Marshall's Fantasy trajectory. He's hovered in the 90s since then, however showed his potential when given the solo duties. Marshall averaged 107 in the 4 games Ryder missed to finish 2021 and 114 when attending 60% or more CBAs in 2022. With Ryder retiring and Ratten, the coach who preferred to use Marshall as a backup ruck, no longer there, we can expect Marshall to fulfill his Fantasy and real life potential in 2023. With question marks over Gawn and Grundy playing together, Marshall will be a very popular starting ruck option - and for good reason. Update: Jack Hayes preseason injury might hurt as they are now missing Marshall and King for the early rounds, meaning Marshall could be needed up forward.
afShort: Averaged 114 when attending 60% or more CBAs and with Ryder and Ratten gone, expect Marshall to fulfill his Fantasy and real life potential

afComment: Lloyd was the premier defender in Fantasy in 2019 and 2020. His scoring method was sustainable - the Swans' primary distributor, played on from every kick-in and consistently generating easy uncontested marks. This hasn't been the case in the past 2 seasons, dropping his average 17 points and then 7 points to 90 in 2022. The Swans had a clear change in game style, being more attacking from defence, meaning there were less easy plus six opportunities for Lloyd. He's also lost some kick-in duties to Nick Blakey after having a mortgage on them for years. He's still a consistent defender, it's just hard to see him ever reaching the 100+ heights of the past as the Swans continue to deploy their attacking game-style.
afShort: Hard to see him ever reaching the 100+ heights of the past as the Swans continue to deploy their attacking game-style.

afComment: Whitfield has let down many coaches, including myself, the past 2 seasons. After back-to-back 107s, he's put up 95 and then 91 and looked a shadow of the hard-running, ball hungry, Fantasy gun he was. Last year he was used on a wing and half forward, and rarely down back where he did most of his damage in the past. I think a change of coach could help reinvigorate him and get him back to his best, and I'm actually glad he's lost his defender status this year as it will save the tempation of starting with him. I'd pay up in Draft though as a move back to defence will see him return to a top 6 defender before the season is out.
afShort: Two down years in a row for the proven gun and if it weren't for his mid-only status, I'd be tempted to go back again

afComment: Cumming has backed up his impressive NEAFL numbers in 2019 and 2020 to become a handy defender for the Giants, both in real life and in Fantasy. A 91 average isn't enough to be a top 6 defender, but further improvement, which we've seen in every season he's been in the comp, could certainly push him there. Cumming's not on my radar as a starting selection, but he's worth a spot on the watchlist to see how the new coach and game style impacts his scoring.
afShort: Further improvement, which we've seen in every season he's been in the comp, could certainly push him towards the top 6 defenders

afComment: Witts had a terrific season made even more impressive given he was fresh off an ACL injury. Prior to 2020, he'd been a 90-100 guy from three of the past four seasons, so his output was certainly no fluke. He should improve a bit with a full preseason under his belt and I'd guess he'll score in line with how he finished 2022, which was 96 in the final 5 games. 96 wouldn't have him as a top 2 ruck and out of calculations for a starting position, however he'll be a serviceable ruckman for his Draft owners.
afShort: 96 in the final 5 games should be a nice indication of his output given he was returning from an ACL, making him a serviceable ruckmen but not a top 2 option

afComment: Seb Ross had somewhat of a resurgence in 2022, increasing his average by 10 points per game. He's still yet to ever recapture the form that saw him average 107 and make a significant impact in the 2018 Fantasy season, but his move back into the midfield with 61% CBAs certainly help, up from 30% in 2021. A change of coach may reinvigorate Ross, but I highly doubt he'll become a relevant Fantasy midfielder again.
afShort: Back in the midfield rotation in 2022 but still yet to recapture the form that saw him average 107 in 2018

afComment: Vlastuin had a career best Fantasy year in his 10th season. He's always been on the radar in Fantasy, given he's a former top 10 draft pick with thought of eventually moving to the midfield. However, he's become far too important of a defender to ever make the switch. With Houli retiring and Short moving into the midfield, Vlastuin became Richmond's primary distributor in defence, taking 36% of the kick-ins and averaging 90 points per game, up 14 on 2021. It could've been higher if not for an injury impacted 36, however injuries are something that have burdened Vlastuin for most of his career. He's still only 28 and will gain confidence from his career best year, so there's a chance he improves again in 2023. However, with the strengthening Tigers' midfield with Taranto and Hopper arriving, it's likely we'll see Short return to defence and take away some of Vlastuin’s usage. One to watch, but not in starting squad calculations for me.
afShort: Will have confidence coming off a career year but Short's likely return to defence and take away some of Vlastuin’s usage in 2023

afComment: Hall's Fantasy career will go down as one of the biggest rollercoaster of emotions. After showing patches of big scores in a midfield role at the Gold Coast, highlighted by his 105 in 2016, he turned into an attacking half-back at the Roos where he was the number 1 defender in Fantasy in 2021. However, his 2022 season began with a hamstring injury in the preseason and it didn't stop there. Hall had 2 games with less than 50% game-time (one with just 2 minutes) due to his ongoing hamstring and soft tissue injures. When not injured, he showed he still had it, with 3 scores over 120 in his 11 matches. However, he also (somehow) found himself out of the Roos' best 22 as they looked to play the youth. It's almost impossible to trust Hall in Fantasy in 2022 given his hamstring woes, the fact he's now 32 and that he may not be in Clarko's 22 (at least, not in that attacking half back role which Xav tells me Clarko won't tolerate), so we're going to have to resist the temptation of a player capable of being the D1 priced at 90.
afShort: 32 with hamstring woes means we're going to have to resist the temptation of a player capable of being the D1 priced at 90

afComment: Dale has been a revolution since his move to defence, clearly putting up his best two Fantasy seasons. He improved again in 2022, taking his average up 7 to 89. He'd need to improve by at least 7 points per game again to be a worthy selection in Fantasy and given his season splits were all around the 90-mark and more than half of his games were sub-90 scores, I doubt he'll suddenly become a high-90s defender.
afShort: Been reliable since his move to defence, however more than half of his games were sub-90 scores, so I doubt he'll suddenly become a high-90s / top 6 defender

afComment: Injuries have limited Prestia from fulfilling his Fantasy potential. After failing to play 10 games in the prior two seasons, Prestia played 19 in 2022, however in 3 of those he played less than 50% gametime due to early game injury. He's got the ability, however now on the other side of 30 and the fact Tigers have a deeper midfield, it's likely he will be managed a lot more in 2023 given his importance to their team structure. Add in the early game injury risk, he's certainly not someone I'm considering.
afShort: 3 games less than 50% game time after failing to reach 10 games in the two years prior makes the 30-year-old too much risk for me

afComment: Heeney has been the ultimate tease in AFL Fantasy and never as much as he was in 2022. After years of 'more midfield time' discussions in the preseason which never eventuated, it looked like it was finally going to happen after he had over 50% CBAs in the preseason practice match and Longmire backed it up with comments suggesting the move was real. However, he continued to play majority forward with small stints in the midfield - 18% in the first half of the season. They reduced as the year went on and his 4% CBAs post byes were not much more than he'd been getting in prior years. He still managed to score pretty well for almost a pure forward, averaging 89 points per game for the H&A season. This is why he's such a tantalizing prospect, if he can average 90 with 11% CBAs, imagine what he could do with 50%+! As a pure forward though, there's no value in his price as there was last year. So unless we see that 50% CBA number in the preseason and want to go down that road again, I'm not considering him as a strong starting option.
afShort: The ultimate tease has almost run out of 'more midfield time' chances, so unless we see 50%+ CBAs in the preseason, I won't be going down that road again

afComment: Now this kid can seriously play. After being introduced into the Swans' midfield rotation in 2021, Warner became a staple in 2022, attending 73% centre bounces in the second half of the year and 79% last 5. He's one of those players who are more damaging in real-life than in Fantasy, showcased by his sub-90 average despite polling 12 Brownlow votes from the midfield. Heading into his 4th season and 3rd full year, he'll no doubt improve again with fitness and natural progression. A lot of this improvement might be counted by some additional opposition attention, such was the damaging nature of his game. So I think he'll bump his average up into the mid-to-high 90s in 2023, but he needs to be over 100 to be a worthwhile selection at that price.
afShort: Heading into his 4th season, the future AFL star should improve again, but he'll no doubt receive extra attention which will make it tough to average the 100+ he needs to be a good selection

afComment: In a year where new club colours brought career best seasons (Hewett, Dawson etc), Cerra didn't get the memo. Arriving from Freo where he had four seasons of teasing us in Fantasy in sporatic scoring in various roles, he arrived at Carlton who at the time were crying out for midfield depth. This made me excited for the natural on-baller, who averaged 115 in NAB League, 10 more than now ex-teammate Andrew Brayshaw in the same team. However, while he did see career high CBA numbers (54%), he took a backseat to Cripps, Hewett and Walsh as the main three midfielders and averaged just 88 points. He was impacted by an early injury in one game and excluding that score of 5 he averaged 93. I think he can get that up to 100 in 2023, which could be lineball whether that is a worthwhile pick priced at 88. If he can get 105 then he's certainly worthwhile, but with his likely very low ownership, it's probably not worth the risk.
afShort: I expected more from 54% CBAs but 93 excluding lowest could bump to 100 in his second season at the Blues

afComment: After two seasons of regressing following his debut year, Rozee broke out in 2022. It wasn't all pretty though, but his progression and season splits certainly were. He averaged 44 in the first 4 rounds on 7% CBAs. He was then given consistent midfield opportunities and averaged 91 in his next 7 up until the bye from 56% CBAs. This role remained post bye, where he averaged 102 and 108 in his last 5. This is the sort of growth and splits we look for in Fantasy because we can get someone priced at their full season average (88) knowing they can average over 100 in the right role, plus any natural progression that we normally see when a player is just 4 seasons into their career. Rozee wasn't just a success in Fantasy, but starred in real life and went on to win Port's best and fairest award. That's enough for me to be confident in the midfield role remaining. And if anything, it could bump up to 70% with Boak phasing out. Midfield Rozee is a 100+ player which is enough to be a worthwhile pick priced at 88 and could be enough to be a top 6 forward for the season.
afShort: Averaged 98 following the midfield move and should only improve on that

afComment: Matt Crouch came into 2022 with a 30% discount after missing the entire 2021 season with groin issues. Some people have a hard rule of not picking players off an injury and they were proved right on this occasion. However, I like to look for a discount wherever I can and those same people would've missed out on someone like Sicily. There is no right answer, but one thing we have learnt is that it's very hard to trust someone with soft tissue injuries. Crouch, who was once a dominant midfielder of the comp both in real life and in Fantasy, had his lowest season average since his second season of 88. He also struggled for regular games, playing just 11 for the season and 1 of the last 9. He clearly fell out of favour to the younger Sam Berry and Schoenberg. When he did play, he was restricted to just 67% TOG. I think the Crows have moved on from Crouch and it's likely he'll struggle for regular gametime again in 2023, so I'm ignoring that discount to his career best season and avoiding him in Fantasy.
afShort: Former stud played 1 of the last 9 games and 67% TOG when playing, suggests the Crows have moved passed him

afComment: Serong has been a tease in Fantasy ever since he averaged 83 in his debut year. From there he hasn't really broken out, averaging 82 and 88 in his next two H&A seasons. The former top 10 pick ticks a lot of boxes and plays in a style that should see him be a Fantasy stud in the future. It's no question midfielders rely on CBAs for scoring and while Serong has been a regular in there since his debut season (67%, 71% and 66%), he's yet to hit the 80%+ mark we see with the top Fantasy mids. I didn't expect him to reduce his CBAs in 2022 following the departure of Cerra, however the emergence of Brodie (68%) and the evergreen Mundy (65%) weren't in my calculations. Mundy has retired which should open up a spot but it's likely that O'Meara will soak that up. It's becoming pretty crowded now at Freo, but I still think Serong will step up to 75%+ in his 4th season. That should give him enough opportunity to crack the 100 mark for the first time, which would make him a decent selection at this price. However, he's let us down enough in the past for me to pass on him.
afShort: Waiting for the breakout since his debut and that could come this season if he can get his CBAs up to 75%

afComment: After dealing with hamstring and ankle injuries in his first two seasons, the former number 7 pick made himself at home in Freo's defence in 2023, playing 22 matches at an average of 90 points. His lethal kick was known, but it's his intercept work which has been just as impressive. He has all the makings of a star in real life, the question is can he be a Fantasy star and a 100+ defender. That's the mark he'll need to be to prove a worthy starting pick priced at 88. He showed he was capable of this during the finals where he averaged 110. It's the 13 scores under 90 that worry me and these will become less and less the more confidence he gains and the more he demands the ball. I feel like this is 6 months away so I'm resisting the temptation. However, if he displays this added hunger in the preseason or early rounds, I won't talk you out of it.
afShort: 90 in last 5 and 110 in finals suggests he can breakout in 2023 and push towards the 100 mark

afComment: The mid-season draft pick from 2021 came straight into the Hawks' side, finding his feet right away, setting the AFL record for tackles on debut with 14. However, his 2nd season was even more impressive. He went from what I thought has a hard working 'scrapper' to a genuine midfielder, finishing runner up in the Hawks' B&F behind defender James Sicily. If that wasn't a sign of him being their main man in the middle, then trading away veterans Mitchell and O'Meara is. At just 21 years old and another preseason under his belt, those CBAs should shoot to 75%+ and he could become a 100 averaging midfielder in 2023. However, it's hard to average 100 when your team is getting smashed most weeks, which is likely following the Hawks' offseason moves. That's enough to put a line through for me, but don't let me talk you out of it if you're keen on the rising star.
afShort: The runner-up B&F will be the main man without Titch and JOM, however it might be hard to score consistently in big losses

afComment: Daicos was as good as advertised. Playing down back, he was so clean and composed and finished the season with an average of 88. While it doesn't sound massive, his 88 average didn't do it justice as Collingwood's game style wasn't conducive to high scoring. In fact, he was the Pies' leading Fantasy scorer post their bye. There are a few questions to ask for 2023. Does he remain in the backline or will he transition to the midfield? Will Collingwood play more of a Fantasy friendly game style? Will opposition teams continue to lock down on him as we saw at times last season? There are enough unknowns for me to pass on Daicos as a starting squad option. However, the case has been there plenty of times before with second year players where if they look like taking a Taranto/Oliver sized leap, then you can jump on in the early rounds and do so with more confidence.
afShort: Collingwood's low scoring game style the main thing holding him back from being a top 6 option in his 2nd season

afComment: The damaging half back was a borderline top 6 defender from 2019-2020 when he had a mortgage on the Dogs' kick-in duties. However, since Dale has switched to defence in 2021, Daniel has dropped slightly and now finds himself outside the calculations for a top 6. Dale took 56% of the Dogs' kick-ins in 2022 compared to Daniel's 35%. An interesting point was that Daniel took 71% in the final and scored a 97. If he can ever return to the being main guy then he could be considered, but Dale looks pretty secure in that role for now.
afShort: Dropped to a level below the top 6 defenders ever since Dale moved to defence in 2021 and took the kick-in duties

afComment: Perryman has been a reliable wing/half back for the Giants since 2019, averaging 88 and 85 in 2020 and 2021. He was never in Fantasy discussions given he was a step below the top 6 defenders, however his name popped up into lights when McVeigh took over as coach in Round 10 and gave Perryman his first CBAs. He attended 51% and scored a then season high of 114. A defender who played inside was certainly interesting, however it was short-lived after he injured his ribs 2 games later on 31 and missed the last 6 games. He did return to the midfield , highlighted by a 132 from 90% CBAs in Round 22. A defender priced at 87 who attended centre bounces and can score 130s is attractive, however McVeigh is gone and I doubt he'll be used in the middle for Kingsley, despite the loss of Hopper and Taranto. Predicting the Giants' CBA rotation has been an impossible task, so keep an eye on it in the preseason, but I think Perryman will return to a wing/half back role and be a low-90s scorer. Regardless, he's lost his defender status for 2023 so he's not a strong option in Classic.
afShort: Lost his defender status after being used as a CBA mid under McVeigh and I think he'll return to a wing/HB role in 2023 which caps his output

afComment: It was apparent from early in his career that Butters was going to be a star of the comp one day. Unfortunately, it's meant a lot of coaches have backed him in for a breakout in Fantasy for two years now and been let down. However, he's had excuses. A bad ankle injury kept him to just 10 games in 2021, but that included a 119 in Round 2, and 83 before getting injured midway through the 3rd quarter in Round 4 and then three scores over 88 in his last five games of the season. Last season was a mix of big scores when given midfield time (2 scores over 120 when averaging 52% CBAs), low scores (5 under 70 from 26% CBAs), injuries (MCL injury when on 44 before half time) and duds (a 34 when sick all week). However, when he had full fitness and played in the right role, he showed he can be a top 6 forward after all, averaging 107 in his last 5 games. The forward line is getting crowded with a number of great starting options and Butters takes on more risk - role and injury due to his bash-and-crash nature - than the others. However, I'm a believer and think he can be a 100+ averaging forward this season, which would make him a great pick at this price.
afShort: We've waited 2 years for the Fantasy breakout and his 107 in the last 5 of 2022 could be a sign of things to come

afComment: Ellis has the Fantasy game that is capable of putting up some monster scores. He had 2 scores over 125 last year, following his 7 over 110 in 2021 (including a 169). He's gained defender status for 2023, which keeps him in the discussion as there aren't many defenders with that scoring ability. His kick-in rate increased as the season went on which lead to higher scoring. However, as the Suns become more competitive, there are less slow plays where Ellis is the beneficiary of some easy plus 6ers. He'll likely have some high scoring games again in 2023, but mixed with some low scores (13 games sub-90 in 2022). He'll be a level below the top 6 in Fantasy.
afShort: High ceiling and defender status makes him relevant in 2023, but I've got him just below the top 6 given his inconsistency

afComment: After finishing 2021 emerging as a top 2 ruck, Darcy had a disappointing 2022. It started in the preseason where nothing went right. He broke a thumb, had sore groins and then an Achilles injury that kept him out of the first practice match and Round 1. It's the second interrupted preseason in a row for Darcy after his knee injury in 2021 and it showed, scoring 47 in the AAMI and 83 in pre bye. He looked more of his 2021 self post bye, averaging 89 in the second half and 90 in his last 5. His season high of 147 came from 89% CBAs, and this is the CBA level we'd love him to be consistently. He's been a 68%-73% CBA ruckman the last two years, largely due to the interrupted preseasons. The hope of that reaching 80%+ took a hit in the preseason with the recruitment of Luke Jackson, who you'd think will ruck more than Rory Lobb did last season. Lobb averaged 20%, which isn't a heap, it was more Meek who took over 60% when playing. Meek is gone so the outlook for Darcy might not be as grim as some are predicting. I think he'll ruck 70% which is what he did in the last half for a 90 average, it's just hard to see him being a top 2 ruck, which he could've been without Jackson given he's heading into his peak-ruck period of season 7.
afShort: Ready to breakout after 2 interrupted preseasons in a row, however the arrival of Jackson will put a cap on that

afComment: Is there a 28 gamer that has had more airtime in Fantasy than Braydon Preuss? After missing his full first season at the Giants, many were relying on Preuss to be their R2 in 2023. On face value, he was a success when he played, averaging 94 points per full game played. It was the fact he only played 10 games and got injured/suspended/dropped at the wrong time all year. Sadly, this has been the consistent story for Preuss his entire career. There's no doubt he's a very good Fantasy scorer when on the park (highlighted by his 132 from 10 VFL games in 2019), but he's become too hard to trust. When he was priced below 60 as he has been for his entire career, then it was a risk worth taking. But now that he's priced at 86, I'd rather start with a ruck with equal upside and less downside (i.e. English and Marshall).
afShort: Lead the rucks for PPM in 2022, unfortunately it's the M that we can't trust him playing every week

afComment: Nank has been a consistent ruck since arriving at the Tigers, averaging between 80 and 90 in 5 of the past 6 seasons. That's nice to rely on in Draft, but he's never going to be the top 2 ruck or 15 point upside player we're hunting for in Classic.
afShort: Between 80 and 90 in 5 of the past 6 season so hard to see that changing

afComment: Early in his career, it looked as though Luke Ryan could be a gun Fantasy option going forward. However, he has since become a very handy real life defender for Fremantle and his role has quickly become less Fantasy friendly. He still has the attributes to go big and does so every so often, highlighted by a 151 last season. However, I feel he’ll give up a few extra touches to Hayden Young this year and likely remain a mid-to-high-80s Fantasy defender.
afShort: A mid-to-high 80s defender with a high ceiling which might be capped as Hayden Young becomes more prominent

afComment: A much-improved season in real life and in Fantasy and now finds himself at the Blues where he should have a wing to himself. Wingmen don't score premium-mid Fantasy numbers, so while he could match his career high, he's not going to be in the conversation.
afShort: Wingmen are capped to the 90 mark in Fantasy so this is the best he'll be

afComment: At his best, the West Coast captain can easily eclipse his price, being 17 points less than his 2019 season. Unfortunately, he's struggled with soft tissue injuries since then, playing just 37 games in 3 years at less than 70% game time. His PPM is still good enough, but you can't trust the 32 year old in your Classic team.
afShort: His best is good enough but 37 games in 3 years at less than 70% game is too risky for a 32-year-old

afComment: Redman had a career best season in real life and in Fantasy, bumping his average up from 68 to 85. However, it was highlighted by his 4 120+ scores. What caught the eye was his 113 average in wins. Unfortunately, the Bombers didn't win many games and his average was impacted by his 73 average in losses. With the Bombers likely to improve in 2023 and Redman still just 25, we can expect him to increase his average again which would see him knocking on the door of the top 6 defenders. His inconsistency makes him a risk (13 sub-90 scores from 20 games including 6 less than 70), but he'll be a super unique option for anyone willing to take a punt.
afShort: Averaged 113 in wins in 2022 which catches the eye given Essendon should be winning a lot more this season

afComment: Smith has been a consistent 80-90 player for the majority of his career. His forward status gives him some relevance in Draft but with the amount of quality options up forward, the 34-year-old isn't a consideration in Classic.
afShort: 80-90 isn't bad for a forward but not with the other quality ones out there

afComment: After 11 seasons in a row averaging at least 98, Pendlebury put up his 2nd mid-80s average in a row to show that he is finally slowing down.
