He was still asked to play a prominent role in the Pies' midfield, attending 61% of their centre bounces. This is more of a sign of the lack of depth in the Pies' midfield last season. However, with the arrival of Tom Mitchell and hopefully a healthy Taylor Adams, I expect we might see Pendles taking a step back in 2023. This could mean he gets DPP at some stage during the season, but I think we won't see an increase in scoring from the 35-year-old.
afShort: Likely to take a step back which might mean DPP at some stage but unlikely to increase his scoring

afComment: Green has steadily improved in each of his 3 seasons, however the Giants' midfield logjam has stopped him from really breaking out. Arriving into the league as a highly-touted, Cripps/Oliver type, he clearly needed some time to get his fitness up to AFL standard, playing just 66% and 71% in his first 2 seasons. However, he looked like a man last season and his 82% TOG was a great sign. However, his 58% CBAs was not. He had his chances early in the season and looked good, but reduced his midfield time as the year went on. With Hopper and Taranto gone, Green is the obvious beneficiary and should see his CBAs jump to over 70% in 2023. The question is can he push his average to the 100 mark needed to be a good selection at that price. His low kick-to-handball ratio and lack of marks (just 2.8 per game v 4.4 for the top 8) are my concerns but I think he'll increase his possession rate and tackles to take him to around 100.
afShort: The obvious beneficiary of Hopper and Taranto leaving, just needs to work on his marks and outside game to push the 100 mark needed

afComment: After a career best Fantasy year in 2021 in his 13th season, Rich returned to the 80s guy he's been for the majority of his career. That's not enough to consider the 32-year-old.
afShort: 32 and back to scoring in the mid-80s

afComment: After a shocking 2021 where he lost his place in Essendon’s first-choice midfield mix, Shiel bounced back somewhat to average 84. After the bye he returned to be a high CBA player and averaged 99. If he can maintain this role then a score close to 100 could be achievable, however a career best of just 102 in 11 seasons shows he's very been a prominent Fantasy player.
afShort: 99 post bye from 76% will be best case scenario and he might not see 76% again

afComment: Sam Berry was given every chance to succeed in 2022, playing prime midfield minutes over the likes of leadership group member Ben Keays and former B&F winner Matt Crouch. This shows Adelaide must rate him highly, and he showed a great amount of improvement. He led the comp in tackles per game, which is a great achievement for a 21-year-old in his first full season in the midfield. Normally the leading tacklers are Fantasy studs and number 2 on the list was the number 1 Fantasy asset in 2022, Rory Laird. However, Berry's 17.6 disposals per game are a long way off what they need to be to be a relevant Fantasy midfielder. With another preseason and if given the same opportunity, he could bump that to low 20s and push his average to the mid-90s, but that's not enough as a pure mid in Fantasy.
afShort: Crows love him with 76% CBAs post bye and led comp in tackles per game, just needs to win more of it to be relevant as a mid-only

afComment: After a career best 2021 where he broke into the midfield at stages and looked great, Langford had a disappointing 2022, restricted to just 9 games due to hamstring issues and dropped his average by 22 points. Unfortunately, he's a victim of the AFL Fantasy pricing mechanism, where he's priced at a 3% discount to his career high 87. This means that despite his forward status, he's not an option given he's the 9th most expensive forward while ranked 55th on 2022 average.
afShort: Disappointing 2022 but priced on his career high 2021 season while removes any discount

afComment: The sky looked the limit after his 87 and 99 in his first two seasons in the comp. However, he’s put up back-to-back 84s since moving to West Coast. I was pretty bullish on him last season following reports he was back in career best condition, however early season Covid and then the West Coast struggles meant he had another disappointing season. At 28, he should be at his peak, meaning averaging 99 again isn't out of the question. However, he doesn't have the Fantasy game to become a star of the Fantasy competition, with below average marks and tackles (four per game in each category). 84 to 99 is a nice 15-point upside, so he's not a bad option. I just think you need someone who can push 105-plus at this price and midfield only.
afShort: Due for a bounceback after back-to-back 84s, but lacks the tackles and marks to be a 105+ mid

afComment: Looking back on my comments of past season guides, I've always had hope that Gresham will breakout. He'd teased us when given CBAs, averaging 91 in the second half of 2019 when introduced into the midfield (100 in the last five), but then returned to a small forward role the following year. The Saints' midfield is very one paced and I thought someone crafty like Gresham should be used more in there. We saw that consistent midfield role come to fruition in 2022, however he underperformed from a scoring point of view, averaging 84 points from 60% CBAs. It's unknown where he will play under Ross, but I've now seen enough to know that he's a better player in real life than in Fantasy and I doubt he'll trouble the top 6 forwards.
afShort: Finally saw consistent CBAs (60%) but scoring was a bit off the top 6 and future role under new coach is unknown

afComment: Outside of his 2020 season where he was used in the midfield in the absence of Shuey and Yeo, Duggan had a career high Fantasy season, averaging 84 points per game. His 107 in the his last 5 games caught the eye and that type of scoring would see him be a top 6 defender. However, a lot of it was with how West Coast faired last season and they played a lot of slow football to control the scoreboard. I doubt they will play the same way in 2023 and while he should be in his peak at 26, mid-80s appear about him, which won't be enough to see him be a top 6 defender.
afShort: Should be in his peak and mid-80s appear about that, which won't be enough to see him be a top 6 defender

afComment: Since Heppell has moved to the backline in 2021, he's been a solid Fantasy defender, averaging 90 points per game. I thought he would improve in his second season in the role with more confidence. However, the Bombers are full of distributors down back, with Redman, Ridley, Hind and D'Ambrosio all very good kicks of the football. I doubt he'll gain more usage down there, especially with McGrath touted to return to defence. So unless we see him return to the midfield (which would be a surprise), then I doubt he'll come into Fantasy relevance in 2023.
afShort: Averaged 89 since the defensive switch and too many distributors at Essendon for him to bump that to 100

afComment: Jed caught the eye in 2020 when he was the number one ranked player for points-per-minute (minimum two games) on his way to a 104. He never reached those heights again and the Roos moved on from him at the end of 2022. Now at the Suns, he is there as a depth midfielder who I still rate highly, but I doubt he'll ever get the midfield opportunities he had when he was a Fantasy relevant player (62%).
afShort: Depth player at the Suns who has a Fantasy game but I doubt he'll have the opportunity to use it

afComment: Cameron returned to the 80+ Fantasy forward in 2022 after back-to-back 60s. Key forwards a very rarely relevant in Fantasy, however Cameron does score more than the average key forward. However, in a year with so many midfield options in the forward line, there is no chance of Cameron competing with the top tier.
afShort: Scores better than the average key forward, but that's not enough in a year full of fwd/mids

afComment: Gulden is part of the young Swans brigade who all look like they are going to be stars of the comp. Playing predominantly as a high half forward, Gulden moved to a wing in the second half of 2022 and looked great, average 86 in the second half and 95 in his last 5. Players typically take a big step in their 3rd season and I think we'll be seeing Gulden take over a few games in 2023. The question is can he average the 95+ required of him to be a decent pick at that price? The fact he's likely to be a wing and not attend many centre bounces (10% in 2022) makes it hard to average 95+ over a full season. And in a year where there are plenty of forward options who have great CBAs, I think it's best to play it safe and go with the proven guys.
afShort: 95 in last 5 playing on a wing and I think we can expect something similar in 2023

afComment: Tuohy a found a nice role in defence for the Cats and been a decent scorer for the majority of his career now. However, the fact his career best season (86) wouldn't crack the top 20 defenders, he's not an option in Fantasy.
afShort: Consistent but the 33 yr old's best season of 86 isn't a top 20 defender score

afComment: After ankle surgery in the preseason, Zorko had his second worst return of his career in 2022, struggling with injury and form to average 82 points for the season. Remarkably, he had 3 games with less than 50% game time. Removing those and his average wasn't that bad. Zorko has been a Fantasy stalwart throughout his career. His scoring is boosted by above average kick-to-handball ratio, marks, goals and tackles. With all this combined, he's a unique player who doesn't require 30 touches to get a decent Fantasy score. And when he does get 30 touches, he can push out some monster scores. With the buzz around young guns Dunkley, Taranto and Rozee, Zorko could be the bargain buy of them all. However, it would take a brave coach. He's now 34 and coming off the year of niggles. It's the sort of risk I don't normally take with my Fantasy team, especially given the number of good forwards available. But if you're willing to take the risk, then it could certainly pay off.
afShort: 3 games less than 50% in 2023 means he could be a bargin buy, but not for the faint hearted

afComment: Rightly, all the talk is about how Tom Mitchell will go after leaving the Hawks who clearly gave their kids preference over the veterans last season. O'Meara doesn't have the Fantasy pedigree that Mitchell has, but has arrived at a far more Fantasy friendly environment at Fremantle and looks set to take a prominent role in their midfield. Mundy has retired and surprisingly took up 65% CBAs on very low TOG. Serong's 66% will get a boost, but beside him I think we will see something similar from Brayshaw and Brodie. That means O'Meara could carve out 65%+ CBAs, which is only a touch more than what he averaged last year, but in a better environment. O'Meara has had an underwhelming Fantasy career, impacted by injuries throughout. The fact that a man of his talent hasn't averaged over 100 in a season in his 11 seasons is a shock. So 100 is about his best case this season but that would be enough to be a decent pick at that 82 price.
afShort: Yet to average over 100 in his 11 seasons, but a new environment he could push that mark in 2023 which would make him a decent mid-priced buy

afComment: Rowbottom has always been highly rated at the Swans, however appeared to be overtaken by some of the new draftees in 2021, reducing his CBA numbers from the year prior and even finding himself out of the side. However, returned to be one of their 4 key mids in 2022 with 50% CBAs alongside Parker (72%), Warner (63%) and Mills (56%). The way he finished the season (87 post bye and 107 last 5) indicated that he'll be a prime onballer for of the future. With Parker now into his 30s, it's likely to be a Mills, Warner and Rowbottom midfield for years to come. I think we'll see his CBAs bump up to above 60% in 2023 which will hopefully see him increase his disposal count from his current 18, which is about 10 less than the elite mids in the comp. He tackles as well as any of them (6.8 per game compared to 6.0 from the top 8 mids) which gives him a nice floor for scoring, but his lack of outside game will restrict his scoring for now. This will come, but I think it's 12 months away, so I'm not as bullish on him as others seem to be.
afShort: Needs to bump his disposal count from 18 per game to go with his 7 tackles to regularly put up the 107 he did in the last 5 games of 2022

afComment: Saad had an outstanding season and finished at an All Australian half back, indicating he's one of the top few defenders in the league. However, he finished ranked as the 27th best defender in Fantasy, which is the story of his whole career. Saad is far more damaging in real life than in Fantasy and will never be in contention to be a top 6. The role he does play in Fantasy is that he now is the preferred shut down target for opposition sides, meaning Docherty now runs free more often than not.
afShort: Far more damaging in real life than in Fantasy

afComment: After being a big scorer at reserve level as number one ruck, Cameron finally had the chance to showcase his ability at AFL level after Grundy went down in Round 6. He averaged 93 in the 16 games since and showed enough that the Pies traded Grundy at season end, meaning he'll be their main man next year. Given he averaged 48 in the first 5 games (one as the sub), he comes into 2023 priced at 82, 11 points less than what he showed he can do as first ruck. With English and Marshall set to eclipse that, many are overlooking Cameron for 2023. However, he only attended 55% of the centre bounce ruck contests in 2022, given the Pies' preference to use him forward and play Cox in the ruck a bit. The offseason recruitment of McStay will likely see Cox pushed out of the side and McStay playing as second ruck, and there is no way he will be doing 45%. Therefore, Cameron could increase his usage to 70%+, meaning a bump in average could be on the cards. If this bumps to 100, which it could with 70% CBAs, then he could prove a very nice point of difference in the ruck department.
afShort: Averaged 93 after Grundy went down and McStay in could mean even more CBAs than his 55% last season

afComment: Became a regular for the Hawks in 2022 on a wing, playing 21 games. Wingmen aren't great in Fantasy, particularly when they are mid-only. Not relevant in Fantasy.
afShort: Wingman who is mid-only, not a Fantasy option

afComment: After 11 games in 2 seasons following an impressive debut season, Clark returned to form in his first year at Freo. He averaged 80 from a half back flank and was consistent throughout. I think if it weren't for Luke Ryan and Hayden Young, then he would have the potential to push his average into the 90s and be a Fantasy relevant defender. However, for a decent kick, he takes very little kick-ins (3%) and is not the primary distributor. Therefore, I doubt he'll push to that level and more likely remain as a mid-80 defender.
afShort: Behind Young and Ryan for distributor duties meaning he'll likely remain at his mid-80 average

afComment: Adams has now had two injury impacted seasons in a row. The man who has averaged 113+ twice in his career battled with hamstring and knee issues early 2022 which kept him to 88 in the first half of the season. He looked back to full fitness and went at 107 post bye. I thought he was underpriced in 2022, however it was a groin issue that restricted him all year, playing a career low 73% game time, and finally gave way with a complete rupture of his adductor in the final. He's recovered well and should be right to get enough preseason in before Round 1. Therefore, he becomes a discounted option for 2023 being priced at 82. The concern is that he could be managed, which we saw in parts of 2022 where he played sub-70% game time on a lot of occasions. It will be made easier now that Tom Mitchell will take the prime inside mid role. There is also risk of reinjury, which looking at 3 of his past 4 seasons you'd have to say he's now an injury prone player. The Pies also play a less possession heavy game style now than they did when Adams was going 113. However, if you're a high risk / high reward coach, then Adams could a nice unique.
afShort: Has averaged 113+ twice and is priced at 81, but recent injury history the concern

afComment: I've been a bit anti-Gaff for a few seasons and a reason why I don't like wingmen/outside mids in Fantasy. When West Coast were strong, he was super consistent using hard running to gather uncontested possessions and Fantasy points at will, with multiple seasons over 110. But he lacked the inside strength and tackling game to generate consistent 'uber-premium' 115+ scores. And then when the team is less competitive and the possessions drop off like they have the past two seasons, he's prone to sub-par scores (10/16 games under 90, something you'd never see a few years back). While I suspect he'll bounce back to average over 90 in 2023, he's not going to be the 105+ player of the past so I don't think he's worth starting with.
afShort: Two down seasons in a row comes with being an outside mid in a poor side and while both WC and Gaff should be better in 2023, I doubt it will be by enough to be worthwhile

afComment: After a prolific junior career and earning his stripes in defence once drafted, McGrath shifted to the midfield in 2020. He looked good initially and I thought on track to be a Fantasy stud, but his midfield time reduced and he’s been in no man’s land for the past 4 years, playing wing, on ball and half back. Brad Scott has come out and said he wants to settle McGrath off a half back flank, and while I feel like he could still make it as an inside mid, a settled position should be good for his development. At age 24, he should be entering his peak. However, with competition for distribution at the Dons, with Redman, Ridley, Hind and D'Ambrosio taking a lot of kicks, I don’t think we’ll see McGrath breakout to be a top 6 defender.
afShort: A move to defense for the former number 1 pick should see some improvement and might knock on the door of the top 6 defenders

afComment: Swallow is an honest competitor and been a consistent scorer in the 80-90 range for most of his career. However, a career best year of 94 in 12 seasons and fresh off an 81 isn't enough to consider as a midfield option in Fantasy. Keep an eye on him for Draft as he's one who may gain DPP over the year, but even then he'll unlikely feature.
afShort: A long way off the top ones as a mid-only, best chance will be if he gains DPP during the season and comes into Fantasy relevance

afComment: Hopper had a disappointing 2022, dealing with knee issues that limited him to just 7 matches at an average of 66. With the AFL Fantasy pricing methodology, he's priced at a discount on his 2021 average of 90, so he comes into 2023 priced at 82. The promising thing for Hopper is that he's left the Giants where there was always a logjam for midfield opportunities and now finds himself at the Tigers where he should see consistent inside midfield minutes. However, he's had some consistent CBAs in the past, with 75% and 72% in 2020 and 2021 for averages of 88 and 90. He's the reason why you can't rely on pure inside midfielders for Fantasy, as they don't get enough easy possessions and marks (Hopper averaged less than 3 marks last season) to take their Fantasy game to the next level. Not saying this won't change though, as we saw a very similar thing with Ollie Wines, who prior to 2021 was a pure inside midfielder whose scoring was capped to the low 90s. He then leaned up and increased his spread around the ground, seeing him shoot his average up to 112. If he was priced at his 2022 average then I'd be prepared to take that punt, but not now he's priced in the 80s.
afShort: Priced at 82 which isn't enough off his career best 92 even with a favourable move to the Tigers, he doesn't win enough easy ball

afComment: The 32-year-old has played every game in the last 2 years and got decent CBA opportunity, which was interesting considering some of his younger teammates struggled for time in the middle. He's been a tough player for the Giants but I doubt he'll see as much midfield time under the new coach. I expect we've seen the best of Ward and he's not a relevant Fantasy option.
afShort: Might struggle for midfield opportunity this season and won't have Fantasy relevance

afComment: There was a bit of buzz around Lipinski this time last year after his trade to the Pies. He showed great signs from limited opportunities at the Dogs and put up some monster scores at VFL level. He led the Pies for CBAs in the preseason game and if it weren't for an early ankle injury in the AAMI, he would've started in a lot more sides. Those who jumped off were kicking themselves after Round 1 as Lipinski scored 117 from 48% CBAs and was everywhere. However, he only hit 48% CBAs twice more for the season and dropped to 19% in his last 5. His scoring never took off, averaging 80 for the season with reducing splits as the season went on. He heads into 2023 with forward status, however with the arrival of Tom Mitchell and fitness of Taylor Adams, I doubt we'll see him get the midfield opportunities he needs to compete with the top 6 forwards.
afShort: Forwards status is nice but doubt he'll get the midfield opportunities he needs to be a top 6

afComment: Himmelberg's switch to defence midseason was a masterstroke by stand-in coach, McVeigh. It was one I never saw coming and he averaged 98 as a defender, after averaging 54 as a key forward. He didn't just score well, but he made an impact and looked at home in defence, not playing as a key defender but as one of their prime movers back there. If he were to continue in that role in 2023 then he's an obvious underpriced option, priced at 80 when we've seen him score 98 in the role. However, new coach Kingsley comes from Richmond and I highly doubt he will let the Giants play the slow kick-mark game they showcased last year. Also, word is that he's back training with the forwards, which makes sense given their number of tall defenders and lack of tall forwards. Therefore, I'm not sure you can do it, despite that attractive discount to his post bye average.
afShort: Averaged 98 as a defender but word is he's training with the forwards which puts a dampener on what looked like an underpriced option

afComment: I've always held hope Naitanui would make an impact as a Fantasy ruckman of elite point per minute numbers. The issue was he just plays so little game time – never touching 70% in 5 seasons. However, he had his lowest PPM in the previous 5 years last season and for the first time ever seemed to have lost his spring and impact. Sadly, I think he’s past his peak and we won’t see him average much more than he in 2022.
afShort: PPM down last season which shows he's slowing down and sadly I can't see him bouncing back

afComment: I don't think anyone saw Nic Martin's debut season coming. The mature aged recruit who trained with West Coast in the preseason before signing with Essendon, averaged 76 in the WAFL the year prior and came out and averaged 80 at AFL level, including a 130 on debut. He still looked very raw despite being mature aged and the with amount he improved with less than 1 preseason, I think he'll greatly benefit from a full preseason. However, as an outside wingman, I doubt he could improve enough to be Fantasy relevant this season. He retained his forward status which means he might only need 95 to be a worthwhile selection, however I think that's a stretch for him and there are better options out there in the forward line.
afShort: Great debut season and should improve again but scoring is capped as an outside wingman so I doubt he'll challenge the top 6

afComment: After averaging 84 in his second season, Burton looked to be a star Fantasy defender of the future. He hasn't matched that average since in 5 seasons. Unfortunately, he hasn't come on and you can't take the risk on him turning it around this year.
afShort: Hasn't come on as I though he was going to after his 84 average in year 2

afComment: Cotchin plays a perfect team game for the Tigers and as a result, hasn't been a factor in AFL Fantasy for a number of years now. Certainly not an option this year, especially considering he’ll likely lose midfield time to Hopper and Taranto.
afShort: Hasn't had a Fantasy game for 5 years now

afComment: De Goey burst into Fantasy relevance in 2021 when he was shifted into the midfield and averaged 110 for the second half of the season. McRae kept him in there for the full season, attending 77% of the CBAs, however never met those scoring heights, averaging 79 for the regular season. It was a mixture of both McRae's low possession game style and the focus for De Goey to get his possessions in a dangerous position forward of centre. We might see him spend a bit more time forward as the Pies' midfield depth should be deeper with Tom Mitchell and hopefully Adams rotating in there, so while I think he should outperform 79 which he's priced at, I doubt we'll see the 100+ De Goey again under McRae.
afShort: First full season as a midfeilder however McRae's lower possession game plan and focus to get the ball forward of centre means he might not be that 100+ player again

afComment: Aish has become a reliable role player for Freo, playing a range of positions which included being a tagger in 2022 but mainly as a wingman. He's a mid 70s type player, which certainly doesn't make him relevant in Fantasy, particularly as a mid-only.
afShort: Versatile role player not one for Fantasy

afComment: Once a relevant Fantasy forward fell out of favour last season, playing just the 7 games at an average of 68. Now 31, it's likely he'll struggle for games again, especially considering Geelong's off season recruiting.
afShort: Will likely struggle for games again

afComment: Moved into the midfield with great team impact in 2022, highlighted by his strong tackle pressure. He had a small bump in output (66 in 2021 to 82 post bye in 2022 when CBAs went to 59%) but 82 is still not enough to be a relevant defender. Should improve again with Selwood out, but I think he's one of those who is too team orientated to make a impact in Fantasy.
afShort: Pressure midfielder who is too team orientated to make an impact in Fantasy

afComment: Rioli was a revelation in 2022, switching to half back and becoming a star running defender of the comp. The move improved his Fantasy output by 22 points per game to finish with 78 for the season. There's no question he'll remain in the role, even if Short moves back again, but he'll unlikely push that average to the 90 mark needed to be a relevant defender this season.
afShort: Starred down back and will remain in that role but unlikely push that average to the 90 mark needed to be a relevant defender

afComment: Byrne-Jones has been a 70s/80s guy for the past 5 seasons. That's about him I think, so he's not worth considering in Fantasy.
afShort: A 70s/80s defender

afComment: The Big O has become a solid ruck, averaging mid-70s for the past 3 seasons. While solid, he's had the number 1 mantle at the Lions for long enough to know that he's never going to challenge the top few in Fantasy.
afShort: Averaged mid-70s since being the number 1 ruck

afComment: The former number three pick looked set to fulfill his potential in 2019, pushing up the ground to average 99 points per game, including 106 in the last half. Unfortunately, he hasn't gone on with it, dropping his average in every season since to finish on 75 last year. At 27, he should be in his prime and may appear underpriced to what he could produce. However, Billings needs two things to be relevant in Fantasy; forward status and CBAs. Unfortunately, he's available mid-only and attended no centre bounces last season.
afShort: Reduced his averaged every year since 2019

afComment: After finishing 2020 averaging 94 in the second half of the season playing inside-mid, Daicos has been used predominantly as a wingman since, meaning he's yet to recapture that scoring ability. He saw some CBAs in the back half of 2022, averaging 22% post bye, and naturally improved his average to 86 from 72. The Pies were light on for inside mids, but with Tom Mitchell's arrival and a healthy Taylor Adams, I expect Daicos to move back to his wing role, which means he'll be capped with his scoring output in 2023.
afShort: Scoring is limited when on the wing which is where he'll likely play in 2023

afComment: Smith has been a consistent defender for a number of years now without taking that next step and being a Fantasy relevent one. His kick-ins are low for someone with such a nice kick (only 31%) as he's made way for Dawson to be the main man back there. While Dawson is playing in defence, I doubt we'll see Smith pushing that average much higher.
afShort: While Dawson is playing in defence, I doubt we'll see Smith pushing that average much higher

afComment: Coleman had a delayed start to 2022 after a preseason hamstring injury, but returned to produce a breakout season, averaging 78 and looking great as a defender. He averaged 109 in the role at reserve level in 2021, so he can obviously find it. He showed enough to suggest he could one day be a top 6 Fantasy defender, I just doubt that it will be this season while Rich is still around taking the majority of the kick-ins. He did increase his kick-ins as the season went on which resulted in a bump in average.
afShort: Breakout 2022 but unlikley to be a top 6 while Rich is still around

afComment: The former top 10 pick has had a mixed Fantasy career. After a career high season in 2020 which included a 7 week stretch averaging 121 with 3 150s, he moved to a wing in 2021 and Hall and Ziebell took his role as the easy accumulator. McDonald's average dropped to just 68 points in this wing role. He returned to defence last season and improved his average, but was far from the role that saw him be a top defender in 2020. It's unclear what role he'll play under Clarko, but I think one things is for sure that they won't be doing the slow 'chip-mark' game that the Roos have played for the last 3 seasons. One to watch, but you'd need certainty on role before selecting him.
afShort: Has it in him to go big as we saw in the back end of 2020, just don't know what role Clarko will have for him

afComment: Newman has had flashes of Fantasy brilliance throughout his career, however he's never put together a full season. He’s behind Docherty and Saad for distribution duties, which means he’s too inconsistent to rely on in Fantasy.
afShort: Too inconsistent to rely on in Fantasy

afComment: Dunstan has shown he's a genuine Fantasy scorer when given the opportunity, however it's the opportunity that he has struggled with his whole career. He played 4 games in his first season at the Dees and will likely remain a depth player behind their star mids.
afShort: Will likely remain a depth player behind the Dee star mids

afComment: Hind backed up his breakout 2021 with a 77 average in 2022. He's a good player and I'd be surprised if his role changes much under the new coach. However, there is no shortage of distributors in defence at the Dons so I doubt we'll suddenly see an increase in average anytime soon.
afShort: No shortage of distributors in defence at the Dons so I doubt we'll suddenly see an increase in average anytime soon

afComment: Walker's late-career resurgence has been great to watch. However, outside of averaging 115 after 4 rounds in 2021, he's still a key forward and key forwards aren't what you want in Fantasy.
afShort: Scores above average for a key forward however key forwards aren't what you want in Fantasy

afComment: Parfitt has been borderline relevant in Fantasy when he had forward status. He's now only available in the midfield, and considering he was in and out of the side at the end of 2022, he's not worth considering in Fantasy.
afShort: Mid-only and behind in the pecking order now at Geelong

afComment: Fyfe has been impacted by injuries in 5 of his last 7 seasons, however hit rock bottom in 2022. He's never been a natural Fantasy player as he's very much in the Dustin Martin mould of too good in real life to worry about tackling or picking up cheap marks. Despite winning two Brownlows and being one of the premier midfielders in the AFL, Fyfe's best Fantasy season average is just 105. He finished 2022 with an average of 56, which is 49 points off his best ever 105. The form drop was largely injury related, but also came about from the emergence of Brayshaw, Serong and Brodie, meaning Fyfe spent time forward this season - just 29% CBAs. There was a lot of debate as to where Fyfe should play and I'm not sure Freo really knew either. Regardless, he should certainly bounce back and score much better than he did in 2022. Due to playing 7 games, he's priced at a discount to his 2021 average of 84. That makes him less appealing to select in the forward line this season.
afShort: Injury impacted 2022 but role uncertainty takes the gloss off any great bounce back

afComment: Fox had a career best average of 75 in 2021, but remained on the fringe in a strong Swans team. I think it will be much the same in 2023.
afShort: Never played more than 15 games in a season and always seems to be on the fringe

afComment: SPP had a career best season, playing all 22 games as a strong bodied forward. After bursting onto the scene 6 years ago, I had him earmarked to be a midfielder for years to come. However, he's found it hard for midfield minutes and bottomed out last season at just 3%. He's clearly not in calculations anymore and been surpassed by Rozee and Butters, so I think that forward role will be him going forward. In that role, it's hard to see him ever averaging much more than 80.
afShort: Settled in a forward role last season which produced a career best season but not good enough for Fantasy

afComment: The ever-green 34-year-old full forward is playing as well as ever in real life, however that equates to the mid-70 mark in Fantasy, which isn't enough to consider.
afShort: Mid-70s the last 2 and not getting younger

afComment: Curnow's return in 2022 was overshadowed by the other remarkable comebacks of Docherty, Sicily and Witts, but he managed to put up career best numbers and win the Coleman after returning from 4 games in 2 years. Prior to his knee issues, he was looking like he may transition to a tall wingman role in the Kouta-mould, a far more Fantasy friendly role. However, given how dominant he was playing as a key forward last year, he's not moving anywhere anytime soon. And a 77 average from a Coleman season suggests he not going to be a Fantasy option in that time.
afShort: Remarkable comeback from the Coleman medallist and locked into the key forward role which limits his Fantasy upside

afComment: Martin hasn't been a Fantasy stud for 5 seasons now due to his lack of tackles and marks. He's so good in real life that he doesn't need to pad his stats with tackles or defensive running which typically lead to easy marks on the way back. He's also been the number one shut-down option for opposition teams playing the Tigers. He's now past his prime in real life and struggled with injury and personal matters last season, he's become even less relevant in Fantasy circles. Priced at 79, I doubt we'll see him average much more than that given he averaged 74 last year excluding his lowest score.
afShort: Always far better in real life than in Fantasy and 74 excluding lowest in 2022 suggests he's past his peak in Fantasy also

afComment: The rebounding defender did his ACL last season, however is said to be progressing well and on track for a mid-season return. He can put up decent numbers in his half back role, however he'll need a while to get back in the groove and unlikely to make an impact this year.
afShort: Recovering from an ACL and on track for a mid-season return

afComment: Hogan is a different type of key forward. When at his best, he works hard up and down the ground and can put up numbers that make him Fantasy relevant (his 89 in 2018 would rank him 6th amongst current forwards this season). However, he's never looked the same player, and despite playing his best football last season since 2018, he's unlikely to push the top 6 in Fantasy.
afShort: Best season since his 89 in 2028, however he still looks a long way off that player

afComment: After being used as a forward and midfielder in his early years, Blakey had a breakout season in 2022, playing as a dashing half back. He took over the kick-in duties from Jake Lloyd, which shows how much the Swans wanted the ball in his hands and they used him at every opportunity. With another year in the system and role, he should improve again in 2023, however I doubt it will be by enough to be a worthwhile selection.
afShort: Breakout season as a running defender but lack of marks and tackles limit him in Fantasy

afComment: Dangerfield has been on a steady decline since 2017 when he was the 2nd best player in Fantasy. He had his lowest home and away average for 11 seasons in 2022, averaging just 76 from decent enough centre bounce numbers. He's now 32 and Geelong have always taken a cautious approach with their older players, indicated by his 18 games last season at just 75% TOG. That, combined with his mid-only status, makes it hard to take the punt on him this season, despite his cheap price tag.
afShort: As cheap as he's been for 11 years but lack of forward status and age makes it hard to do

afComment: The former top five draft pick had his best season in the AFL in 2022, playing all games as a lead up medium forward. It appears this will be his role going forward and I doubt a midfield move will come, which means outside his 101 average in the last five games of 2020, he'll be too hard to trust in Fantasy.
afShort: Locked into medium forward role so unlikely to improve his average significantly

afComment: Ridley looked like an emerging top 6 defender after averaging 89 in 2020 then coming hot out of the blocks in 2021, averaging 108 in the first four games. However, his Fantasy highlights stopped there. The intercept defender, who was the Bombers’ main distributor at the time, lost the majority of his kick-in duties and went from a loose marking defender who left his man at any opportunity to get involved and intercept, to a lock-down defender matching up on one of the opposition's dangerous forwards. There was hope he would return to the more Fantasy-friendly role last season after Essendon landed Jake Kelly in the offseason, who plays that third tall defender role very well and could relieve Ridley of those defensive duties. While Kelly did this to some extent, the emergence of Redman meant that Ridley took a back seat in 2022, reducing his averaging just 76. I think he’s better than that and heading into his 7th season, he should be entering his peak. Redman is still the main man down there but there’s still a chance Ridley can push back into the high-80s this season.
afShort: Took a back seat to Redman last season but he's a better player than his 76 average

afComment: Cunnington's return was a highlight of 2022. In a Fantasy sense, he's priced at a 24% discount to his 2021 average of 99, meaning he comes into 2022 priced at 75. While never being a natural Fantasy scorer due to the inside nature of his game resulting in a lack of marks and easy kicks, he's still an 85-95 type of player. For him to be a worthwhile selection, he'll need that to be at the upper end of that range. He did manage 99 in 2021, so he is capable of that score, but that was before the emergence of Simpkin and LDU who now have the keys to the Roos' midfield. It will be interesting to see how much time Cunnington will spend in there or if Clarkson opts to give the younger mids more opportunity. Regardless, it's not a risk that I'd be willing to take given there are so many unknowns. A preseason watch just in case.
afShort: Priced at 75 and will need to match his career best numbers to be a worthwhile selection

afComment: The former first round pick moved to Adelaide for more opportunities in 2021, however he has still found it hard to crack into the side. Hately has proven himself as a Fantasy scorer, averaging 113 from 13 NEAFL games in 2019 and over 100 in the SANFL since arriving. He's obviously got some deficiencies in his game for him not to be selected on most weekends. As a mid-only with shaky job security, you can't be taking the risk with him in Fantasy.
afShort: Has the pedigree but mid-only with shaky job security

afComment: The injury plagued mid has always been highly rated at the Lions and played the most games in his career in 2022 with 23. After starting as an inside mid who often played a defensive role, Berry moved to a wing post-bye where he didn’t looks as comfortable and only saw 5% CBAs. He was put back inside in a final and was best on ground and gave an indication we could see him spend more time in there this season. However, that was short lived when Dunkley arrived who will likely take up the main rotation with Neal and a combination of Rayner, Ashcroft, Bailey and Zorko, so I doubt we’ll see Berry get the bump he needs.
afShort: Any chance of an inside mid move hurt by Dunkley coming, so will likely be a role player again in 2022

afComment: 3 seasons in and I still don't know whether Rowell is going to be a Fantasy stud or dud. After record breaking numbers at junior level, Rowell exceeded everyone's expectations in his first few games at AFL level, averaging an adjusted 111 in his first four. He then had a season ending shoulder injury while on 0 in Round 5. He didn't have any luck in year 2, with an early knee injury in Round 1 before returning to play the last 11 games but looked a shadow of himself, averaging 59 points per game but had excuses given the injury and low TOG of 55%. After a full preseason, he came out with a bang, scoring 117 in Round 1 and we all thought we were going to see the Matt Rowell promised to us in his debut season. This was short lived, with a 46 in Round 2 and only exceeded 100 twice more for the season. He plays completely inside with zero spread to get easy possession, highlighted by his 67% contested rate (top 8 mids 47%) incredibly low 1.2 marks per game (top 8 mids 4.3). He looked purely focused on his role which at times meant manning an opposition mid and winning the footy came second. The reports from the Suns were only positive though and he did was top 5 in the AFL for tackles, pressure acts and defensive half pressure acts. So maybe the role was just part of his development and he'll soon be unleased to win more of the footy. In year 4, he we should start to see him enter is peak, and if you asked me 4 years ago what I thought he'd be averaging I'd be confident it would be something over 100. If that were to be the case, he'd prove a terrific starting pick, but from what I saw in 2022, I highly doubt that now.
afShort: Outside of Round 1, he's yet to reach the heights of his junior days and debut season and I'm not confident that he'll reach that this year

afComment: Brad Hill has been disappointing since his move to the Saints, after once being a wingman who could average 90. He reunites with Ross Lyon who was his coach during his career best footy and Lyon has already flagged a return to the wing for Hill. It's hard to see him suddenly averaging 90 again but if he does, he'll be a terrific selection as a defender priced at 75. Certainly one to keep an eye on in the preseason.
afShort: A return to the wing and reuniting with Ross Lyon gives Hill hope of returning to his best footy

afComment: As outside as they come and a reason why wingmen aren't Fantasy relevant, highlighted by his 1.3 tackles per game. Priced 17 points below his career best average, but not an option as he's only available in the midfield.
afShort: Outside wingman with back-to-back seasons of regression

afComment: Greene has the potential to be a top 6 forward if unleashed, as he's shown in the past, he can be a prolific ball winner when playing in the midfield. However, he's also a very dangerous forward and as such has settled in that role. He can still push the 80-mark in such role, so there’s some upside in his price, but not enough to consider in Classic unless we see him get 30%+ CBAs in the preseason.
afShort: Settled in the forward role where he can push the 80 mark but not the 100s when he's played midfield in the past

afComment: Howe finds himself at the Roos where he should see more than the 8 games he played for Hawks last season. Had had draft relevance in the past with defender status and a decent mark game which saw him average 84 post bye in 2021, 85 in limited games post bye 2022 and 98 at VFL level. However, as a mid-only, he's not one to consider in Fantasy.
afShort: Now at the Roos but unlikely to make a Fantasy impact as mid-only

afComment: I've had a watch on Bolton in Fantasy since his 88 average in the second half of 2020 when it looked like he was going to transition to a full time midfielder. However, while hitting great heights in real life, he's yet to match those Fantasy figures given his high impact nature of his game. With the addition of Hopper and Taranto over the trade period, I expect we'll see Bolton play more as that dangerous forward who pinch hits in the midfield, rather than the vice versa. Therefore, I don't think he can increase his scoring to the level required to be a good selection.
afShort: High impact player who might play less midfield following the off season additions

afComment: Drew has become a regular in the Power midfield, playing 45 games in the last 2 seasons at approx. 60% CBAs. With the emergence of Rozee, Butters and addition of JHF, I wouldn’t be surprised to see those numbers reduce in 2022 as Port try to be more dynamic in the midfield. Even if he does play and stay in the prominent midfield role, he's a pure inside midfielder and lacks the spread and easy possessions to make him a relevant option in Fantasy.
afShort: A regular in Ports midfield might find it harder this season with the emergence of the young stars

afComment: Graham appeared to be the next midfielder up once Cotchin, Prestia and Martin start to push out. And given his elite tackling ability and scoring at junior level, he's one I've kept an eye on. After averaging 84 from 40% CBAs in the last 5 of 2021, I expected that transition to happen last season. However, he went backwards, averaging 74 from just 22% CBAs and 49 from 1% in his last 5! He was 11th in line for season average CBAs at the Tigers in a clear sign that he might not be the next mid up. Couple that with the arrival of midfield duo Taranto and Hopper and I think Graham will remain as a high tackling forward. That should see him remain in the 70s and not make an impact in Fantasy.
afShort: Arrival of Taranto and Hopper has quashed any hope of Graham stepping up in the midfield

afComment: For 3 years prior to last, Salem was as consistent as they come but just below the top 6, hovering around the 90 mark. He his injured knee in the first minutes of Round 1 on 3, forcing him to miss the next 10 games. He returned with back-to-back 90s and it looked like he'd continue to be that low-90s player the rest of the season. However, he only managed 78 post bye as he lost kick-in duties (only 7% in last 5) and usage in defence, partly to Angus Brayshaw who took his rebound role when he was out and continued in it on return. He now comes into 2023 priced at 74 which is 20 less than what we know he can do. If he can produce around that mark, he'll prove a great starting squad selection in a year where there are some very expensive safe defenders and then a big gap to the rest. A lot will depend on how Brayshaw will be used in 2023 so he'll be a preseason watch, but I'm coming around to the idea of him being an underpriced defender who shouldn't hurt you up until his bye.
afShort: A poor year which saw him drop from the consistent 90 scorer of the past and if he can recapture that old form he's certainly one to consider

afComment: Former pick 11 played a career high 20 games in his second season at Essendon, averaging 74 points per game. I think he can play, he's just not in the first group of midfielders, being Parish, Shiel and Merrett, and with the recruitment of Setterfield and Hobbs expected to get more mid time, it's hard to bank on Caldwell increasing his workload in 2023.
afShort: Mid-only and no guarantee of mid-time makes it tough

afComment: 31-year-old key forward had some sort of resurgence in 2022, bumping his average up 19, despite 2 games at less than 50% game time. I doubt he can improve again though given his role and age so he's a pass in 2023.
afShort: 31-year-old key forward not a great combo

afComment: The Bombers missed the high tackling small forward in 2022 as he was limited to just the 8 games. As a small forward, he's not relevant for Fantasy, even more so given he's price at 73 coming off a 54 average due to the pricing mechanism.
afShort: Will hopefully bounce back after an injury impacted season, but the small forward isn't going to make much of an impact in Fantasy

afComment: A decent ruck when given the opportunity but behind Draper in the pecking order and hasn't played more than 9 games in last 6 seasons. Can't have.
afShort: Hasn't played more than 9 games in last 6 seasons

afComment: The speedy halfback playted 22 games in 2022 after dealing with a serious ankle injury in 2021. He started to show the talent displayed early in his career and averaged 82 post bye and 97 in the last 5 games. On those numbers he presents some value at a 73 price tag, but I do find it hard to pick a defender to average 90+ (which you'd need) when he's probably 3rd in line behind Dale and Daniel. One for Draft but too risky in Classic for me.
afShort: 82 post bye and 97 in the last 5 games a good sign heading into 2023, but still behind Dale and Daniel in pecking order

afComment: Has played a vital role as a hard running small forward at West Coast for a number of years now, just not a great role for Fantasy scoring.
afShort: Hard running small forward not one for Fantasy

afComment: He's one of the good guys of footy and had some Fantasy relevance in his time, but I was surprised with the amount of opportunity he got last year over the development of the youngsters (21 games at 53% CBAs). I doubt we see him get those chances under Clarko.
afShort: Might find it hard for opportunities this season

afComment: Returned to the midfield rotation post bye with 31% CBAs after just 9% pre, but that didn't yield much of a bump in scoring. Even with forward status, I doubt he'll come into Fantasy relevance in 2023.
afShort: 72 post bye despite 31% CBAs which I doubt he'll see in 2023

afComment: The star small forward has been used in the midfield for burst over the past 4 seasons, but his scoring manages to stay in the low 70s. I see no reason why that will change this year.
afShort: Low 70s for 4 seasons and hard to see that changing

afComment: One of my favourite players and one who I thought we might see unleashed into the midfield one day. After preseason match-sim vision last year, it looked like 2022 was going to be the year. However, it never eventuated. He did start a few games inside towards the end of the year (13% CBA last 5) but it was only for an intimidation / impact reason then he'd move back to defence. He's averaged 88 before as a defender, which is 16 more than what he's priced at. It's probably enough for him to prove a decent starting option, but at low ownership and coming of a 72 average there's too much risk with that. I'm still holding hope of a midfield switch which would rocket him into calculations, but for now he's just a watch.
afShort: Priced 16 less than his best but needs an unlikley midfield move to be considered

afComment: I've been a fan of the former top 10 pick for a few years now. He has a Fantasy game that I think will see him be a top six defender before his career is done. 80 post bye in 2022 was a good sign, but at age 24, you’d want to see a bit more than that to be confident that this will be the year. The ball will be back there a lot this season so I’ve got a watch on him, but I wouldn’t be brave enough to start him.
afShort: 80 post bye and should see a lot of looks this season which might push him into the 90s

afComment: Talented forward had his most consistent season to date including 92 in last 5, but still not enough to be in discussions in Fantasy.
afShort: Max average 74 in 11 season rules him out

afComment: After returning to the forward line and to form in 2021, McDonald had another injury impacted 2022, with foot surgery cutting his season to 9 games. With the pricing formula, he's priced at 69 which is about best case scenario for him these days, he's not an option in Classic.
afShort: Injury impacted 2023 and now priced at his max of approx 70

afComment: Bonner has had flashes of good scores throughout his career, however he's never put together a full season. Port have many similar off the half back line and will likely be on the fringe again this season. Pass.
afShort: Flashes of good scores but always on the fringe so hard to trust
A handy scorer for a key defender helped by 76% of kick-in duties, but still not enough to make him relevant in Fantasy

afComment: After seeing consistent midfield minutes in his debut season with 31% CBAs in the first half, Jordon took up a wing role in 2023 left vacant by Brayshaw moving to a half back. He played an important role for the team, playing 22 games at an average of 72. However, as a mid-only, 0% CBAs is not what you want for decent Fantasy prospects. Maybe one for the future but not while the Dees' midfield is stacked.
afShort: Moved to a wing which will limit his output while the Dees' mids are stacked
Scores better than most key position players on the back of his seven marks per game, but that’s still not enough to be relevant in Fantasy

afComment: Fiorini has always shown Fantasy ability, right from his debut season where he averaged 112 in 4 games at competition leading points-per-minute. He's since struggled for regular games, with the knock on him being he's not very damaging by foot and a bit one paced. After finished 2021 with 111 in his last 5, there was a chance we’d see him get some more opportunities in 2022. That never happened, and he was forced to apply his trade in the VFL for most of the year where he averaged a whopping 135. The selection and role risk is probably too much to wear, but priced at 72 his CBAs are worth monitoring in the preseason just in case Dew has a change of heart.
afShort: Obvious Fantasy ability with 135 in VFL last year, just out of favour at the Suns which makes him too hard to trust

afComment: The number 7 pick of the 2021 draft came with big wraps, some saying he was the most ready-made after Daicos. After a 91 from 65% CBAs in the AAMI, the wraps looked true. However, he took a while to find his feet, averaging 55 pre bye on low game time. However, he looked more and more comfortable as the season went on, averaging 89 post bye which included a 133. He did this with 28% CBAs, which you expect will skyrocket after the trading of O'Meara and Mitchell opening up plenty of midfield opportunities at the developing Hawks where it's very apparent Sam Mitchell is keen to get as many minutes into his kids as possible. 2nd year breakouts are rare, but when they pay off, they can be competition winning, as per Oliver in 2017 (69 to 102) and Taranto in 2018 (61 to 91). Both of those were in my winning teams but neither were in my starting squad. I think it's best to see how they look and what role they will play in the real stuff and given the extra trades in AFL Fantasy you can use them in Round 2 or 3 if Ward looks the real deal. There's every chance he does.
afShort: 2nd year breakouts are rare but 89 post bye and ample midfield opportunity with Mitchell and O'Meara gone, Ward has every chance to do so

afComment: Goldstein has been a great Fantasy ruckman of the past and it took until his 16th season for him to take a back seat and let a younger ruck take control. He was still used in 66% of North's CBAs post bye, but this was well down from his 78% and 87% of the years prior. I'm not sure how Clarko will run it but even if Goldy remains a key pillar of their ruck setup, I doubt he'll improve on his average now he's 34.
afShort: Roos have begun to look at life after Goldy and I expect his reduced role and scoring to continue in 2023

afComment: Not sure there’s a harder player to get a read on that Jaidyn Stephenson, in real life and in Fantasy. After showing glimpses of his early Collingwood days in his first year at the Roos, which included going over 120 twice, including a monster 150, he took a step back in 2022. He looked a shadow of himself, and failed to reach 70 in half of his games. He finished the season in the backline and while he was found out at times defensively, he provided some run and looked at his best, averaging 86 points in his last 5 with 28% kick-ins. Priced at 71, there’s upside there if he can keep that up in 2023. However, a new coach and game style brings even more unknown to the inconsistent Stephenson, so you’d be a brave coach to consider starting him.
afShort: Looked his best in defence with 86 in last 5 but who knows what Clarko will do with him in 2023

afComment: Jackson arrives at Fremantle after 3 seasons at the Dees where he played forward and backed up Max Gawn in the ruck. He has all the attributes to be a star Fantasy ruck one day, with his follow up work and tackle pressure as good as any at his age. When given the shot to lead the ruck, Jackson gave us a taste what what's to come, with a 125 from 67% CBAs when Gawn was out and his 2 scores over 100 came when he played more than 50% in the ruck. Unfortunately, he's landed at a destination with another gun young ruckman and it's likely he'll play second fiddle to Darcy in the ruck this season. It's been floated that Jackson could be used in a Blicavs-like tall midfielder role, but even if that eventuates this year, I doubt he can push his average up towards the 95-mark needed for him to be a good pick at his price, without having more than 50% of the ruck time. One for the future, but unlikely to be this year.
afShort: Arrives at Freo and will likely play second fiddle again which will delay his inevitable Fantasy breakout
A switch to defence saw Battle have a career best season and put up some nice numbers, but not enough to be a relevant Fantasy defender

afComment: Buddy at his peak was a rare case of being Fantasy relevant as a key forward. He's now 36 though, so despite having the odd big game, you can't rely on him in Fantasy.
afShort: 36-year-old key forward not what you want in Fantasy

afComment: Gun small forward who saw some centre bounce action in 2022 with 31% CBAs, but that was purely as an impact and he drifted back forward after the bounce. He managed 80 post bye which is great for a small forward, but small forwards are never good Fantasy options, even the best small forward in the game.
afShort: One of the best small forwards in the comp but still not one for Fantasy

afComment: Actually beat his Coleman season by 1 point per game, but it shows key forwards are not what you want in your Fantasy team.
afShort: Gun key forward, just not Fantasy relevant
Star key forward, not in Fantasy though

afComment: Elliot Yeo was a Fantasy premium in 2018 averaging 106, making him the 12th highest scorer in the comp. He backed that up with a respectable 102 but then the dreaded OP struck, and he's missed more than 50% of games since and struggled with his output. His body didn't look right last season and he dealt with a number of soft tissue injuries which limited him to 5 games. He was shifted to defence, the position he began his career, for a bit of a spark. It's meant that he's got defender status for 2023 which rockets him into relevance. There are plenty of unknowns which will hopefully be solved in the preseason, such as health and role, but a healthy Yeo playing midfield could push the 90 mark and prove a great starting choice. If he plays defence, I still think he'll outscore his price tag but you'd want him averaging over 90 to be a worthwhile pick. Big preseason watch.
afShort: Defender status and price discount makes him very relevant this season - all comes down to body and role

afComment: Finlayson had a career best season in his first at the Power, boosting his average by 15 points to 71. It was largely on the back of Lycett going down, meaning he was forced to be their primary ruck for the second half of the season. He had 65% CBAs and 71% in his last 5 games, which will return to the normal 10-20% this season which Lycett back. His average will likely follow suit.
afShort: Career high average helped by Lycett going down and will likely return to the 60 mark on his return

afComment: Sidebottom has been a Fantasy gun of the past, but now takes a much lesser role at the Pies, splitting his time between wing and half forward and rarely seeing centre bounces (just 3% in 2022). As a mid-only in 2023, he's unlikely to make an impact if he remains in his outside role. Ignore the discount to career high, as his nine games in the shortened quarters of 2020 don't give an accurate reflection.
afShort: Now a wingman and 32 and not in the role that once made him a Fantasy gun

afComment: Stengle was another feel-good story of 2022, winning a premiership and making the All Australian team after being delisted by the Crows. He also produced career best Fantasy numbers, with a 71 average proving a great buy for those who paid up above rookie price last year. However, small forwards cap out at about the 70 mark for the elite, so it's unlikely we'll see any further growth from here.
afShort: Career best season making the AA team, but small forwards generally cap out at the 70 mark

afComment: The former top 10 pick found a role on the wing in 2022 and played a career high 19 games after just 6 in the prior 2 seasons. He’s never been much of a scorer, even at VFL level, and at mid-only and the arrival of Blake Acres on a wing, O’Brien won’t make an impact in Fantasy this year.
afShort: Found a home on the wing in 2022 but with Acres arriving he might find it hard to hold his spot

afComment: The fan-favourite can score when given the chance, as indicated by his 114 at VFL level last season. However has never played more than 13 games in a season in his 7 year career. Doubt he'll beat that figure this season given the inclusion of Dunkley to the Lions' 22.
afShort: Can score okay but never played more than 13 games in 7 years

afComment: Close has done well to become a regular in a very strong team after being taken as a rookie 3 years ago. He's limited to a role player up forward, so he's not an option in Fantasy.
afShort: Role player who has been great for Geelong but not one for Fantasy

afComment: Sloane unfortunately did his ACL early last season. He's on track for an early year recovery, however at 33 and more time given to the kids, I doubt we'll see him make an impact this year.
afShort: 33 and fresh off an ACL

afComment: Lycett had a shocking 2022, having shoulder surgery in April and then had complications with the recovery. Up until then, he had 3 seasons of being Port's number one ruckman after crossing from West Coast.  He was a consistent low-80s scorer, which was never enough to consider. However, his discount for playing 3 games gets him down to priced at 69, which is 15 points below what we know he can produce. Even with the discount, it's still not enough for me to consider as his upside is capped.
afShort: Returning from a horror season and gets a nice discount, but upside is still capped

afComment: Bailey has something special about him and looks to be a future star of the comp. However, he might be one of those who are better in real life than in Fantasy, showcased by his back-to-back 73 averages, despite having big impact in some games. The Lions need someone like him to take the next step into the midfield, but that might be halted by the arrival of Dunkley. I expect his scoring and CBA role to still increase in 2022, however not enough to take a punt on in Classic.
afShort: Better in real life than Fantasy and Dunkley's arrival might limit him to the forward/mid role

afComment: I've been waiting for a Fisher breakout as Carlton have used him in centre bounces throughout his career and he's always spoken of highly by key members of the team. However, the breakout is yet to eventuate and he played just 13 games last season without making much of an impact. With the Blues' 22 getting stronger, I think he might struggle again in 2023.
afShort: Just 13 games last season and might struggle again

afComment: Key forward whose development surprised me last season as he started to take over some games. His average of 70 is great for a key forward, and given he’s just 24 he could improve again. However, I doubt it will ever be enough to make an impact in Fantasy.
afShort: Strong season by the key forward but scoring will be capped

afComment: Baker does a bit of everything for the Tigers, playing forward, back and even in the middle. He can excel at all of them and if we know he was going to remain as a defender or a mid then we might be able to trust him in Fantasy. However, his role is too hard to read and given his likely very low ownership numbers, he's too much of a risk to consider in Fantasy.
afShort: He can play but too hard to predict what role he will play week-to-week

afComment: Became an important role player for the Blues. He's a bit of a fix-it player and even spent some time in the ruck, attending 14% of CBAs. This brings about a bump in scoring, but not enough to consider in Fantasy.
afShort: Role player for the Blues not in Fantasy calculations

afComment: Off-season surgery meant the former first rounder played just 10 games last season after 21 the year prior. Hinkley has flagged midfield time for him in 2022, which unsurprisingly didn’t eventuate. Has a nice Fantasy game to him when on song and may become relevant again in the future, but I doubt that will be this season.
afShort: Just 10 games last year and didn't do a heap in the reserves
Genuine role player in defence who has capped out at the 70 mark

afComment: Chapman has showed great signs in his first two seasons and certainly looks like one for the future. There’s talk of him one day moving to a wing or even inside, but for now it looks like he’ll be applying his craft as a defender. While he certainly has the attributes to score, he’s behind Young and Ryan for distribution and it’s likely he’ll have another year in the 70/80s before we see him take the next step.
afShort: Very impressive first 2 seasons but behind the pecking order in defence so will need to wait before the breakout

afComment: Williams has been disappointing since his move to the Blues - for Carlton fans and Fantasy coaches. He was a popular mid-priced pick in 2021 following a change of clubs for more midfield time after averaging 106 in the second half of 2019 in a midfield role. After string of poor performances, he was banished from the midfield and played in defence. That defence role continued to last season before he badly injured his calf, missing the majority of the season. He enters 2023 priced at 69 which is about 15 less than what he can produce in a defensive role and 30 less in a midfield role. I think his midfield role is over, but I'm still not discounting him to produce decent numbers this year in defence. A preseason watch if you can do it to yourself again.
afShort: Calf injury ruined 2022 but now priced at 69 and I've overrated him in the past but I think he can produce on that price

afComment: Star forward, however has only been around the mid-60 mark in Fantasy across his career. It's about all you can expect from a small forward and that seems to be about his limit.
afShort: Star small forward but scoring limited to sub-70

afComment: McGovern will be looking to bounce back after a few disappointing seasons. He's always been a much better player in real life than in Fantasy, demonstrated by his career best season of 80 points per game, so he's not an option in Fantasy.
afShort: Hopefully stays on the park this year but even at his best hasn't been much of a Fantasy player

afComment: After averaging 80 in the last 5 games of 2021 and 107 in the AAMI, it looked like McInerney was going to breakout last season and that the wing/half back role left vacent by Jordan Dawson. However, he was one of the few young Swans who didn't improve, averaging just 66 for the year. The breakout may come this season, but at mid-only and lack of CBAs (3% last season compared to 13% in 2021), he's not worth taking the punt on in Fantasy.
afShort: Let a few down last year and now only available in the midfield

afComment: So far in his career, Scott has played wing, a half forward, as a tagger and then finally settled as a defender in 2023 where he can career highs in scoring and games played. He looks like he could become a decent player, but who knows what Clarko will do and Scott's role and position in the team are unknown.
afShort: Career high in scoring and games played after shifting to defence, but not what how Clarko will use him in 2023

afComment: The former number 11 pick has been a regular for the Swans since his second season, playing over 21 games per season since. I thought he was a breakout candidate in 2020 after averaging 90 points in his final five games of 2019, however he's stagnated from there. This is on the back of a big drop in CBAs, where he took 69% in the first half of 2020 yet only 2% in the second half of 2022. Looks like the new Swans’ youngsters have overtaken him and it’s likely he’ll remain in defence.
afShort: Pushed out of the midfield which reduces his upside

afComment: Wright has been great for the Bombers since arriving in 2021, topped off by his B&F win last year. However, a 69 average in a B&F year shows you how capped key forwards are for Fantasy scoring.
afShort: 69 average in a B&F year shows you how capped key forwards are for Fantasy scoring

afComment: Setterfield has shown promise throughout his career, from being a top five pick, to big NEAFL numbers, to averaging 100 in the second half of 2020 with decent CBA numbers. However, he struggled for consistency and games at the Blues, not reaching 70 in either season despite averaging 107 at VFL level. He now finds himself at the Bombers who are crying out for a tall midfielder and there's a chance he steps right in and plays his preferred role. As a mid-only option, it's too risky to take a punt on him priced at 69. But I have a feeling he'll beat that price by a fair bit.
afShort: Hopefully gets more inside opportunity at the Dons

afComment: Bowes was a prolific midfielder in juniors, averaging 118 points in the NAB League which saw him be a top 10 pick at the Suns. He played predominantly in defence at AFL level looked to breakout as a Fantasy gun, averaging 95 in the first half of 2021, taking the majority of the kick-ins in that time. He then injured his hamstring and played a less prominent role when he returned and finished the year with an 81 average. That made him a potential underpriced option last season, before shoulder surgery in the preseason ruled him out for the first 4 months of the year. From there things got a bit weird. He played just the 5 games and spend a lot of time in the VFL, where he averaged 92. He was then offloaded to Geelong in what will go down as the worst trade in history, with him and pick 7 going to Geelong for a future 3rd pick #salarydump. Geelong said they were keen to land him, but it's unknown if they wanted him of the pick 7 attached. He struggled for games at the Suns and it will be tougher to break into the reigning premiers' 22, but if he is named in Round 1 and performs in the preseason, he's still the talented player who averaged mid-90s for a large part of 2021.
afShort: Might find it hard for opportunity at the Cats but has displayed a Fantasy game in the past so remains a preseason watch

afComment: Now established as the Cats’ number 1 ruck, but a career best of 86 and fresh off a 68, he’s not going to be the ruck you want to own in Fantasy.
afShort: Now 32 and fresh off a 68 with no 100s

afComment: The mature aged recruit, who came into the AFL with some great numbers in the SANFL (109 average in 2018), hasn’t missed a beat since arriving at the Saints, only missing 3 games in 4 years. His role is different to when he was in the SANFL, he plays more of a defensive role at the Saints which limits his value in Fantasy.
afShort: A consistent role player at the Saints

afComment: The 2021 SSP selection burst onto the scene in a terrific role off a half back flank, finishing his first season averaging 70. However, the momentum was halted with a stress fracture in the preseason practice match, delaying his start to the 2022 season. He managed 9 matches at an average of 58, well down on his debut season. His VFL numbers weren’t great either, so I think he struggled with the delayed start. He’ll be better in 2023 with a full preseason, but priced at 68, he’s not worth the risk.
afShort: Disappointing 2022 after promising debut season, should bounce back

afComment: After a career best 81 in 2021, Hardwick returned to the 60-70 type defender in 2022. He did average 82 post bye when his kick-ins went from 28% to 39%, but with so many distributors at the Hawks, including Sicily, Bramble and Scrimshaw, I think he will remain in this range from now on, unless something happens to Sicily as it did in 2021.
afShort: Regressed with Sicily back but post bye showed he can still go 80+

afComment: If you had asked me after his 2nd season where Clark would be heading into his 6th, I would've said he'd be a top 6 defender by now and if not defender, then he'd certainly have midfield status. The former top 10 pick averaged 84 in the second half of his 2nd season and was heavily involved in centre bounces. He hasn't come on from there, averaging 79, 73 and 54 in the 3 years since and seen less and less time in the midfield. He’s also had a shocking run of luck, none more so than last season. He had shoulder surgery after a preseason match when he was getting CBAs and looking good, forcing him to miss the first 13 rounds and then had surgery again on a nasal fracture from a sickening clash in Round 16. He’s due for some luck and a chance in coach might see him finally unleashed into the midfield. Unfortunately he’s not priced at the 54 he averaged last season due to playing less than 10 games but he remains a preseason role watch priced at 68.
afShort: Due for some luck and has the ability so a big role watch in the preseason

afComment: Noble has become a regular in defence for the Pies after being picked up in the mid-season draft of 2019. He's a 70-75 guy, which is respectable but not enough to be relevant in Fantasy.
afShort: 70-75 guy which is not enough to be relevant in Fantasy

afComment: Flynn is part of the ruck merry-go-round at the Giants and managed 24 games in the past 2 seasons, averaging around the 70 mark. He's displayed some talent, I just don't want to deal with the GWS rucks.
afShort: Looks good when playing but can't trust the Giants ruck setup

afComment: Hickey has been a sensational get by the Swans. However, he still only manages to rank 14th amongst rucks for average and at 32, it’s hard to see that average increasing.
afShort: At 32 unlikley to be a top 10 ruck
32-year-old key forward who tops out at the 70 mark

afComment: McIntosh has a career high average of 70 heading into his 11th season. His outside role limits him from pushing up to triple figures and becoming a relevant Fantasy option.
afShort: Outside wing with mid-only not what you want

afComment: Averaged 80 post bye when he took a more prominent role with McGovern out, but even if he scores that for the season he won't be a Fantasy relevant option.
afShort: Key defender who got a bump with McGovern out

afComment: ANB is a genuine role player in the Melbourne forward line. Very valuable for the Dees, not so much for Fantasy.
afShort: Very valuable for the Dees, not so much for Fantasy

afComment: One of the best young defenders in the comp and that became well known in 2022 when he took out All Australian honours. At just 23, he'll improve his reputation again in 2023, however he still won't be Fantasy relevant.
afShort: Gun young key defender but not one for Fantasy

afComment: Ladhams moved to Sydney for more opportunities, however didn't get them, playing just the 11 games for the season. He's shown he can score well in the sole ruck role and averaged 102 in the VFL last year, but Hickey still appears the main man at the Swans and I doubt we'll see Ladhams push his average at AFL level up to the 90 mark required.
afShort: Still behind Hickey and needs to be the sole ruck to score

afComment: Seedsman had a career best season on a wing in 2021 but sadly hasn’t played since due to concussion. He’s now on the rookie list and we’ve had no indication that he’ll play again. Even if he does play and with his discount, he’s still a pass as a mid-only.
afShort: Dealing with concussion issues and now on the inactive list

afComment: An ankle injured and stress fracture in his foot meant that Sheed played just 1 game last season. He gets a 27% discount which means he enters 2023 priced at 67. He’s never been a damaging Fantasy player, highlighted by his 91 average from 66% CBAs in 2021, however at that price he must be considered. In his 1 game in 2022, he had 88% CBAs, which is an indication Simpson wants to use him as an inside mid, rather than the wing/half forward role he’s played for a lot of his career. If he plays an inside role in 2023, he can certainly push 90 again which would make him a worthwhile mid-priced selection. Keep an eye on his CBAs in the preseason for confirmation.
afShort: Big discount after 1 game last year and if he can keep those CBAs up he can bounce back to the 90s

afComment: After becoming a regular in the Swans' backline, Cunningham was limited to just 9 games in 2022 due to an abdominal injury and form. I had some decent homes for him to fill the void left by Dawson, given his booming kick and 27% KI rate in the last 5 games of 2021, however Blakey ended up taking that slack. With 9 games he only gets a 3% discount to his better 2021 average of 68, so he's not the value to take on the risk of a breakout this year anyway.
afShort: Still has potential but just 9 games last year and 0% KI not a good sign

afComment: Farrell is known for his booming left foot and Port Adelaide like to use that weapon on the wing and forward of the ball to create deep opportunities. He returned from an ACL in 2022 and had a career best Fantasy season, averaging 67. You’d think he’ll see more opportunity in 2023 with Amon leaving on a wing, but as a mid-only option, you can’t have him in Fantasy.
afShort: Could see more opportunity with Amon leaving, but not as a mid-only option

afComment: Jiath broke out in 2022, bumping his average by 27 points to finish with 72. He backed it up with a 67 which suggests that 70-mark is about his limit. He has even more impact in real life with his intercept ability being as good as any in the comp.
