It's hard to rely on intercept defenders in Fantasy and for that reason, it's hard to see Jiath coming into the Fantasy relevance conversation again.
afShort: The 70-mark appears his limit and it's hard to rely on intercept defenders in Fantasy
Has talent but hovered around the 60-mark for his 6 seasons in the AFL

afComment: A tall forward who scores his best when playing ruck, however doesn’t like playing there. English will take the lion share anywhere so Lobb’s ruck time is limited. Pass.
afShort: Scores okay in the ruck but will spend most his time forward now at the Dogs

afComment: After sitting behind Goldstein for many years, Xerri finally got his chance in 2022, playing 12 matches at 50% CBAs. He looked good at time too, with his contested marking and follow-up work a feature. Goldy is still around and I'm not sure how Clarko will play it, but with Coleman-Jones also there I doubt we'll see much more than the 50% ruck time Xerri got last season. He has shown he can dominate at the VFL level, averaging 105 in 2021, I just think we'll Goldy gone before we see Xerri hit his straps at AFL level.
afShort: Got his chance in 2022 but it's crowded in the rucks at North so hard to see him increasing

afComment: After just 6 games in his second season, Stephens looked more like the impressive first year player he was to play 15 games on a wing for the Swans. The former top 5 pick may one day move into the midfield, but as a mid-only who gets 0% CBAs, there's not enough upside to select him this season.
afShort: Has potential but mid-only and 0% CBAs makes it tough
A decent scorer in the past, Dumont is a depth player for Port and not one to consider

afComment: Howe's 2020 season is an obvious anomaly, given it's his only one over 90 in 12 seasons. The short quarters and 4 matches may have had something to do with it, but he did look unstoppable in those 4 games. Since then, he has resumed more of a shutdown role on an opposition dangerous forward. He's also lost a lot of kicks to Daicos and even Maynard and Quaynor who have stepped up the last 2. Ignore the discount to career high, he's not that Fantasy player anymore.
afShort: Ignore the discount to career high, he plays a more defensive role nowadays

afComment: Guthrie played a career high 21 games for Geelong in 2022, cementing his spot in the team and winning a premiership. He had some nice scoring games when Geelong switched to a kick-mark play and when Stewart was missing, but I doubt he’ll ever average enough to be considered in AFL Fantasy.
afShort: Now a regular for the Cats but not one for Fantasy

afComment: A PCL injury kept Pittonet to 8 games in 2022. During that time, De Koning took over as number 1 ruck and looked great, so I'm not sure how much ruck Pittonet will play in 2023.
afShort: Might have lost the number 1 spot to De Koning which will make it tough
Struggled for games since being drafted and scoring to date in the AFL hasn't been great

afComment: A career best year in defence from the 24-year-old even had some calling for All Australian. A 66 average is about what to expect from decent key defenders, so he's not one for Fantasy.
afShort: 66 in a close-to-All Australian year

afComment: Zak Jones has progressed from a half back flanker to a wingman to an inside midfielder, where he provided something different to the plethora of inside mids (Steele, Ross, Brad Crouch). He played the role pretty well in 2021, averaging 89 highlighted by a 151 and 123 in consecutive weeks. He never hit those heights last season though, averaging 65 from diminishing CBAs after taking indefinite leave to start the season. Not sure what role Ross Lyon will give him but if it’s a 50%+ CBA one like 2020 and 2021 then he could certainly bump his average by 20 and provide some value as a starting squad member. However, there are far safer selections out there than Jones.
afShort: Looking to bounce back from 65 in an interrupted year after back-to-back 89s

afComment: Sharman has an impressive set of hands, but has only played 13 games since being taken in the 2021 mid-season draft. Plays as a 3rd tall and tried in defence, but haven’t seen enough to think he’s going to be a Fantasy option, especially at that price.
afShort: Still finding his feet at AFL level

afComment: Not many half back flankers are taken as a top four pick, so Ash obviously has the talent. He showed some of that talent in 2021, particularly in the first half of the season when he had kick-in duties and averaged 88 points per game - highlighted by a 146 against the Pies. In an odd shift by Leon Cameron, he's since been playing in the midfield, at times as a tagger, a wingman and others just as a pure mid ahead of the more proven types. That means he's got midfield only status, ruling him out of selection in Fantasy. I imagine he'll move back to half back this season and get defender status to hopefully one day become the stud defender expected of him on draft night.
afShort: Hopefully moves his natural half back position
Just 7 games from the key defender in 2022

afComment: Highly rated small defender who has become a regular for the Lions, often taking the opposition's number one medium forward. It's not a role for producing decent Fantasy scores though and he's not relevant this season.
afShort: Very good small defender but not a scorer

afComment: Taylor has become a regular for the Roos and has a bit about him. I think he'll become a good player, however his role (defensive half forward) will keep him around the 60 mark when playing.
afShort: Defensive half forward role will keep him around the 60 mark
Gun pressure forward for Fremantle, not the role for Fantasy scoring though

afComment: A defensive midfielder who saw 1% CBAs for the season after being a staple there for over 10 years. With Hawks looking to give time to their kids, he’s moved to the Roos where he will reunite with Clarko. I do think he’ll play more of an off-field leadership role, but if Clarko does give him high CBAs in the preseason, he could be an interesting option in the forward line.
afShort: Likely to take a step back at the Roos but still worth seeing how it plays out given price and position

afComment: After a fairy-tale debut and then being the most popular pick in Fantasy in 2020, Pickett has found himself on the wing at the Tigers in a very team-first role. With mid-only status and coming off a 66 average, it’s hard to make a case for him.
afShort: Mid-only status and coming off a 66

afComment: The former number one draft pick returned from an ACL last season to play all 24 games, averaging 62 points. So far in his career, he's been more of an impact player than an accumulator, which is never a great thing for Fantasy scoring. We've all been waiting for him to pop and be the explosive, goal kicking mid the Lions are crying out for. Coming back from a knee is never smooth sailing, so we can excuse him for his low output in 2022. However, the fact that his scoring and CBAs reduces as the year went on isn't a great sign. Dunkley arriving will take some CBAs away, but I still think they need to allocate a spot for one of Bailey, Rayner and Zorko, so I still expect him to get a small bump in midfield minutes. That's not enough to make him relevant in Fantasy though based on his output to date.
afShort: Still waiting for the breakout and CBAs reducing as the season went on isn't a good sign
4 uninterrupted seasons at the Lions and low-60s is what we can expect

afComment: Saw some opportunity with the depleted West Coast team last season, playing 18 games for a career high 64. Showed enough signs to suggest he might stay in when they’re full strength. I can’t see him ever been a prominent scorer though.
afShort: Might find it tougher with a full strength West Coast

afComment: Lukosius returned to the forward-line in 2022 after looking great as a running defender the year prior. His Fantasy output felt it, dropping 22 points per game. If he remains a forward, then you can rule him out of Fantasy calculations. If he moves back to defence, where he showed shades of a young Lachie Whitfield, averaging 88 with his elite kick and hunger for the ball, then he needs to be considered priced at 64.
afShort: Flopped in his return to the forward-line and can bounce back if he moves back to defence

afComment: Holmes had a fantastic 2nd season, taking a prominent role on a wing and even spent some time inside for the eventual premiers. His scoring didn’t reflect his impact, but his 74 post bye and 81 last 5 was about right. I think he can reproduce that level in year 3, which is not enough to consider as a mid-only.
afShort: Great season but even his 85 in last 5 isn't enough to consider as mid-only

afComment: At his peak, Walters could be a damaging midfielder, as demonstrated by his adjusted 104 points per game to start the 2020 season (from 64% of CBAs). However, with Serong and Brayshaw stepping up, the 32-year-old is now used solely as a small forward (1% CBAs in 2022). He's not worth considering.
afShort: Now a pure small forward with 0% CBAs

afComment: Small lockdown defender returned from an ACL to play 9 games in 2022 before doing it again. We wish him all the best in recovery.
afShort: ACL for the second time last season

afComment: After a very impressive first season, Bowey looked like he was going to take another step with a 125 in Round 2. While he maintained the role, he didn’t reproduce that output and eventually found himself out of the side towards the end of the season. He’s showed enough to suggest he’s going to be a gun in the future, but he’s behind a few at the Dees so it won’t be for a few years yet.
afShort: Was out of the side at the end of the season and behind a few at the Dees for usage

afComment: An intercept defender was forced to play more of a lockdown role with all the injuries at the Blues. He was a fringe player before then and I imagine him to be on the edge again this season.
afShort: Got opportunity with all the injuries last year but might struggle now

afComment: Mitch Lewis announced himself in 2022 as a star key forward of the comp. But even the best key forwards cap out at the 70 mark, so that's about max for him.
afShort: Gun key forward but limited in Fantasy
Become a regular but career best of just 70 in 11 seasons rules him out

afComment: Stringer had a disappointing season after a career best 2021. A groin injury in the preseason saw his midfield minutes drop from 69% CBAs the year prior to 37%, but even when he was in there, he looked far from the 94-averaging player from the second half of 2021. Both Worsfold and Rutten liked using him in the middle but with a new coach, Stringer’s role is up in the air. As is his fitness, which is also never stable. He’s a pass for me.
afShort: Disappointing 2022 after a career best 2021 - form, fitness and role too hard to predict
Small forward that has missed a lot of footy due to various injuries

afComment: Was very impressive in his debut season, averaging 63 from a wing but kept getting better as the year went on. Mid-only wingmen aren't are great combo in Fantasy, add in a 2nd year player and it's a no for me, but hopefully he goes on with it.
afShort: Impressive wingman with a bright future but mid-only rules him out

afComment: Sparrow has been getting midfield opportunities in a strong midfield since his debut. The scoring hasn't followed suit, averaging 63 from 32% CBAs. He's obviously highly rated, however he'll likely continue in a forward-mid role for the time being while the big boys are still there, and I doubt we will see his scoring spike much more than 70. Pass.
afShort: Mid-forward who gets CBAs but yet to show a scoring game

afComment: Ross has shown a bit when given the opportunity and dominated at reserve level (116 average from 3 games in 2021 and 99 in 2022) so I think he's got potential to belong at AFL level at one point. However, as a Fantasy option, he's not a very attractive one at that price, mid-only and with Taranto and Hopper entering the fold.
afShort: Going to find it hard with Taranto and Hopper

afComment: A crazy debut season for JHF. Outside of all the noise, I thought he showed more than enough on field in a struggling side and so much going on off field. He saw 40% CBAs in his first year which I doubt he'll meet at Port given their more seasoned midfield group. He's a pass for me, but as we know about 2nd year breakouts, it's not too late to jump on after 2 or 3 rounds if they look the real deal.
afShort: Doubt he'll see the 40% CBAs at Port, but should get more looks in a stronger team

afComment: Sholl finished 2020 with an adjusted 110 and 84 and was the designated kicker at the Crows. He then had a 102, 103 and 130 in his first five games of 2021 and looked to be a serious player of the future. It all went downhill from there and Sholl has struggled for senior opportunities since. I've seen enough to believe he'll be a player in the future, but as a midfield only option in Fantasy he's not an option this year.
afShort: Wing with mid-only status yet to cement his spot in the team

afComment: Curnow signed a 1 year contract after not playing a game in 2022. The much loved veteran provides great leadership and depth to the Blues, but I doubt the 33-year-old will be in their best 22 this season.
afShort: No games last year and could be the same again

afComment: Darling missed the entire preseason which meant he had a slow start to 2022, averaging 60 in the first half. This increased to 69 in his last 5, which is a more accurate reflection of where he's been the past 5 seasons. I expect him to be around that mark in 2023, which is well below the level required to be Fantasy relevant.
afShort: 69 in last 5 is about what to expect
34-year-old key forward isn't what you want in your Fantasy side

afComment: With Pittonet out with injury for a lot of 2022, De Koning got his chance, playing 19 games for the season at 70% CBAs. He impressed with his leap and marking ability, however didn't make much of an impact in Fantasy scoring, averaging 62 for the year. He's never been much of a scorer though, even in juniors (69), VFL (59) and in the second half of 2021 when he did get a clear run at it with 76% CBAs (63). He should show progress with natural improvement, however it won't be enough to warrant starting with him in Classic.
afShort: Now the number 1 ruck but never been a Fantasy scorer

afComment: Hollands finally got his chance in Round 19 after being drafted pick 7 two years prior and didn't disappoint. He played on a wing and certainly didn't look out of place, even scoring 118 in one game. He's only available in the midfield this year which dampens any chance of him making an impact in Fantasy this season. But one for the future if he ever moves inside or gets forward status.
afShort: Looked great in 5 games but mid-only rules him out this year

afComment: Schoenberg has slowly increased his midfield role, from 18% CBAs in 2020, 35% in 2021, 38% in the first half of 2022 and then 56% to finish. However, his scoring output hasn't chanced, hovering around the 60 mark throughout. He's highly rated at the Crows and will likely be part of their main midfield brigade in 2023 alongside Laird and Berry, but until we see a scoring ceiling, he's going to be irrelevant in Fantasy.
afShort: Getting more looks in the middle but scoring is yet to pop
The star key forward of the future will miss the start of the season with a shoulder reconstruction
Debuted in 2022 and looked great on a wing, but now as mid-only won't make a Fantasy impact this year

afComment: A 2021 mid-season draftee saw some midfield opportunities in 2022 given the injuries to their prime moves and averaged 62 points. With most of the cattle coming back, I doubt he'll see those chances again and he's not an option in Fantasy.
afShort: Might struggle for opportunities in a full strength West Coast team

afComment: The Irishman is a favourite of Mitchells, who used his strong tackle ability in centre bounces, attending 42% for the season. Like fellow Irishmen, he'll continue to get better, but a 62 average last season indicates he's not going to be a Fantasy scorer.
afShort: Used in centre bounces last year but average remained modest
Fallen out of favour at the Suns after being the eighth highest averaging forward in 2019

afComment: Impey dropped 24 points from his 2021 average, despite his favourable defender role. Even if he bounces back to the mid-80s, the upside isn't worth it.
afShort: Down year for the role player
Key forward who scores best when rucking (111 from 74% CBAs), but he won’t be doing much of that at the Pies
Key position player who has struggled for games at multiple clubs and I doubt it will change at a 3rd
A shutdown medium defender was used on a wing at times in 2022, but even that didn’t yield decent scores

afComment: Hobbs looked terrific in a limited role in his debut season. He finished with an average of 61 from 15% CBAs, but displayed a Fantasy game to him with a score of 95. It will be interesting to see what role Scott has for the natural midfielder, given he spent the majority of his time up forward last year. If he can get his CBAs up to 30%, along with natural second year progression, we should see a nice bump in scoring from the former pick 13. I doubt that jump will be enough to make him a worthwhile selection, but forward status does keep him on the radar.
afShort: Will hope to spend more time in the middle where he showed enough to suggest he'll be a player of the future

afComment: The Carlton swingman still hasn't been able to get a good run at footy since moving from Adelaide. He looked to have settled as an intercept defender and looked great in the preseason, scoring 89 from limited game time in the AAMI. However, a bad hamstring injury in Round 2 saw him miss the next 16 matches, something that has seemed to have happened to him throughout his career. He returned to average 73 in the same role in the last 5 games, taking 28% of the kick-ins. If he can have a decent run at it, I think he can average 75-80, which is a nice bump from his price of 61, but not enough to consider starting with.
afShort: Injury prone swingman has settled into an intercept role and should push the 75-80 mark this year if fit

afComment: After moving to defence in 2021, Laverde has become a regular for the Bombers, playing every game since. His scoring output has remained in the high 50s / low 60s mark, so he remains irrelevant in Fantasy.
afShort: Key defender with limited scoring

afComment: After just 4 games in 6 seasons, Hinge played 17 in 2022 as a tall wingman and mobile defender. He showed some nice flashes, but with an average of 61 and SANFL average of 74, I doubt he’ll come into Fantasy relevance.
afShort: Got his chance on a wing and half back but scoring seems limited
Scores okay for a small forward but limited in that role

afComment: After having one of the most Fantasy-friendly roles in 2021 where he did what he wanted in the backline to average 100, Ziebell regressed hard in 2022 as he moved to a role in the forward line. He's shown he can play multiple roles across the ground and there's no doubting his commitment to the team, but at 32, I think we've seen the best of him in real life and in Fantasy.
afShort: Not sure what role Clarko will give him but it won't be the one from 2021 so ignore the discount

afComment: It took until Round 23 for Goater to debut but when he did he looked great, using his athletic rebounding skills to score 83. He's one we wish didn't debut so he'd be basement price this season, instead he's priced at a 27% discount to that score to be 61. It's a bit of an awkward price and one I wouldn't be willing to spend unless we see a few big scores in the preseason.
afShort: Looked great in his 1 game but unfortunately that means he's pretty expensive for a 1 game player

afComment: From such a promising start, Day has had a frustrating few years in the AFL. The lightly-built former first round pick looked at home in his debut season, averaging 75 through 11 matches and was incredibly composed under pressure. We didn't see much of him in his second season due to injury, however he did have one big game with 103 points. I was hopeful for a big leap last season but it never happened, missing the first 2 rounds for fitness and then averaging just 61 points for the remainder. Hawthorn's defence is very stacked for distribution (Sicily, Scrimshaw, Jiath, Bramble) and Day took a backseat. I'm hoping with a full preseason under his belt, Day can return to form and look more like the player I had earmarked to one day be a top 6 defender.
afShort: Hoping for a bounce back after a few down seasons following a promising debut

afComment: The 31-year-old still has a knack of kicking goals, averaging 2 in return from playing just the 1 game the year prior. He's now at the Lions where he should see more looks than he did at the struggling Hawks, but at his age and role I'd say he'll top out around the 70 mark.
afShort: Should see more looks at the Lions but doubt he'll average much over 70
Scoring limited in the small forward role
18 matches after being delisted was impressive but might find it tough now full strength
Returned from a broken leg to play 20 matches but he’s a shutdown defender

afComment: A sickening ankle injury cut his season to 12 games. Sounds like he should be fine for Round 1. Highly rated, a beautiful kick and found his spot on a half back flank, it’s just hard to see him becoming a relevant Fantasy player this season.
afShort: Returning from an ankle injury and might need time before he hits his straps

afComment: The number 9 pick of the 2020 draft has played an impressive 38 games in his first 2 seasons, providing some x-factor around goal and in the air. He’s been tested in the middle at times and looked comfortable, scoring his season high 82 when he had 67% CBAs. The Bombers have a few who run through there, but I think we’ll see more of Perkins in 2023. He’s not cheap enough for me to consider, but with his forward status he’s worth keeping an eye on.
afShort: A watch on his CBAs in preseason as he looks a player and forward status makes him relevant

afComment: For a key position player, Riccardi's marking ability means he is capable of some decent Fantasy scoring. However, he was used more as a forward last year where he doesn’t score as well. Still yet to lock down a position in their best 22, he’s not an option this season.
afShort: Still yet to lock down a position in their best 22

afComment: A fringe midfielder had every chance to succeed in his 4th season given the injuries at West Coast, however he failed to deliver, averaging 59 from 44% CBAs. He might struggle for games with a healthy list this season.
afShort: Yet to look a scorer and might struggle with stars returning

afComment: Higgins has always been on the radar of Fantasy coaches following his monster junior scores which were likened to Fantasy great Tom Rockliff. After being limited to a small forward role with minimal Fantasy impact at Richmond, he arrived at the Saints at the end of 2020 and was flagged for some midfield opportunities, music to all Fantasy coaches' ears. However, this has never eventuated, and he didn’t have a single CBA last year. He's always worth monitoring, but there's no way you can start with him based on what we’ve seen.
afShort: The junior stud has been limited to a small forward role at AFL level and hard to see that changing

afComment: Draper finally has a full run at it in 2022, playing all 22 matches after a tough run of injuries and getting himself AFL ready. However, he only managed 59 points from 69% CBAs. What's more disappointing is his highest score being just the 88 points. Judging from his scoring to date, it's hard to see him making an impact in Fantasy.
afShort: First full season but didn't show enough of a Fantasy game

afComment: Rankine finds himself at Adelaide after 3 years at Gold Coast where he established himself as a dangerous small forward. There's talk of him running through the middle for the Crows, who do lack a bit of excitement amongst Laird, Berry, Crouch and Schoenberg, but I can't see him suddenly bursting into Fantasy relevance.
afShort: Talk of mid-time at the Crows, but I'll have to see it to believe it

afComment: Doedee has been a decent scorer for a tall defender on the back of his elite intercept marking ability, averaging over 70 twice from 2018 to 2020. He has been a bit down the last 2 seasons and took a back seat to Jordan Dawson last year, dropping his average to 59. That’s 15 points below his best, but with Dawson still there I doubt he’ll get back to the 70s.
afShort: Dropped his scoring with Dawson taking over

afComment: Zurhaar is a bash and crash forward who is a powerful athlete and shares some (very minor) similarities with Petracca. A move to the midfield could be on the cards one day, but I don't think it will be anytime soon so he's not an option in Fantasy.
afShort: Strong forward who unless the unlikely midfield move happens, will remain around the 60-mark
Very exciting player to watch, but like most of his team mates, doesn't generate a lot of points under the current game style

afComment: Wehr was recruited as a mature age running defender to fill the void of Heath Shaw retiring and Zac Williams' departure. He finally got his chance in 2022 and was used on a wing, where his neat kicking skills were on display. In terms of Fantasy though, he's now a mid-only with an awkward price point, so he's not relevant in the game this season.
afShort: Debuted as a wingman but now mid-only at an awkward price
His 71 in 2020 was an outlier, expect 50-50 from the gun small forward going forward

afComment: Played 12 matches and proved to be a strong hit-out ruckman, but there is a bit of competition there at Hawks with Lynch and Meek vying for the number 1 role.
afShort: Bit of competition there at Hawks with Lynch and Meek vying for the number 1 role

afComment: Haynes had one of his worst outputs in 2022, in both real life and in Fantasy. It's always hard to rely on defenders who generate a lot of their possessions through intercepts as they don't always come and often the opposition tries to lead them away from the ball. He was also thrown forward at times. He's only 30, so he should be able to bounce back in the right role and system. His best is a long way off what he's priced at, but I wouldn't be buying into that value on what I saw last year.
afShort: A long way off his best in 2023 but always hard to rely on interceptors
General defender who doesn't generate enough Fantasy points to be relevant

afComment: After 9 games in 3 seasons, West finally got his chance in 2022 and calved out a nice role as a small pressure forward. West was a highly touted inside midfielder as a junior, but with the depth of the midfield at the Dogs, he looks like he's going to continue in the forward role. While that's the case, he won't be a factor in Fantasy.
afShort: Found a spot as a small forward but unlikely he'll move into the middle anytime soon

afComment: Cox played 18 games last season in an important forward/ruck role and looked a favourite of McRaes. With McStay arriving, I think he'll take that forward/ruck role and we might not see as much of Cox in 2023.
afShort: McStay might take the forward/ruck role and we won't see as much of Cox

afComment: Former pick 8 is now at North where he'll likley play as a shut down defender. Outside of his under 18s season where he had a run in the midfield, he hasn't shown enough to suggest he's going to be a Fantasy option
afShort: New team, same shut down role

afComment: Super impressive debut season from the speedy midfielder. He played a few roles, from forward, wing and even inside mid, and looked good in all. Mid-only this year rules him out, but one to watch for the future.
afShort: Looks a player of the future but mid-only rules him out this year
A broken foot kept Ceglar to 2 games at his new club, but Stanley was the preferred in finals so he might find it tough again
32, small forward for a struggling team - not what you want to see in your team

afComment: Long has been around for a while without cementing himself in the 22 at St Kilda. He played a career high 18 games last season and now finds himself on the Gold Coast. He finished the season at half back and looked really damaging with his ball use and straight line running, averaging 82 in his last 5. He’s been earmarked for the same role at the Suns where I think that 80 average is achievable over a full season. Priced at 58, it’s almost enough to be a decent mid-priced starting squad selection for some cash gen and scoring in the early rounds. Keep an eye on him in the preseason.
afShort: A move to GC and if he can keep the role and scoring from his last 5, he could be a decent mid-priced defender
Genuine role player up forward for the Suns
Moved back to the forward line after a year on the wing explains the drop in scoring
32 years old and hasn't played a full season in 6 years, Fantasy days are over

afComment: Back-to-back 20 game seasons, Webster shows flashes of decent Fantasy scoring when he gets on the end of a few plus-sixes in the backline, however he's never taken it to the next level and become a decent Fantasy option.
afShort: Role player in defence for the Saints

afComment: After looking the goods in his debut season, Bianco played 10 games in his second, reducing his average by 16 points to 45. His average was impacted by being the sub on a few occasions but unfortunately he's priced at his 2021 average as he played less than 10 H&A games. Regardless, he's not going to be a Fantasy option until/if he ever moves into a full-time mid role.
afShort: Still yet to cement his spot in the Pies' 22
Lock-down defender didn't see a bump at the Roos despite more ball being back there

afComment: Williams has always teased with a bit of a Fantasy game about him, averaging 80 in 2 of his 5 seasons while playing as a defender. His role was more defensive last year than it was in the past, and it resulted in a 9-point reduction in scoring. He could return to scores in the 80s, however it's unlikely based on 3 of his last 4 seasons.
afShort: Has potential and scored well in the past, but 3 of last 4 low seasons makes it tough
Talented medium forward who doesn't look a scorer

afComment: Flanders was taken pick 11 in the 2019 draft alongside fellow Suns' top draftees Rowell and Anderson. However, he's certainly yet to make as much of an impact as those other two picks. He dominated at reserve level, averaging 104 points, so the talent is still there. He played just 9 game in 2022, which means he's priced at a 3% discount to his 2021 average of 59, not the 44 he went at in 2022. If it was the latter, you could consider it if he has a midfield role in the preseason, but not at that awkward price.
afShort: 104 in the VFL a good sign for the former first rounder but yet to establish himself at AFL level

afComment: Foley arrived at West Coast with some great numbers in his under-age years but he's yet to show it at senior level. He's been forced to take a defensive role when playing seniors and at reserve level, which led to him averaging 57 points in AFL and 74 in the WAFL. He had every chance to breakout last year with the injuries at West Coast and it didn’t happen, so I doubt we’ll see it this season.
afShort: Big numbers in juniors but unable to replicate it at AFL level
Unless the former top 2 pick transitions into a ruckman, won't be a Fantasy relevant player

afComment: A back up ruck to Draper that has impressed at reserves level. He won the VFL Best and Fairest for the Bombers in 2021 and averaged 87 and 89 points the last 2 years, showing his potential. Draper is the clear number one man at Essendon, so opportunities are likely to be limited again.
afShort: Back up ruck to Draper with some decent VFL numbers

afComment: The ruckman played a career high 18 games in his first season at Brisbane after struggling for games during his career at Geelong. He played backup to the Big O and looked great at times in a forward/ruck role. He’s always been a decent scorer with the right opportunity, as shown by his 91 and 96 averages in the last 2 VFL seasons and 91 from 77% CBAs when Big O missed last year. However, I doubt he'll get the chance to play as the sole ruck while Big O is healthy.
afShort: Scores well when solo but I doubt he'll get the chance while Big O is healthy
Key defender who is unlikely to play this season

afComment: Became a regular in 2022, playing 22 matches as a hard running forward. The role isn’t great for Fantasy scoring though.
afShort: Small forward role not great for Fantasy
The 2021 mid-season draft pick has played most games since, but as a low scoring wingman
Returned to defence from a tagging role but still not a Fantasy scorer
Lost his spot in the team last season and even if he does play, he's more of a role player
Breakout season for the key forward, but only resulted in 63 post bye
Far from the player who averaged 85 in 2017, now scores like a regular key forward
Hard working half forward but a role player for the Dons
Star key defender in real life, not in Fantasy

afComment: The key forward has had a season where he averaged 86, which would rank him 8th amongst current forwards. However, he's more the 55-65 player we've seen the last few years.
afShort: More of a 55-65 key forward these days.

afComment: Macdonald entered the comp with a reputation of being a high production midfielder who is effective at stoppages and works hard defensively. He obviously impressed as he debuted in Round 1 and went on to play 19 matches. He was initially used as a small forward but progressed to play as a tagger, performing a number of shut down jobs on some of the league’s best runners. He maintained his forward status for 2023 and with the departures at the Hawks, there's a chance he gets his go inside where he excelled as a junior. At his awkward price, it's not someone you'd be starting with this season, but his 121 average in his draft year means you should always keep an eye on him.
afShort: Big junior numbers but was used as a forward/tagger in his debut season, might get his chance this year with all the departures
A very good footballer but scoring will be limited in his small forward role

afComment: Throughout his career, Wingard has had periods of great scoring in a Fantasy friendly midfield role. 109 in the last 5 of 2021, 98 in his last 5 of 2019, 100 for a 9 week stretch in 2018 and 104 through 10 games in 2017. However, as a small forward, he scores like any other small forward, not very well. In 2022, Wingard saw just 21% CBAs, like his other veteran Hawk teammates, well down on prior seasons. He didn’t go on a 100 averaging stretch, which means he’s priced at 56, the cheapest he's been since his debut season. If the forward role remains, there’s a bit of value there but not enough to commit to. However, if he looks to be the one to take up the midfield slack from Mitchell and O’Meara leaving, then he should be on your radar for Round 1. FWIW, the way Sam Mitchell coached last season, I don’t expect Wingard to get the 50%+ CBAs required.
afShort: A down year and now as cheap as he's been since his debut season, will he see more mid time following the departures?
The key defender played a career high 19 games due to the injuries at the Blues and scored typical of a key defender

afComment: Lynch moved from Collingwood to the Hawks in search of more opportunities, yet could only manage 7 games in his first season there. He battled with injury and then found himself behind Reeves in the ruck. The Hawks have added Meek to their ruck group in the offseason who appears to be the leader of the 3, meaning Lynch might find it tough for opportunities again in 2023. He’s averaged 90 at VFL level for the past 2 seasons which is decent enough, I just think it will be hard for him.
afShort: Battling with Meek and Reeves for a spot, so he could find it hard again

afComment: Fritsch had a career low Fantasy averagin in 2023, averaging 57 points for the season. He plays as a small forward and his higher scoring seasons he had stints on the wing and half back, which explains the decline. He'll be limited to a 60 averages while in the forward role at the Dees.
afShort: Limited to a 60 average while in the forward role

afComment: Behind O'Brien in the pecking order and the Crows have always preferred to play the one ruck. He did average a massive 112 in the SANFL last year, following his 105 in 2019. He's certainly AFL ready, I just doubt he'll get the opportunity again.
afShort: Big VFL numbers but still behind O'Brien
Just the 5 games last season as the Dogs look to have moved passed him
Not quite a key position player, but plays tall and scores like one
Emerging key forward could breakout in real life this season, but his role means that won't be in Fantasy

afComment: Out of all the 2020 draftees, I was most impressed with Powell’s first season, which makes his 2022 even more disappointing. The former pick 13 averaged 68 in his first season after having 35 disposals per game in SANFL Under-18s in his draft year and I earmarked him to breakout in 2022. He went on to play 18 games at an average of 56 in his second season, with less midfield time (16% CBAs down from 30%) and looked a shadow of the promising first year player. An extra preseason and new coach could see him bounce back and his forward status keeps him relevant for 2023. He’s not one I’d start with, but he’s worth watching to see if last year was just a blip.
afShort: Disappointing second season after an impressive debut year, hopefully he can recapture that form under the new coach
A reliable defender for the Suns, though unlikely to average much over 60 in this role
A restrictive small defender not in a Fantasy friendly role
101 VFL average but yet to cement a spot in the Saints team
Never been an accumulator of the football, illustrated by his best career season being 60 in 13 seasons

afComment: The pick 1 in the last year's midseason draft played 4 matches in his debut season at a 68 average. He averaged 96 at NAB League level and 67 in the WAFL, but the talk during the midseason draft and even at the 2022 National Draft was that he would've gone first round if available in it. His tackling impressed, averaging 7.5 a game which is elite numbers, and he got decent opportunity with 51% CBAs. West Coast have a few back from injury this season so I’m not sure what role Culley will play and at mid-only he’s not an option for this season.
afShort: Strong tackling mid impressed last season but unsure what his role will be in a full strength West Coast line-up
Brilliant return from the former number 1 pick, but his full back role isn't a Fantasy-friendly one

afComment: Spargo is a regular at the Dees, playing 49 games in the last 2 seasons. He's currently limited to a small forward role, which isn't Fantasy friendly. He may one day progress into the midfield, but it's an extremely hard midfield to break into at Melbourne.
afShort: Important small forward for the Dees, not for Fantasy
A gun full back of the comp but not relevant in Fantasy
Just 9 games last year after 22 the year before, the small forward will be on the fringe again

afComment: The former pick 28 played 7 games in his debut season an impressed with his kicking skills and speed. He might be one for the future, but he'll likely need a bit of time before being a regular midfielder.
afShort: Impressed in his debut season but will need time before being a regular midfielder
Yet to match his brilliant debut season and with mid-only, it's not worth punting on the bounce back
The developing ruck had his chance in 2023 with no NicNat and only managed a 55 from 52% CBAs
Tall wing yet to show he can accumulate the footy

afComment: The son of Peter and younger brother of Trent, Jase played 7 games in his debut season in defence and impressed. Port Adelaide's defence is strong and it might be hard to get a regluar spot this season, but he certainly looks one for the future.
afShort: Impressed in 7 games last year but hard to trust in 2nd season
Key defender on the fringe of the best 22
Dropped 19 points last season but even if he returns to his 74, he's not a worthwhile selection
JK retiring may help, but 55 from 19 last year isn't Fantasy worthy
Fringe key defender that doesn't have a scoring role
Promising running defender, but behind a few for usage so he might need some time before we see him at his best

afComment: Maginness played a career high 16 games in 2022 as a wingman and tagger. He has elite running capacity which allowed him to shut down some of the best runners in the AFL, but it’s not a role that leads to scoring. At mid-only, he’s not relevant this season.
afShort: Hard running wing/tagger isn't much of a scorer himself

afComment: The mature-aged ruckman played 6 games in 2022 after 5 in 2021. With the arrival of Lobb and English hitting his peak, we might not see much more of him in 2023.
afShort: Unlikley to feature with Lobb backing up English
Now at the Dees but unlikely to change his scoring output nor place in the 22
Intercept defender better in real life than Fantasy
Pressure forward out of consideration in Fantasy
Small forward not what you want in Fantasy
Scored best in past when rucking and given how good he was up forward last year, that won't happen
Role player at Port in defence, not a scorer

afComment: Thomas' 2022 season was as disappointing as I've seen. The former top 10 pick was heading into his fourth season coming off a career best season of 81, 93 in second half and 107 in his last 5. With CBAs increasing in line, and low TOG, he ticked all the boxes for a breakout. He instead went down in scoring by 28 points per game and down in CBAs, even finding himself playing VFL football for a lot of it. A fresh start with a new coach is a blessing and it sounds like he's been training as a half back in the preseason and match sim. He's one of the bigger preseason watches as if he can even get back to his 2021 level of scoring, he'll be a worthwhile pick.
afShort: Hoping for a bounce back after a disappointing 2022 - 93 in 2nd half of 2021 the hope!
Gun key defender and despite dropping 17 points, not one for Fantasy
Can play forward, back and ruck and it looks like he's settled in the least Fantasy-friendly role, defence
Struggled in his return from an ACL and said to be trialled in defence which should boost scoring but no enough to consider

afComment: Meek has been stuck behind Darcy at Freo but developing well in the WAFL. He averaged 103 points for Peel last season, up from 95 the year prior. He moved to the Hawks in the offseason where there is every chance of him being their number 1 ruck. Reeves and Lynch are currently there vying for that role and both are pretty good, which means it's not a sure thing Meek takes the number 1 spot. If he gets the nod, I can see him putting up 80+, which is enough for some early cash gen while the other rucks settle. With Hayes going down at the Saints and the concern Marshall might be forward, Meek at R2 is becoming a more realistic move.
afShort: Big chance to be Hawks number 1 guys which could see 80+ scoring based on his WAFL form

afComment: Was drafted as one of the premier midfielders of the 2020 draft, however has had to settle with a forward role for the time being given the midfield depth at the Giants. He now finds himself at Geelong, who despite being the reigning premiers, they’re not super deep in the mids. He should get his chance to play more midfield which would be a boost to his scoring. He did get 37% CBAs in the first half of last year and only managed 60, so I don't think we're going to see high scoring from him. Keep an eye on him given his talent, forward status and more mid time, but I doubt he'll make an impact in Fantasy this season.
afShort: Should get more midfield opportunities at the Cats but going by his scoring to date, I doubt he'll boost his score enough
A role player in defence for Freo who has only managed 13 games in 2 years

afComment: Fogarty has been on the radar since he was drafted after his elite junior numbers, highlighted by a 124 average in the NAB League. However, managed just 3 games last year for the Blues after struggling for opportunities at the Cats earlier in his career. Hard to trust based on that.
afShort: Just 3 games last season and might find it tough again for opportunities
Small forward played 17 games last season but scoring is limited

afComment: Ralphsmith played 13 games last season in a half back role and looked good. However, it only yielded an average of 53, and with the likelihood of Short moving back to defence, Ralphsmith might be on the fringe in 2023.
afShort: The likelihood of Short moving back to defence, Ralphsmith might be on the fringe in 2023
Still behind Preuss and Flynn for the starting ruck spot
Found a role in defence but not a scoring one

afComment: There's no doubting Coleman-Jones has talent, however he's yet to really crack it at AFL level. Not even a move to the Kangaroos provided more job security, with just 10 games last season at an average of 53. He continued to dominate at lower level, averaging 104 at VFL level after 115 the year prior and 116 in his draft year. Those scores came from playing predominantly in the ruck and at AFL level, he plays as a key forward. If he's ever handed to keys to be the number 1 ruck then he could be worth a look, but that's an unlikely scenario.
afShort: Yet to cement his spot at AFL level despite but VFL scores
74 in 2020 the outlier, he's been a mid-50s guy his whole career
A reliable defender but not a scorer

afComment: Worpel has had two poor seasons in a row after bursting onto the scene. He averaged 97 in just his 2nd season and backed it up with another 97 in his 3rd, which included 104 in the 2nd half. After looking like becoming a star mid of the comp, he completely regressed, averaging 79 in his 4th season and dropped another 27 last year to average just 52. He played just 46% in the midfield and certainly didn't suit the outside role he was forced to play. Mitchell and O'Meara's departures mean there are CBAs up for grabs at the Hawks. But what I've seen since Sam Mitchell has taken over doesn't give me confidence that Worpel will receive any of these. Mitchell doesn't want Worpel winning outside ball and demands him to play a role that isn't great for his Fantasy scoring. He has to be a preseason watch regardless based on past scoring history and his price, 45 points less than his average in his 2nd season. A consistent midfield role would make but a decent midpriced option, I just think Sam Mitchell will give more time to Ward, McDonald, Newcombe and Moore meaning Worpel might not get that bump in CBAs.
afShort: A big fall from his early career scores and could get his chance to bounce back with the departures of key mids
Role player for the Tigers who lost his spot in the 22 at times last seasons

afComment: Rachele burst out of the blocks in 2022, kicking 5 goals on debut and 12 after 5 rounds. He slowed as the season went on, as many rookies do, but certainly showed enough to suggest he’s going to be a star of the future. The former pick 6 has been floated as a possible midfielder this season and I think we’ll see him used in there at times as he offers something their current mids don’t. However, I doubt we’ll see him get the 50% required for him to score well enough in Fantasy to consider in our teams.
afShort: Talk of more midfield time but I think he'll predominantly be a small forward again this season which isn't great for Fantasy

afComment: Arrived as a mature age (26) SSP selection after being SANFL's premier key forward in recent years averaging, averaging 128 in 2021. He didn't disappoint, scoring 111 on debut and I had to double take if it was him of Marshall. Unfortunately, he did his knee in Round 6 and missed the rest of the season. He was set for an early season return, however hurt his foot at training and is now set to miss the first part of the year. He was never a starting pick himself, but with King also missing the early rounds, the likelihood of Marshall having to play forward has increased.
afShort: Loved his 4 games last season and unfortunately he's out for the start of 2023 which could have implications for Marshall
Plays as a speedy small forward and certainly hasn't looked a scorer to date
Tall swingman whose scoring hasn’t moved much with a change of position and club
A key position player who would score a bit higher if he kicked straighter, but not enough to make an impact
Returned from a second ACL to play 15 games and show some good signs, just not enough for Fantasy
Tall forward/ruck who is yet to cement his spot in the Swans' 22
Developing key forward / backup ruckman also yet to cement his spot in the team

afComment: Tucker has moved to North after 7 seasons with Freo, displaying some Fantasy talent. He was having a career best season in 2020 when playing in the midfield (46% CBAs) before it was cut short due to injury. He went at 95 in the first five rounds and was averaging an adjusted 84 until scoring a zero in his last game, dragging his season average down to 73. He then played as a defender when he returned in 2021, going from 46% CBAs to 0% and averaging just 61 points per game. He played forward in his limited opportunities last season, averaging 52 but that included 4 games with less than 50% game time. He dominated in the WAFL to average 99, so he can score when in the right role. I'm not sure his role will be in the midfield at the Roos, but if it is in the preseason, then he's worth a look as a mid-priced forward.
afShort: Should get more opportunities at North and if that means midfield then he's worth a look at that price
Might see more games on the wing with Hunter leaving, but career best average of 58 and just 59 in VFL last year isn't a great sign
Former pick 16 playing as a small forward and unless an (unlikely) move to the mids occurs, he's not going to be a factor
A junior stud who plays as a role player in defence at the Dees and down the pecking order for distribution
Small forward broke out last season but still only managed 51 points in the role
14 games last season in defence but not an accumulator of the ball
Looks a player with his clean hands but doesn't win enough football to be relevant in this game
A nice intercept marker, but a genuine full back and not a player you want in your team
Key defender in and out of the side

afComment: Martin showed a heap of promise early days but has failed to go on with it. He bottomed out last season, averaging 51 points per game, which is 33 points below his best. Up until the 2 seasons, he was a mid-to-low 80s guy, so you'd have to think he could get back to that level. But it would be hard to select him based on the last 2 seasons.
afShort: Dropped off the last 2 seasons and despite his discount to career best, he's hard to trust
A gun intercept defender but you don't get extra Fantasy points for intercepting
4 games in 3 years at the Dees, might get more chances at the Dogs but at that price and mid-only he's not worth it
A solid key forward at almost 2 goals a game, but not a scorer in this game

afComment: Got his chance last season with Lycett out, playing the 7 games to average 56. He's done his time in the SANFL, averaging almost 90 for 3 seasons, so I expected him to score a bit better than he did. Port opted to play no recognised ruck at times, using Finlayson and Dixon over Hayes, which isn't a great sign. Lycett is back so I think we might see Hayes go back to the SANFL.
afShort: Only 7 games in a year Lycett missed a chunk isn't a great sign

afComment: In a down year for West Coast, Hough was one of the few shining lights. He played 15 games and looked very composed with ball in hand. He should get his chances again while West Coast are developing and improve again, but I doubt it will be by enough to make him relevant.
afShort: Impressive debut season but unlikely to make an impact this year
Mature aged rookie played 15 games on debut, but in a small forward role, not the midfield role where he averaged 100 in the VFL
Key defender who excels in one-on-one contests but doesn't have much of an offensive game

afComment: Robertson was one of the most hyped rookies in Fantasy when he was drafted, following his elite scoring in his draft year; 113 average in the National Championships (ranked 1) and 120 average in WAFL colts (also ranked 1). He hasn’t done a heap at AFL level in his first 3 seasons, playing just the 7 games last season for a 62 average. His 104 in the VFL shows he still has it, but it might be much the same for Robertson this season as Dunkley puts him another player behind for midfield opportunities.
afShort: Junior gun but might be much the same this year as Dunkley puts him another player behind for midfield opportunities

afComment: Saints look like they got a steal with Windhager, taken pick 47 of the 2021 draft. He looked as comfortable as many of the top picks, playing multiple roles including as a tagger inside. I think he's got the attributes to make it, but in his second season at that price, it's unlikely he'll be relevant this season unless he plays as ball winning mid.
afShort: Impressive debut season and one for the future, but unlikely to be this year

afComment: Campbell is dealing with a sore achilles which is likely to delay his start to the season. The relevance comes due to the potential of him playing as the main ruck and Rowan Marshall forward, which us coaches don't want. Campbell did average 112 at VFL level last season but I I doubt he'll ever get the regular number 1 role at the Saints.
afShort: Depth ruck dealing with a sore achilles which is likely to delay his start to the season
A small forward with a bit of energy about him, not one for the Fantasy scorers though
Struggled to cement his spot in his 6 seasons
The veteran medium forward has been on the fringe of the Demons' 22 for a while now
Defender without much attacking side to his game
Loved the look of this mid-season draftee with his elite kicking skills, however can’t see him taking the leap from this price
Mid-only and no CBAs rules him out
Tall forward who doesn't score enough to consider
Key defender with a career high average of 60

afComment: It's not the first time Milera has created some buzz as a mid-priced selection in the preseason. In 2018 he averaged 93 in the last 5 games which made him a popular pick in 2019. In 2019, he started strong, averaging 86 in the first half before getting injured and interrupting his season. Unfortunately, it's been the same old story for Milera, who has more time off the park than on. He played 12 games last season and certainly looked like he'd missed a lot of football, averaging just 50 for the season in mixed roles. He enters 2023 with a full preseason under his belt and the word is that he's been moved back to his favourable half back position. He's a preseason watch for both role and confidence, because if he can average 80+, which he's shown he can, he'll prove a great mid-priced selection. But comes with the obvious injury, role and spot in 22 risks.
afShort: Talk of a move back to half back where he's gone 80+ before, if he can do that again he'll be a great pick - massive IF though
Promising key forward but not one for Fantasy
Averaged 91 in VFL after 100 the year before, but unlikely to get a decent role at AFL level
Talented forward now at Geelong where he could see more games but won't score enough
Plays the defensive forward role super well for the Pies, just not a role for Fantasy
Failed to live up to expectations after being taken with pick 6, the change of environment to West Coast has so far failed to reignite his career
Showed great signs in his 1st season as an intercept mark and tall forward, but won't be in Fantasy calcs this year
Mid-season draftee whose scores at reserve level don't jump off the page
Hard working forward who now at age 31, might find it tough to squeeze into their best 22
Has showed some nice signs, but a developing tall forward is always going to need time
Played 41 games in 2 seasons but the former top 10 pick hasn't shown much in the scoring department
Key defender who dropped 12 points due to reduced kick ins and I doubt it will go back up
Plays 2nd ruck behind Nank, which means he's in and out of the side
Drafted top 10 in 2018 as a midfielder, although limited to defence and scoring isn't there
Mature age who put up big scores at reserve level before being drafted and in the VFL last year, but doesn't play that role when at AFL level
Has tempted coaches since his 95 average in 2016, but he's dropped a long way off and proved far too inconsistent
A depth player in the forward line with a career best average of 58 from 6 seasons

afComment: Owens played 7 games in his debut season and looked the goods, showcased by a great tackling ability. He was used in a tagging role and up forward. Could be one for the future, but I doubt he'll feature in Fantasy calculations this season.
afShort: Showed a great tackling ability but I doubt he'll feature in Fantasy calculations this season
Mid-season draftee looked great with his hands and skills around goal, not a Fantasy scorer though
Only 2 games in debut season, looking neat in defence, but there are plenty of them at the Dogs so might find it tough again
99 in SANFL, up from 67, but scoring at AFL level looks limited

afComment: Cox impressed everyone in his first season, playing 20 games at an average of 56. He dropped to just 5 games at 48 in year 2 as he continues to develop and find his role in the team. It might be a few years before we see the best of Cox.
afShort: Versatile high pick, might be a few years before we see the best of him
Lightly-built mid-season pick looked pretty good last season, but I doubt he'll become an accumulating defender
Been on the outer the past 3 seasons after being a regular goal kicker for the Suns
Solid defender but highest average over the 9 years is 59
Mid-season pick averaged 104 at VFL level and looked good in the AFL, but with Mitchell there might find it tougher
An accumulator at reserve level for a number of years, however he's never cemented his spot in the 22
Brilliant season and a star of the future, but tall defender not the role for scoring in Fantasy
16 games from the former pick 1 and will continue to get better, but not as a Fantasy asset
The versatile Kangaroo not a Fantasy scorer
75 in 2019 was on a wing, he's now back as a key defender so ignore the discount to career high
Only 9 games in 2 seasons but he's a goal kicker, just not a scorer
Never played more than 11 games in a season, too hard to trust

afComment: Top 10 pick with monster junior numbers (109 in WAFL Colts), high endurance and good size. He made the step up to seniors, averaging 96 in the WAFL this season and had some chances at AFL level, playing 4 games. 2 of those he had less than 50% game time as sub, so his 58 average isn't the best read. I think we'll see a lot more of him this season, but it's still going to be hard to get consistent CBAs with Brayshaw, Serong, Brodie and O'Meara taking up the majority. While Freo are contending, it's unlikely they will give many minutes inside to their kids, but I can see Erasmus playing on the wing this season. Expect a nice bump in average, but it might be a year or two before we see him putting up consistent numbers worthy of Fantasy selection.
afShort: Looks to have the attributes of a future star, just might need some time to get his chance in the contending Freo side
Taken as an overager in the 2020 rookie draft and played the majority of game but in a defensive forward role

afComment: The mature aged pick of 2021 had Fantasy coaches tongues wagging after averaging 121 in the WAFL in his draft year. His season was delayed due to an AC injury, but he debuted in Round 7 and didn't disappoint, scoring 110. He missed the following week with COVID protocols and then never reached those heights again. Outside of his debut, I was underwhelmed by him and despite him still being 25, I think he might struggle for games in the full strength West Coast line-up. If he is a first choice mid in the preseason, there's some value at that price given what we know he can do, but he's been used on a wing at AFL level and I doubt he'll get the inside minutes.
afShort: Monster junior scores and on debut looked to be Barlow 2.0, but didn't go on with it and now unlikely to have an inside role
Only 2 matches in 2022 and with the emergence of the young Freo defenders, I doubt we see much of him this season

afComment: Campbell showed a lot of promise early as a rookie, scoring 96 in his second game. He ended up out of the side and then became injured. He played 14 games in his second season but most of them as sub. He's got a terrific kick on him and showed enough for me to think he'll be a star of the future. Priced at 46, he'll outperform that price if given the opportunities, but based on the first 2 years, he might not get enough chances.
afShort: Elite kick and has talent, but hard to see him getting enough chances this year to make him a decent pick
Key defender and certainly not a scorer
Top 10 pick but a tall key defender with a sub-50 VFL average
Developing tall defender who famously finished top 10 in AFL Fantasy Classic in 2021, not relevant himself though
Key defender and certainly not a Fantasy scorer

afComment: Former pick 3 with huge potential, averaged 94 in the VFL which shows he shaped up well against the men. One for the future, but likely to remain on the outside / VFL until he fully develops.
afShort: Future star and should get more chances in 2023, he just might need some more developing before we see him ready to pop
28-year-old key defender that has a career-high average of 62
Genuine key defender
Played 15 games and looked great, but small forward isn't going to be a scorer
Irishman got his chance in 2022 but 52 at AFL and 56 in VFL doesn't look like he's going to be a scorer
Just 49 in SANFL and 39 in AFL
Vandermeer has some talent, but a career average of sub-50 doesn't suggest he's going to be a scorer

afComment: McLean comes into 2023 high on the watchlist. He returned from back-to-back ACL reconstructions to play in the finals, where he scored 100. This score isn't built into his price, so he's priced at a 30% discount to his 65 in 2021, being 45. The 60-mark is what he averaged from 2019-2021 and if he returned to that level he'll made a decent level of cash, but the scoring wouldn't be worth the extra cash from a rookie. However, he's averaged 94 at AFL level before in 2018, and in that year he was going at 105 in the first half. He also averaged 96 in the VFL last year, so on that form he can surpass the ’60-mark’. A preseason watch, obviously any CBA action will be a bonus as a small forward role is very hard to rely on in Fantasy, but he’s certainly underpriced.
afShort: Priced at 45 after missing the regular season but form in finals, VFL and 2018 suggests he can blow that price out of the park
A consistent defender for the Cats, never surpassed 58 in a season though
Injury kept him game less in 2022 and even if he bounces back to 2021 form, he's not worth selecting
Got his chance in his first season due to injuries and looked okay, but a nullifying defender who won't be a scorer
Might get more chances at the Dons, but a key forward who has never been a scorer

afComment: Sharp finished 2021 looking like he was the Suns’ wingman of the future, averaging 79 points per game (excluding his 6). He found it harder in 2022 though, only playing 11 games at an average of 45. He showed enough in ’21 and at VFL level (110 average) that he can outperform that price by enough if given the opportunity. However, that’s not guaranteed and the fact he’s only available in the midfield, he loses a lot of appeal.
afShort: Priced well below his 2021 and VFL scoring, but yet to cement his spot and mid-only makes it tricky
Tough defender who I confuse with Moore at times such is his marking ability, but far from a scorer in Fantasy
Played 6 games in '22 both forward and back, and while he looked more at home in defence, he doesn't look like high scorer
Natural inside mid and showed his talent with a 87, but limited to a forward role at AFL level, unlikely to score much there
I liked his 3 games but didn't appear after Leon left, might get more chances now but scoring history isn't flash
Former first rounder yet to show any signs he's going to make it

afComment: The first-round draft pick from 2019 finally debuted in 2022, playing the 5 matches. He looked pretty good in limited game time (61%) and would've learnt a lot in his 3 seasons at the Cats. He's now at Hawthorn where he should walk into their best 22 and play a decent role. That's enough to put him on the watch list, but mid-only and moderate scoring history (68 in draft year, 61 at VFL level, 52 at AFL level) will make it hard to do.
afShort: Will get his chances at the Hawks but poor scoring at lower level curbs any excitement
Has scored okay when playing as a backup ruck, but now solely a key forward (1% CBA in ’22)
Talented player and VFL numbers up from prior season, but just 44 from a few CBAs at AFL level not great reading
Star defender who has put up 70 in the past, but he’s purely focussed on defending now
Strong bodied defender seems a favourite at Port and was even flagged for mid-time last year, but that never happened, and he places a defensive role for the team
Promising key defender, not as a Fantasy scorer though
Small pressure forward not in a role for scoring, so unless we see an (unlikely) midfield move under Clarko, he won't be relevant in Fantasy
Numbers at junior level were okay, however 45 at AFL and 63 at VFL as a defender aren’t great

afComment: The mid-season draftee played 2 games in his first season but showed great signs in both of them with an 84 in 1 game and an early injury in his other. With Lycett back, I'm not sure how much we'll see Teakle, but he did provide some energy that Port have lacked in the ruck for a while. He's a bit awkwardly priced, so unless he's named sole ruck in Round 1, he won't be relevant this season.
afShort: Might struggle with Lycett back
Should get a decent role at West Coast, has averaged 70+ in the past but hard to rely on outside runners

afComment: The former top 10 pick hasn't really come on and then unfortunately did his ACL last preseason. He has attributes to be a good Fantasy defender, a neat kick and ability to generate marks. He finished 2020 averaging 83 in the last 5 games and that's about the mark I think he can produce at his best. He's obviously going to need some time to find his feet when he returns and it's unknown what role Ross will have for him, but if he looks fit in the preseason, he's a midpriced defender I don't mind, especially given the gap between the top 5 and the rest.
afShort: Returning from an ACL and priced well below his potential, if he looks fit in preseason you could take the punt

afComment: The former number 3 pick has always been on the radar due to his draft position, but is yet to deliver. His numbers at VFL level are getting better, but mid-only in 2023, you can’t do it on exposed form.
afShort: We've been waiting for a breakout but mid-only in 2023, you can’t do it on exposed form
Small forward new club but same unfavourable role
Versatile tall that can play at both ends but with 2 games last season, he's a depth player

afComment: Returning from 2 years in Ireland and should lot into his customary running defender role at the Lions, who need some pace back there. His best ever season was a 70 average, with the majority in the mid-60s. He's priced at 42, so there's obvious upside on his price. But I don't like mid-pricers who average in the 60s as more often than not you can get a rookie for much cheaper who can produce similar output. It's a pass for me, unless he looks more like a 75-plus scorer in the preseason.
afShort: Back from Ireland but career average in the 60s probably isn't enough for the additional price
Has potential to be a very good key forward, but not a Fantasy one
The hard running tall forward has great hands and should play more than he did at GC last season, but won't come into Fantasy calculations
Small forward became a regular, but average of 42 sums up the role
Mid-only with a 57 SANFL average and 43 AFL average

afComment: After impressing in his debut season, Edwards suffered osteitis pubis for the whole of his second season, eventually ending his season early. He's highly rated internally, however at that price point for a mid-only, I doubt he'll get the midfield opportunities this season to prove worth it.
afShort: Interrupted 2022 and highly rated, but tough at that price and mid-only
32-yr-old full back on the rookie list, not the combo you want
Knee surgery in offseason for the defender
Yet to show much of a Fantasy game in his first 3 seasons
Impressive key defender, but not a scorer
Versatile tall struggled for games last season and the Bombers may have moved past him
Key forward who might struggle for opportunities this year
Always been highly rated internally but mid-only with 47 average at AFL and 66 at VFL suggests otherwise
Defender with 5 games in 3 seasons and an average of 67 in the SANFL
Brilliant tackle pressure in the forward line, but in a small forward role, scoring is always going to be limited
SANFL numbers reduced last season (72 to 64) and scoring wasn't great at AFL level
Mid-only, 0% CBAs and 41 average from 14 games doesn’t read great
Promising tall defender will be sidelined for the start of the season
Small forward with a 51 VFL average and max 4 games at AFL level in a season
Might get more chances this season but judging by his first, unlikely to score well

afComment: Emerging key forward missed the entire 2022 season due to injury. He put up 69 in just his 3rd season, showing that he will score more than the average key forward. He's priced at 40 given his missed season, which is well under what he has produced. I never like having key forwards in Fantasy, even if they are cheap. A sub-60 average would make it a poor pick as you could get that output from a rookie for less of a price. He'd be a great pick if he can reproduce that 69, but West Coast aren't as strong as they were then and 3 of his last 4 seasons have been sub-60 scores, so I'm out of this one.
afShort: Missed 2022 meaning he's priced at 40, well down from his best (69) but I never like key forwards in Fantasy
Small forward who spent most of last season as sub should get more chances at GWS, but the small forward role isn't a high scoring one even with a full game
Developed as a great defender, but a 40 point average from a full season suggests he's far from a scorer
Only 2 games after 13 the season before suggest he might struggle for opportunities again
Played a far less attacking role at the Tigers, ignore the discount to career high for the 33-year-old
2 games last year and then put on the rookie list suggests the Lions may have moved past him
Great numbers in his draft year and played the 1 game on debut, mid-only and a premium rookie price doesn't make him that attractive even if named Round 1
Medium defender picked up in the 2020 mid-season draft, had averages in the 60s at VFL level up until last year's 71, so doesn't appear a scorer
Small forward showed plenty in his first season, but that still led to a 40 average such is the role
A big ball winner at the lower level, Banfield has mostly played as a defensive forward in the AFL which doesn't generate high scores, especially as sub 10 times

afComment: Former top 5 pick is still very lightly built, but showed some moments in his 4 games last season. Once developed physically, the high leaping Andrew should become a gun ruckman, but until then it looks like he's being trailed as a tall defender. He's suspended to start the season, however as he is still developing, he wouldn't have been relevant anyway.
afShort: Suspended to start the season, however as he is still developing, he wouldn't have been relevant anyway
Versatile big man has become a very reliable defender for the Giants and has also pinched hit in the ruck, but as a defender he's not going to score enough in Fantasy
Reliable defender missed 2022 with a serious ankle injury, discounted price but never been over 57
A developing ruck prospect played 9 games in 2022 due to injures, however he still looks a few years off the level

afComment: The former pick 6 certainly hasn't come on as we all expected him to, and bottomed out last season with just 4 games at senior level. The Swans seem to have a way of getting the best out of players, so there's some home there now that he's made the switch, however scores around the 50s in the past wouldn't make him an attractive pick.
afShort: Hopefully gets a chance at the Swans, but scores around the 50s in the past not enough
Made the move to the Suns in 2021 in a very strange recruitment, never played more than 8 games since arriving and will unlikely be in their best team again
I liked the look of the running defender when he first started, but max average of 40 and just 12 games last season doesn't read well
Strong marking forward who only played 2 games last season and a 63 VFL average isn't great

afComment: Highly rated by those who have seen a lot of him. He's yet to show much to date, however he's spent most his time playing as a small forward and is tipped to play more on the wing in 2023, where he can use his elite leg speed and evasiveness. The former top 10 pick should see a bump in scoring if that eventuates, I just can’t see it improving by enough based on exposed form.
afShort: Training as a wing which is better than a small forward, but I can’t see him improving by enough based on exposed form
Was recruited as a hard-running midfielder, but been used as a small forward when at AFL level and hard to see him changing that

afComment: Promising key forward who showed some great signs in his limited games. I think he'll become a very good player, but young key forwards are never good Fantasy options
afShort: Young key forwards are never good Fantasy options
Great to see Tippa back! But will need some time getting to fitness and never been a Fantasy asset as a small forward
56 VFL average and 3 sub 40 seasons at AFL level sums him up

afComment: Constable was delisted from Geelong at the end of 2021 and was thrown a lifeline by Gold Coast, however he didn’t see much more AFL action with just the 1 game in 2022 (as sub). Constable has been a strong VFL player over his career, averaging 100 last season and 111 in 2021. He averaged 83 from 7 games in 2019 at the top level (his debut year), so he can obviously find the football. It's a question on if he is best 22 – Gold Coast bat deep in the midfield and he’ll likely find it tough again.
afShort: Great VFL numbers but has very been able to get a decent crack at AFL level, unlikely to change this season
Just 4 games last season, he can look great on his day but moderate averages to date even if he does become a regular this season
Started his career as a forward but moved to defense, however scoring and position in team still not solid
Simpson burst on the scene with a 128 in Round 6 2020, but struggled since and didn't play a game last season
Former Australian basketballer has been putting up decent VFL numbers, but opportunites at AFL level seem limited
Developing key forward should get more chances this year, but 55 at VFL level doesn't suggest he's going to be a scorer
Back from a year away, gets the discount but he's never been a scorer in Fantasy
23-year-old full back has cemented himself as the main man in deep defence for the Crows, far from a scorer though
Missed the entire 2022 season for injury and they missed him up forward, however scoring limited in the small forward role and no an option despite the discount
Returning from an ACL, will need time to find his feet and even at his best, the star forward isn't a Fantasy option
Set to miss the start of the season after a shoulder recon in December
Looked good in his 3 games last season and creating a lot of buzz internally this preseason, but VFL average of 33 and AFL 45 doesn't suggest he's a scorer

afComment: The younger brother of Dan, Sam is slightly taller and more able to push up through the midfield. Played 9 games in his debut season as a forward and creating some buzz internally this preseason, but if he remains in his forward role he's unlikley to score enough.
afShort: Creating some buzz internally this preseason, but if he remains in his forward role he's unlikley to score enough
Ferocious key forward should get more chances with no Lobb, but not a Fantasy scorer
WAFL average of 66 and an off season incident makes him an unlikely Round 1 starter
Key defender returning from an ACL, will need time to get back to his best which isn't high Fantasy scoring anyway

afComment: Cuningham looked to have found himself a spot in Carlton's 22 in 2021, getting decent time through the middle. He started the season with 35% CBAs but then tore his ACL early in Round 4 on a score of 0, dragging his average down. He hasn’t played since as he’s dealt with calf issues. It sounds like he’s healthy now, but with the added depth of Carlton's midfield with Cerra and Hewett arriving since he’s been out, it's unclear what role he will play (if any). He is under-priced based on his ability, but there are too many question marks to consider him.
afShort: Almost 2 years out of the game and was just getting going before his ACL, hard to see how he fits in now with Cerra and Hewett in the midfield
2020 mid-season draftee who was selected as a backup and depth ruckman, but Cameron and Cox have that now

afComment: A two-month foot setback meant that Bytel didn't feature at AFL level in 2022 after 13 matches in 2021. He was used at centre bounces regularly when playing, attending 43% of CBAs from 54% game time in 2021. His average from 2021 looks poor, but he was used as the injury sub on five occasions. His VFL average of 91 is a better reflection of his ability, however he's going to find it hard for regular games again in 2023.
afShort: No games in 2022 not a great sign for the fringe midfielder
Hard to crack a game for the Lions and his VFL average of 67 isn't great if he ever does
2 games in his first season but a tough team to crack and mid-only he's out of calculations
A role player for the Dogs who has hovered around the 40s in his career and I can't see that changing

afComment: Marchbank has been plagued by injuries over the past 3 years. He managed his first game for 3 years in 22, only to get injured in it and miss the next few weeks. He returned to finish the season and displayed his natural intercept marking ability. His best is 69, which would make him a nice cash generator at his price. But he’s not that same player now after those injuries, so he’s a hard one to commit to.
afShort: Talented defener plagued by injures and his body is too hard to trust now
Injury prone defender is in and out of the side and typically plays as a lockdown defender, so he's not attractive even at that price
Tall defender picked up as a SSP has cemented his spot in defence for the Crows, however he's not a scorer in this format
