A developing defender who lost cash last season depsite starting priced at 32, says enough about his scoring ability early in his career
Speedy forward with a great kick was exposed to AFL football last year and did some nice things, but will certainly need more time to develop
Irishman who has speed but poor scoring at VFL and AFL level
A lockdown defender for the Swans who has fallen out of favour the past 3 seasons
A hard, contested ball winning midfielder played 3 games in his 1st season and showed good signs with 71 in the VFL
Back up ruck/forward might get his chance with McStay leaving, but scoring to date has been limited

afComment: Finlay has been a hard one to get a read on. There was no under-age football in his draft year, so we had to rely on his 2019 year where he played as a 17-year-old for Oakleigh Chargers, a team that boasted Matt Rowell, Noah Anderson and Will Phillips in the midfield. Finlay was forced to play mostly across half-forward but showed some great signs and from all reports was more advanced than his (half) brother who by contrast only came good during the second half of his draft year. We saw the similarities in Finlay's debut when he was thrown into the middle for the final quarter and racked up over 10 disposals. However, he hasn’t shown much since. He’s averaged over 90 in the VFL since drafted, so the talent is there. Priced at 33 and with forward status, I think he’s worth considering if he’s named Round 1 as an expensive rookie but with more experience.
afShort: Averaged over 90 in the VFL since being drafted and if he gets his chance, he's worth spending up on
Key defender with historically low scoring in his limited opportunities, despite nice VFL form
The brother of Jarrod now at Gold Coast, and VFL form (97 2021, 90 2020) is good enough if ever named

afComment: Corey Wagner was on both North Melbourne and Melbourne's list and played some solid footy in his time at AFL level. He's been at Port Melbourne in the VFL the last two years and has continued to improve, where he had an exceptional back end of the 2022 season after moving to half back. He averaged 84 in the VFL last year and the 26-year-old body makes him a prime on-field rookie if named Round 1. Unfortunately, he's not priced at the basement price, but at $285k, he's still worth paying up for.
afShort: 26-year-old with AFL experience averaged 84 in the VFL last year and a great defender rookie if named Round 1
Mid-season draftee from the SANFL kicked 20 goals throughout the first 8 games as a small forward which is impressive but the small forward role isn't for Fantasy
GC have plenty of small pressure forwards but he with Rankine out he might play more, role isn't attractive though
Versatile tall that can run through the midfield but scoring to date at VFL and AFL level suggest he's not there yet
High leaping, strong marking, medium forward however low production (62 in VFL) suggests needs more time at VFL level to develop
VFL average up from 60 to 80 and might find things easier at Port, but small forward role isn't great for scoring
Played 8 games after getting picked up in the midseason draft, playing as a key-position defender where scoring was limited
Half-back was second at Sandringham’s B&F but couldn't get a senior gig, 71 VFL average was okay but might struggle for games again

afComment: Was said to be the premier midfielder and the readiest to play from the 2020 draft pool. Phillips for Oakleigh averaged better numbers at the same age during the finals than Matt Rowell and Noah Anderson. However, he didn't look it in his first season, averaging 44 in his 14 games. He averaged 93 in the VFL which was promising. He then missed the entire 2022 season due to glandular fever. He’s now fully recovered and training very well, spending most of his time in the midfield. Unfortunately he doesn’t have the forward status of last season, however at this price and credentials, he’s an automatic selection for me unless multiple basement price rookies put their hands up.
afShort: Fully fit after glandular ruined his 2022 season, training in the midfield and highly credentialed junior makes him almost a lock
The former number 11 draft pick hasn't found a spot at the Kangas and a 68 VFL average suggests even if he does, he's not a great Fantasy option
Small forward was hampered by injury throughout season 2022, not playing at all and will need some VFL time before he's ready
Highly rated and injury prone key forward and ruckman will need more time to develop before he ever comes into calculations
Key forward who returned from 2 ACL injuries to debut in 2022, looked like he needed the run and will be better this season but not Fantasy relevant
53 VFL average and less at AFL doesn't read well
Was highly rated in his draft year but delisted at the end of 2022 then re-rookied is never a good sign

afComment: Previously been a relevant player in Fantasy with multiple 90s seasons back in 2017 and 2018. He then became out of favour at Freo, not playing a game last season while averaging 99 in the WAFL. Gold Coast have given him a lifeline and if he happens to be named Round 1 then he has to be considered, however with their up and coming young midfield, I doubt we see Blakely play a prominent role.
afShort: A gun in the past and now at GC, unlikely to play a favourable role but if he does he must be considered

afComment: Possessing the trademark run and carry game that many other Irish players have, Geelong will look to play Mullin as a dashing half-back after developing his skills over the preseason.
afShort: Defender fresh off a code swap from Gaelic Football

afComment: Previously a wingman entering 2022, Cadman developed into the best key position forward in the draft, headlined by strong contested marking ability and averaging 2.5 goals per game in the NAB League and U18 Champs. From his time as a midfielder, he knows how to get the ball in his hands, and has been likened to Jeremy Cameron, averaging almost 17 disposals and 6 marks a game, although his impact is yet to be discovered against bigger bodies in state leagues. He may get some games early, but will likely be a slow burn and need time to develop, and it's difficult to pay top dollar for a KPP.
afShort: A KPP at top dollar, we'll wait and see on Cadman's role in the preseason.

afComment: Arguably the best player in the draft, Chris Fagan mentioned Ashcroft could have debuted in 2022 if he was eligible. A prolific ball winner both inside and outside, he has a great fantasy game, averaging 118 in both the NAB League and the U18 Champs, and was awarded the Larke Medal as the best player of the champs. Assuming he plays round 1, he should be an automatic starter in your midfield.
afShort: The best fantasy scorer in the draft, Ashcroft is a must if he starts round 1.

afComment: Sheezel is a mid-sized forward with the ability to partner ball-winning ability with heavy impact on the scoreboard. Averaging 19 disposals and 3.3 goals a game, Sheezel went goalless just once in the NAB League instead finishing with a monster 159 fantasy points as he showed off his midfield prowess. Despite being bottom-aged, we should hope to see him feature early in a rebuilding North Melbourne side, but we may need to have a look during the pre-season.
afShort: Huge junior numbers which hopefully will translate to the big time, should be safe on-field if named round 1.

afComment: A tough inside ball winner, Wardlaw's 2022 only featured 3 NAB League games due to a number of hamstring injuries which also caused him to miss the U18 Champs carnival. 6 tackles and 20 disposals a game and the loss of JHF should see space open up to play early assuming his injury woes are behind him.
afShort: Inside midfielder who should have no problems slotting in at AFL level.

afComment: Primarily an outside player both on-ball and on the wing, Tsatas provides a huge ball-winning ability, averaging over 33 disposals and 7 marks a game throughout his NAB League campaign. Perhaps a small blemish on his record would be his defensive capabilities, averaging just 1.3 tackles per game in that same period. With the Bombers already having a number of accumulators on ball, expect his breakaway speed to be on full display with early games on the wing.
afShort: Outside ball accumulator with good delivery going inside.

afComment: A mid-forward mix, Humphrey averaged 100 fantasy points throughout the NAB League, and that too kicking relatively inaccurately in front of goal, finishing with 21.18. Touted for his leadership capabilities, the Suns should be keen to get games into him early, and the departure of Rankine should open the door for a mid-forward, though we should temper scoring expectations with the likelihood to be more forward early on.
afShort: Midfielder with the ability to go forward and hit the scoreboard.

afComment: A classic inside mid, Mackenzie thrives on stoppages and his ability to extract. His 3.7 tackles a game could use some improvement for an inside mid, as could his ability to hit the scoreboard, with just 4 goals across 10 NAB League games. He did however finish on a high, with 26 and 2 in the Grand Final. After the midfield exodus at Hawthorn over the trade period, let's hope to see him get a run at it in the preseason.
afShort: Inside mid who generally requires stoppages to get his hands on the ball.

afComment: Drawing strong comparisons to Joel Selwood, Clark is a strong inside mid with clean disposal and widely valued leadership traits. He was the second highest averaging player during the U18 Champs, going at 105 points per game and earning himself the Vic Country MVP. He seems ready-made for the AFL, but we also know that Geelong have a tendency to give their draftees more time to develop.
afShort: Thoroughly consistent inside mid and a projected future leader.

afComment: Having played last season primarily as a lockdown defender, Ginbey transitioned into a well-balanced midfielder for WA during the U18 Champs, including earning the WA MVP. Despite this, his fantasy numbers are not as great as other top picks, averaging around 75 in both the Champs and the WAFL Colts. In the 4 games he played in the WAFL, he averaged just 33 points, indicating he may be handed a defensive role if he plays early, so we'll have to keep an eye on where the Eagles play him in the preseason.
afShort: Having moved from defence to midfield, does his best work extracting from the contest.

afComment: Having drawn comparison to the likes of Bont and Danger, Phillipou is a big-bodied mid capable of taking over games through either weight of possession, or his ability to push forward and hit the scoreboard. He produced massive numbers in his SANFL U18 games, going at 123 from 8 games, with just 2 scores under 100. He had a good turnout for SA in the U18 Champs at 72 across his 3 games before an ankle injury curtailed his season.
afShort: A match-winner both in the middle and going forward.

afComment: A hard-running well-balanced mid with the ability to run off half back, Hollands should have a solid fantasy game after averaging 94 through the NAB League. Carlton typically like to get games into their high draft picks early, so hopefully we'll see Hollands slip onto a wing or half back flank across the preseason.
afShort: High possession winner able to find the ball wherever he lines up.

afComment: The second of Brisbane's father-son picks, Fletcher is a balanced midfielder with clean disposal, averaging 23 touches across 3 games in the U18 Champs. He should score well if he plays, although it might be tough to slot into an already stacked Lions midfield and he'll need time to develop physically.
afShort: Clean user and able to play inside or outside.

afComment: A big key position defender, Busslinger missed most of the season after undering a shoulder reconstruction, playing just 2 games for WA and 4 in the WAFL Colts. He scored well and got plenty of the ball due to his intercept marking ability, averaging 24 touches and 8 marks, but there's always a question mark when translating that to the AFL. His scores when playing in the WAFL were extremely underwhelming, indicating he'll likely need to time to develop in order to compete with the stronger bodies in the AFL.
afShort: Key defender with intercepting ability and accumulates linking defensive chains.

afComment: Playing similarly to Dustin Martin, Hewett is an inside mid who aims to break from stoppages and drive the ball forward at any cost, sometimes leading to poor kicking efficiency numbers. While capable of breaking games open, as shown by his 115 when returning through the WAFL Reserves and a huge game 1 for WA in the U18 Champs where he picked up BOG honours, he struggles with consistency. After a 29 disposal and 2 goal game, he failed to hit the scoreboard again and averaged just 16.3 disposals for the last 3 games. Despite his 2022 scores looking lower than other top picks, Hewett spent most of his year in the WAFL against tougher opposition, and his size and physicality should see him very capable of playing early in the season.
afShort: Game-breaking but inconsistent inside mid

afComment: A tall but skinny key forward, Jefferson provides strong overhead marking and the ability to hit the scoreboard even from minimal disposals. Averaging just 9 disposals a game, he averaged 3.5 goals a game in the U18 Champs and 2.2 in the NAB League, at least having a very high kick-to-handball ratio to scrape a few extra points. His Fantasy prospects aren't great, with very low tackle numbers and high reliance on marks into set shots which will prove far more difficult to come by against better defenders in the AFL, while his size will mean he may not even play in 2023 let alone round 1.
afShort: Tall, skinny key forward unlikely to play round 1

afComment: A strong inside mid with good consistency over his NAB League and U18 Champs games, Rowston averaged around 90 points including 22 disposals and 5 marks a game. Playing for Calder, he had a 2:1 kick-to-handball ratio and was able to hit the scoreboard every other game, while he had a roughly 50-50 split between contested and uncontested possessions. As always, the Giants have a seemingly endless line of players bound for more midfield time, so we'll have to see where he plays in the pre-season to get a proper idea of his role.
afShort: Inside mid with high kick to handball ratio

afComment: Primarily a lockdown defender, Michalanney does well reading the play and using his height to fly for intercept marks. Unfortunately his numbers don't jump out, averaging 65 for the season in the SANFL Reserves and 26 in the Seniors. Given his role will almost certainly be a shutdown role if he plays, its hard to pick him as he'll be a slow burn at best and there should be plenty of better options for a lower price.
afShort: Lockdown defender, hard to pick

afComment: Weddle is a tall defender who is already well-built, giving him the ability to play on taller opponents when required. He provides great speed when exiting defence, often driving the ball forward as displayed by his 3.5 R50s a game in the U18 Champs. His numbers in the NAB League are relatively modest at just 54 average, and he seems the type who could have some very high scoring Fantasy games when match-ups suit.
afShort: Tall defender with a big rebounding game

afComment: Allan is a tall mid capable of playing both inside and outside, averaging 25 disposals and 6 marks a game in the WAFL Colts. Given his growth spurt over the last year combined with his athletic ability, he could play anywhere on the ground, including as a key position player, although we'll have to wait until he fills out physically to find out where he settles.
afShort: Outside mid who could go key position

afComment: A high pressure small forward, Konstanty should provide scoring opportunities with strong defensive pressure, best shown by his average of nearly 6 tackles a game through his NAB League campaign. Although they had a disastrous finish to the season, the Swans made very few list changes and seemingly had quite a settled side come season's end, so we may need to see him force his way in with a huge preseason or early VFL showing.
afShort: Small forward with huge defensive pressure

afComment: Jones is a small outside mid who uses his elite agility and speed to navigate contests and drive forward. He averaged nearly 20 disposals a game for WA and scored 5 goals in his 4 games, while his early form in the WAFL Colts including a 145 point game saw a promotion to the Seniors later in the season. Although he was drafted from a mid position, be wary that the Giants directly stated they saw him in a small forward type role so his scoring expectations should be tempered.
afShort: Drafted as a mid but likely to play forward

afComment: Gruzewski is a tall swingman, able to play key positions at both ends of the ground. Given the roles he's played and his junior numbers, it's unlikely he'll be too relevant in the Fantasy game.
afShort: Key position defender with ability to go forward

afComment: The first ruckman selected in the draft, Barnett is already well built at 96kg on his 202cm frame. He had a great season for West Adelaide at U18 level, going at 94 including a 5 game stretch averaging 120 which saw him earn a promotion to the senior side. The Eagles already have a few rookie rucks in line to play so it seems he might be unlikely to start early this season, if at all.
afShort: Rookie ruck, unlikely to play early

afComment: Clarke is a high-pressure forward who can handle stints in the midfield while consistently hitting the scoreboard, going goalless just once after round 1 in the NAB League. A 7 goal performance in round 4 showed he could hit the scoreboard hard, but it was his 33 disposals and 2 goals in round 10 that produced his highest fantasy score, a great effort considering his Sandringham Dragons side featured 3 of the top 7 draftees of this season. Going into a Bulldogs team with huge top end midfield talent, expect him to play a small forward role if he manages a game, and therefore inconsistent scoring as per his junior numbers.
afShort: A small-medium forward with the capability to go huge

afComment: At 199cm tall in a key defender post, Hayes' best scoring prospects come when he can be freed up to intercept and release the ball from the backline. Despite being bottom-aged and having only just turned 18 in December, he produced strong scores in the NAB League, going at 80 points including over 20 touches a game. He still needs some time to develop physically, but coming into an Essendon side looking to play their youth, we'll keep an eye on him in the preseason to see exactly where he fits in.
afShort: A near 2 metre defender with strong intercept marking

afComment: Capable of producing a big game, George was previously touted as a top 10 pick before an ACL rupture in the finals series of the NAB League saw him slide back to North Melbourne's pick 26. Wildly inconsistent, he produced 3 games of 80+ where he kicked a combined 14 goals, but he couldn't pass 40 in any of his other games. Given how late his injury occurred, we shouldn't expect to see him until very late this season, if at all.
afShort: A medium forward coming off an ACL injury

afComment: Noted as a small defender by the Swans, Vickery's scoring may be erratic as he will be asked to match up on some of the game's premier small forwards. His best chances come when he can break away and deliver off half-back and up onto the wing, while his 4.2 marks a game indicate he is part of chains in ball movement out of defence. Ceiling games in Rounds 8 and 9 of the NAB League of 25 disposals each show he can produce a big game, while he had just 1 recorded free against across his 13 games! At just 72kg, combined with Sydney's current strength in defence, we'll probably expect Vickery to be given a bit more time to fill out and perhaps play later in the season.
afShort: A small-medium running defender with strong breakaway off half-back

afComment: At 189cm tall, Ryan has great ball sense, knowing when to leave his opponent and intercept while proving extremely damaging on the rebound. In his U18s season in a premiership-winning Glenelg side, he averaged 106 fantasy points with incredible consistency, amassing between 28 and 30 disposals in all but 1 game, where he had 25 and kicked a goal. A low of 5 marks to go with 3.3 tackles a game shows he can score in all areas and should be considered when he manages to play.
afShort: Medium defender who can fill the stat sheet

afComment: A strong ball-winner, Burgiel averaged 22 disposals in the NAB League while also hitting the scoreboard consistently, although his finishing could use some work, kicking 12.11 from his 9 games. His standout attribute is his speed, recording the 3rd fastest 20m sprint in the combine, and he uses this to great effect, breaking away from stoppages and creating space when up forward. He was moved all around in the U18 Champs, playing both up forward and down back, but showed his versatility by changing his game, recording 4.3 marks a game up from his 2.3 average in the midfield. Coming into a WCE side fresh off a disastrous 2022 season, let's hope to see them blood their youth early and see how he fits in during the preseason.
afShort: Predominantly a midfielder but has shown he can be dangerous up forward

afComment: With a lethal long kick, Cowan is at his best when rebounding off half-back and delivering down the line, recording a 3:1 kick to handball ratio in his NAB League campaign. He also displayed a high level of consistency, never falling below 20 disposals and occasionally could hit the scoreboard, with 4 goals for the season. Touted for a leadership role in the future off the back of captaining Tasmania, he should be ready to play early in the season and if given a role off half-back should score well.
afShort: Rebounding defender with a high kick-to-handball ratio

afComment: While he is physically well developed, Van Es' scoring throughout juniors indicates he'll be unlikely to put up big scores in his transition to the AFL. Given he is a key position player, his average of 50 in the NAB League and 44 in the U18 Champs should come as no surprise, although he did produce the highest running vertical leap at the combine so St Kilda are bullish on realizing his athletic potential. Given his size, he should be capable of playing early, but we'll wait and see if he fits in during the preseason or is given more time to develop his craft.
afShort: Well-developed key defender with strength in marking contests

afComment: Binns is an extremely hard worker on the outside, gaining 75% of his possessions uncontested with a lowest disposal game of 18 in the NAB League grand final. He only got better in the U18 Champs, going at nearly 26 disposals a game on top of 6 marks and hitting the scoreboard every other game although his finishing in the NAB League was poor, kicking 8.17 for the season. He'll definitely be a wait and see during the preseason as he'll likely need time to develop physically before he's ready to play.
afShort: A hard-running outside mid with consistency in hitting the scoreboard

afComment: At 196cm and 90kg, Davies is a capable key defender whose best scoring comes from reading the ball and intercepting, averaging 9 intercept possessions in the WAFL Colts and 7 marks for WA in the U18 Champs. He also had a high uncontested possession rate at 72% indicating he is likely to link up in defensive chains off half-back. He struggled physically against some of the larger key forwards in the U18 Champs so he may need more time to develop physically before selection.
afShort: Tall defender who plays best when he can peel off to intercept

afComment: McMullin is a pressure player more than anything, noted for his one-percenters despite averaging under 2 tackles a game in the NAB League. His junior numbers are not great reading for Fantasy fans, averaging just 44 for the season which included a 26 and 29 in the Elimination and Preliminary finals respectively. He saved his best for last, producing a 73 point game which included a goal and 17 touches while he also kicked 2 goals in 3 games for Vic Country. Given we'll have to pay up for him, there should likely be better rookie options for your forward line even if he starts round 1.
afShort: High-pressure mid-forward but unlikely to score well

afComment: Starting his season in the forward line, Hotton averaged just 10 disposals from 3 games but a move into the midfield saw that increase to over 20 from his other 5. His best game of the season came for Vic Metro against SA, where he kicked 3 goals to go with 24 disposals. Unfortunately he'll be out for at least the first half of the season with a stress fracture in his back so he won't be a starting option.
afShort: Forward-turned-midfielder who can still damage in either position

afComment: Having moved from the forward line last season, McCallum has a great read of leading patterns, often resulting in good intercept marking numbers. His junior numbers aren't great, averaging 55 throughout the NAB League while his season ended with an ankle injury in the preliminary final. His best turnout came in Round 5, where he amassed 27 disposals and 10 marks en route to 99, however, he also had 3 games under 10 disposals indicating more of a lockdown role. No current news of him bashing the door down for selection Round 1, so we'll wait for the preseason to see where he fits in.
afShort: Medium-tall defender with capability of playing both tall and small

afComment: Turning out for Dandenong in the NAB League, Hustwaite was a highly consistent inside mid with the ability to swing back when needed, recording under 20 disposals just twice across his 12 games, while also averaging over 4 tackles a game. Despite being noted as an elite kick, where his composure was compared to Scott Pendlebury, Hustwaite has a tendency to handball, with just 2 games recording more kicks than handballs and overall more than 60% of his disposals going by hand.
afShort: Defensive-minded inside mid with high handballing numbers

afComment: One of the best lockdown defenders in this years draft, Adams had a strong season in the WAFL Colts, averaging 68 points and 5 marks per game. He showed his versatility in Round 12 by covering in the ruck, which included 11 hitouts and all 3 of his goals for the season. These strong performances saw him earn a call up to the League side for Round 17, where he had a solid game with 11 disposals and 6 marks. Given he has missed time in each of the last 2 seasons with shoulder injuries, expect Melbourne to give him more time to develop strength before debuting.
afShort: Key defender with a strong contested marking game

afComment: A slow start to the season as a small forward saw Gallagher record just 9 disposals and 29 points combined across the first 2 games before back-to-back 3 goal games showed a better glimpse of his talent. However, it was a move to the backline for the second half of the season which saw him burst onto the scene and become arguably the best Fantasy player in the comp from Round 13 onward. He averaged 35 disposals and over 5 marks per game for his last 5 which included a 3:1 K:H ratio, while also remarkably still hitting the scoreboard, with 18 scoring shots in the same period. Given his versatility, and having shown he can score heavily, he should be a good pick-up when he manages to break in for a game.
afShort: Highly capable in any area of the ground, having played in all 3 positions across his draft year

afComment: Best regarded for his two-way running, Mitchell uses his elite work rate to run opponents into the ground between half-back and half forward, averaging 3 I50s and 1.5 R50s across the NAB League. His best performance came in Round 8 from a strong all-round performance, with 2 goals, 31 disposals, and 7 marks for 126 Fantasy points. He could use some work on his discipline in contests, with just 6 FF to 15 FA for the season while he could use a bump in K:H ratio given he plays primarily on the wing. Given Sydney are coming off a strong 2022 and minimal list changes, expect Mitchell to have an extended run developing in the VFL before earning his chance at AFL level.
afShort: A wingman who works hard off half-back and delivering inside 50

afComment: A great start to the season at SANFL Reserve level saw Emmett earn a promotion to League level where he held his spot from Round 6 until the completion of the season. He started slowly, managing just 3 behinds in his first 5 games, however he managed at least 1 goal in every game from there onwards, including 11 goals over a 4 week golden period from Rounds 14-17 and an overall scoreboard impact of 17.10 for the season. Having played a full season of SANFL, he should be physically ready-made to make the jump into the AFL, it will just come down to how the Crows view his craft as to whether he plays early or is given more time to develop.
afShort: Slightly mature-aged medium forward with good senior experience

afComment: A huge developer over the 2022 season, Knobel is still growing and will need some time to develop into his massive frame. Given his height, he is more in the mould of the big lumbering ruckman, being able to push forward and provide a strong aerial option and an accurate shot at goal, kicking 5 straight in his NAB League campaign. However, with Fremantle bringing in Luke Jackson to partner Sean Darcy, there appears no spot in the immediate future for Knobel, so he'll likely be given an extended period to build up before debuting.
afShort: The 2nd best ruck in the draft, but stuck behind a few options at Fremantle

afComment: Capable of playing both inside and outside, Dowling turned out a monster year in the SANFL U18s, filling the stat sheet with nearly 31 disposals, 7 marks and 5 tackles a game on top of kicking 18.15 in front of goal. His standout performance and easily the standout performance of the draft, was his R16 match where he amassed 44 disposals including 35 kicks, to go with 17 marks, 6 tackles and 4.3 culminating in a 215 point display. If given the opportunity, he knows how to find the ball and should be a solid scorer when he makes his debut.
afShort: Massive accumulator and the highest Fantasy averaging player in the draft

afComment: For a KPP, Keeler showed strong scoring ability in the SANFL U18s, averaging 82 ppg where he was dangerous up forward with 19 goals, while being used in ball movement through the midfield when playing as a ruck. The Saints noted his potential ceiling as one of his appealing features which is a strong positive but also indicates they don't see him as ready yet for the AFL and will need time to develop. With Marshall at lead ruck and Jack Hayes likely to return, with Tom Campbell also very close, it should be no surprise if Keeler doesn't manage a single game at the top level this season.
afShort: Key position forward with flexibility in the ruck

afComment: While not lighting up the stats sheet every game, Alwyn Davey Jr produces his best work in short bursts through the midfield and providing a threat around goals. At just 180cm and 76kg, Essendon see him as exclusively a small forward early in his career with the eventual goal of being able to play as an impact midfielder. Wait and see if and where he fits in during the preseason.
afShort: Mid-forward with elite speed and pressure

afComment: Despite being small in stature, O'Sullivan has no problems in and around the contest with a strong start to the season for Oakleigh seeing him earn a spot in the Vic Country squad for the U18 Champs. He unfortunately sustained a fractured collarbone in the first game, putting him out for 2 months before reaggravating the injury upon his return to Oakleigh 2 months later. With his size and injury history a valid concern, expect Hawthorn to give him lots of time to build strength and develop in the VFL before being a chance of debuting.
afShort: A small well-balanced mid whose draft year was marred by injury

afComment: Playing primarily as a key forward, Lemmey played at all 3 levels in the SANFL across 2022 with his best performance coming in R13 at U18 level, where he kicked 6.0 from 18 disposals and 10 marks. His only poor score in U18s came against eventual premiers Glenelg where his inaccuracy cost him, kicking 1.4 from 7 disposals. He was also swung into the ruck and backline on occasion, and Carlton drafted him with this intention, noting they see him being able to play at either end of the ground. As with most talls in their first year, wait and see where he fits in, but don't hold your breath on him playing early.
afShort: Athletic key forward with experience in U18s, Reserve, and League level in SANFL

afComment: One of the feel good stories of the 2022 draft, Richards played NAB League in 2017 but went undrafted, instead going into teaching and playing local football where he earned an invite the combine after 3 B&Fs at Wangaratta. Despite playing as a midfielder, he managed 29 goals from 11 games, including a monster performance in his third senior game where he kicked 11 goals. The Magpies will likely look to play him as a small forward, having mentioned that he is undersized for a pure mid, but should be able to flex into other roles.
afShort: Mature-aged midfielder with explosive pace and high work-rate

afComment: Despite a relatively slow start to his 2022 campaign, Smith came home strong in the second half of the season, averaging 25 disposals and 4 marks in a poor East Fremantle team. Richmond were impressed not only by his defensive work in the WAFL Colts, but also his forward craft at school level and see him capable of playing wherever needed.
afShort: Half-back who took his game to the next level in the back half of the season

afComment: While not as much of a natural ball winner as some other inside mids, averaging 20 disposals per game, Bond more than makes up for it with his physicality, averaging 9 tackles and earning his touches at nearly 50% contested. Only time will tell, but given his playstyle, it's hard to tell whether he was fortunate or unfortunate in being drafted to the Crows. His high-pressure contested game should fit right in with the likes of Laird and Sam Berry, but will that also mean he can't break in due to being too similar? At basement price, he should be a good selection when/if he manages to play.
afShort: Defensive-minded, physical inside mid

afComment: Having overcome injuries over the previous 2 seasons, McLennan played most of the season in the NAB League, with 3 games at VFL level as well. He has the capability to play tall and small, but it's always in a lockdown position, so his scoring will never be great. On a somewhat positive note, his scoring barely changed when transitioning to VFL level, but it's hard to go backwards from 37 anyway. Not really pickable unless there's some clear role change in the preseason.
afShort: Lockdown defender with some senior experience

afComment: Having spent most of his year injured, playing just 2 SANFL U18s games and 1 U18 Champs game, Munkara will be keen to get a full preseason under his belt in 2023. He uses his speed and agility to create front half pressure and consequently goal opportunities, averaging 4 tackles and 3 goals this season. He'll need some work on his consistency with recruiters noting he has a tendency to fall out of games at times.
afShort: X-factor medium forward who delivers best in short bursts

afComment: Unfortunately for MacDonald, the numbers don't quite do him justice, with his line-breaking abilities for Oakleigh and at school level earning a Vic Metro call up for the U18 Champs. The Hawks see him slotting in at either half-back or a potential move to the wing, however given his scoring from juniors, there should be other options producing better scores.
afShort: Damaging off half-back by breaking lines with explosive pace

afComment: Drury put out a solid season at Oakleigh, averaging 85 from 7 games, including 2 scores of 115+. He dominated Round 1 but could have been so much more, kicking 3.5 from his 21 disposals, while a 31 disposal, 9 mark effort in the Wild Card match gave him his highest score for the season. Overall he could use some composure in front of goal, finishing with 7.14 for the season, and his tackling at just over 2 per game could use a bump. Despite playing as a mid for most of juniors, his size will mean his best chance at playing will come as a pressure forward, and thus his scoring will likely suffer.
afShort: Small mid-forward with solid numbers at state and national level

afComment: A little bit of a ruck-forward mix, Owen has solid contested marking ability while his height allowed him to dominate games from the ruck. He'll need some work on his consistency, with 4 sub 50 scores in the NAB League, including 2 below 30. With players like Amartey and McLean vying for a similar role, Owen will almost certainly not play this season while they work on his development.
afShort: Ruck with limited possessions and some developing to do

afComment: Williams doesn't possess the physical attributes of many of the other draftees, instead using his speed and agility to skirt the edge of contests and transition off half-back and into the forward 50. He had a good showing at WAFL Colts level, averaging 17 disposals while showcasing his defensive capabilities with 10 tackles across the final 2 rounds. He'll need a mountain of work in preseason to get strong enough to play after coming in at just 63kg, so wouldn't even be expecting him to play this season.
afShort: Rapid outside mid/half-back

afComment: Somewhat similar to his father, Harvey is strong in the contest and dangerous around goal, kicking 5.4 and averaging 23 disposals and 6 marks from his 7 completed games. In a developing North Melbourne side, Harvey might get games early, and if picked, he is a proven scorer at junior level and should have some success at AFL level.
afShort: Tough mid-forward with a strong inside game

afComment: Having spent 3 years pursuing a basketball career, McDowell-White returned to Brisbane in 2022, playing in 4 of their last 5 games at VFL level. His scoring potential isn't great, with a season high of just 13 disposals and 56 points, while Brisbane have noted they will look to let him build over another preseason, and fighting for a position in a stacked midfield indicates he will be more of a development player for the future.
afShort: Mature-aged mid-forward returning to the game after an extended break

afComment: A hugely tap-dominant ruckman in the WAFL, Free had 3 games of 55+ hitouts with a season low of 31 which came against Fremantle ruck Lloyd Meek. While he doesn't quite rack up the disposals, averaging just over 10 per game, his defensive workrate steadily improved over the season with 27 tackles from his last 5 games, resulting in a 92 average. Given he is mature-aged, he will absolutely be ready to play and should score ok, but the main problem is knowing when that chance will actually come. North have looked like developing Xerri into a proper first ruck, with Coleman-Jones developing into a ruck-forward role and that likely leaves no space unless their form warrants dropping.
afShort: A massively dominant ruck at WAFL League level

afComment: Highly capable as either a mid or a forward, Magor averaged 22 disposals and 2.3 goals at SANFL U18 level for an average of 102. In round 8 against eventual premiers Glenelg, he picked up 41 disposals and 2 goals for 161, while he also kicked 5.1 and 6.3 in his last 2 games upon returning from an ankle injury. He also showed his ability to find space by reaching 9 marks on 4 separate occasions, including 3 contested in the final round. His most likely spot if he manages a game will be up forward due to his size but it'll still be difficult to break in initially.
afShort: A ball winner and goal kicker who can break games open in either role.

afComment: While he has played all over the ground, Gillbee is best using his outside game to run off half-back and the wing. He ran the equal fastest time for the 2km time trial at the Draft Combine, and was part of the NAB League Team of the Year this season. He much prefers to dispose by foot, with 37 kicks to 12 handballs for the Allies, however he'll need to work on his 59% KE. Given his flexibility he could be a chance at playing early and should score relatively well if he gets a half-back/wing role.
afShort: A great utility pick, having played back, mid and forward for separate stints

afComment: A typical small forward, Jayden Davey uses his speed and agility around goals to create both offensive and defensive threats. Having missed 2 seasons with ACL injuries, expect the Bombers to be cautious with their approach in the preseason and likely give him an extended period before setting sights on a debut.
afShort: Small forward coming off consecutive ACL injuries

afComment: Bakerhad a strong period from Round 5, averaging 24 disposals and 7 tackles, however he had a lean month after that, dropping to just 14 disposals including registering just 1 tackle in Round 17. He'll need to work on consistency, with lean and strong periods seemingly lasting over a month at a time. Also expect some time for him to put on a bit more weight in order to compete physically.
afShort: Speedy wingman with great defensive pressure

afComment: An exciting outside mid in juniors, Bennetts is best when transitioning the ball from midfield into the forward 50, while also being dangerous around goal. He averaged 18 disposals and 1.1 goals per game across 13 NAB League games for 75 points. He's expected to move to a small forward role at the top level, and this will mean his scoring will take a dive from his junior numbers.
afShort: Midfielder in juniors but will turn to a small forward role

afComment: Having played in all 'tall' positions across the season, Fremantle see Draper as a key defender in their future. As per usual with key position players, his scoring won't be great, with 5 of his 8 games this season featuring sub-10 disposals and failing to pass 2 tackles in any games after returning from injury. Expect him to be given a while to develop his craft before a chance at selection.
afShort: Key position swingman with elite athleticism

afComment: Farris-White played football as a junior, though has barely played for the last 6 years, and will be seen as a development player for a team in absolutely no need of rucks. Given he's not even the best rookie ruck option at Melbourne, there's virtually 0% chance he plays so only time he might see on field is captain loopholing.
afShort: Ruck coming off a code swap from basketball

afComment: Despite his skinny frame, Marshall is a capable key defender, using his reach to intercept and spoil while also chopping out in the ruck when needed. At just 84kg, he'll need plenty of time to develop before his body is able to hold up against the stronger forwards at AFL level.
afShort: Tall but skinny key defender

afComment: Solidly built at 204cm and 104kg, Reidy played the entire season for Frankston in the VFL, showing his flexibility by playing both Ruck and Forward when required. He averaged 20 hitouts and 4 tackles, with his best game coming in Round 21, with 27 hitouts and 3.1 for 116 points. Unfortunately he's stuck in line behind Darcy and Jackson, although given his development, may jump past Knobel if a spot opens up this season.
afShort: Mature-aged ruck with a full season at VFL level

afComment: Johnston is an athletic rebounding defender, reading the ball well through the air to intercept and break away off half-back, best shown by his 28 intercept possessions and 22 R50s from 36 disposals for NT in the NAB League. His preference is clearly to deliver by foot, with just 3 handballs to his 33 kicks, although his defensive side could use some improvement, averaging just 1.5 tackles per game. He should be an exciting pick if he plays, but will likely need more time to develop his defensive craft before he is handed a debut.
afShort: Medium-sized rebounding defender

afComment: Barkla produced a highly consistent season in the SANFL U18s which saw him earn a promotion to League level for the final 3 rounds of the season. He never went below 18 disposals after Round 4, while also recording 6+ marks on 3 occasions. He averaged 20 disposals at 82% efficiency for the season, although his League games were quieter, averaging just 8 touches at 71%. If he breaks in to the team, expect him to play off half-back and potentially earn DPP status.
afShort: Outside mid/half-back with clean disposal

afComment: Madden is physically well ahead of many other rucks in his draft class, weighing in at 112kg, and he'll learn to use that size under Shane Mumford at the Giants. He performed strongly in the NAB League, with 14 disposals and 25 disposals per game for 81 points. He has had a delayed start to his preseason after an ankle injury, but that likely won't affect his standing anyway, with the Giants stating he is seen as a long-term prospect.
afShort: Ruck-forward with a touch of senior experience

afComment: Previously having played as in inside mid, Long broke his collarbone in Round 1 of the NAB League, shifting to the forward line upon his return in Round 16. He averaged 89 upon his return and his U18 Champs numbers were promising, averaging nearly 6 marks per game and a 3:1 K:H ratio with the standout performance being a 3 goal game against WA.
afShort: Small inside mid with the ability to push forward

afComment: Having not even been selected to play in the NAB League, Sestan instead plied his trade in the Goulburn Valley League, topping the goalkickers list despite playing just 6 games. That included a massive bag of 24, and although he won't see that kind of opportunity in the AFL, it's good to know he takes his chances in front of goal. Unfortunately he's more of a depth player and currently looks unlikely to crack in to a strong Demons side.
afShort: Medium forward who can kick a bag

afComment: At just 65kg, Riccardi is best on the outside where he can use his run transitioning off half-back and through the wing. He'll be given plenty of time to develop physically before managing to play, so may not even expect the debut to come this year. With Isaac Smith now 34, that spot on the wing seems the most likely avenue whenever the retirement comes.
afShort: Small, agile outside midfielder

afComment: A bit of an in-between height, Murdoch has played both tall and small in primarily lockdown roles during his NAB League season. Just 2 scores over 60 doesn't bode well for scoring capabilities in the top flight, and being a rookie at Geelong doesn't help either. Almost certainly will be better options elsewhere even if he manages to play.
afShort: Medium defender who can play a variety of defensive roles

afComment: Having dominated in the forward line at SANFL U18s level with 26 goals from 11 games, including 0 goalless, Foster earnt a late call-up to the SA side for the U18 Champs as ruckman after first-choice Harry Barnett was out with COVID. He strongly impressed recruiters, managing to retain his spot in the side as a forward as Barnett returned. Geelong are looking to develop his game further, so don't expect him to play this season.
afShort: Key forward who can chop-out in the ruck

afComment: A great reader of the ball in the air, more than half of Montgomerie's disposals came off the back of a mark, averaging 8 marks across his 17 games this season. At 190cm, he should play as a 2nd or 3rd tall defender, and having physically developed over the last few years from playing at senior level, expect him to be ready for a call-up as soon as space opens.
afShort: Mature-aged intercept defender with nearly 2 full seasons at SANFL League level under his belt

afComment: A highly consistent scorer, Campbell averaged 89 for the season for Tassie in the NAB League, with a season low of 67. He managed at least one scoring shot every game, with his peak coming in a massive Round 5 performance where he kicked 6.2 from 32 disposals and 11 marks for a 179. His playstyle could complement Richmond, given they already have enough inside grunt and he could play a more natural outside game, but he also seems a perfect candidate to get the graveyard shift on a half-forward flank having playing mid-forward through juniors.
afShort: A hard-running mid-forward who does his best work on the outside

afComment: Already a cult hero thanks to his name, Brain is an impact player up forward, with a highly dangerous skillset around goals. The Lions see him in a high forward role with eventual development into the midfield, though his scoring through juniors has never been great.
afShort: X-factor medium forward, able to play tall or small

afComment: Having played at League level in the WAFL for most of the season, Green put up commendable numbers playing as un undersized midfielder, averaging over 72 ppg from 18 disposals and 4 tackles, with a season high 122 coming in the final round which included 31 disposals, 4 marks and 7 tackles. He might struggle to find a spot in the Tigers outfit early on, as the inclusions of Taranto and Hopper are likely to eat up any openings in the midfield, and he generally fails to hit the scoreboard, with just 2 goals for the season.
afShort: A small midfielder with good senior experience

afComment: Performing best when in close, Clohesy is an inside mid with great stoppage craft, averaging over 7 tackles and 23 disposals per game in the NAB League. He put in a massive round 1 performance with 27 disposals and 14 tackles, with 6 frees for helping him to a 139. His current knock from recruiters is his kicking and minimal impact away from contested areas.
afShort: Aggressive stoppage midfielder

afComment: Not to be confused with the elite wingman by the same name, Scully is a tall forward who used his height to great advantage to dominate U18 level in the SANFL, which included a 5 week period where he kicked 31.5 and averaged 99 Fantasy points. The knock on his scoring is that he often doesn't gather stats elsewhere when not scoring goals, failing to record a tackle for the first 7 rounds of the season and never having more than 2 hitouts in a game until Round 16 despite his 203cm frame. Given he'll be moving to the bigger bodies at senior level, expect him to be given a decent stint at SANFL League level before earning a debut.
afShort: Elite tall forward with the ability to go massive on the scoreboard

afComment: Very much a key position player, Young's only score above 60 in the VFL came in a move to the ruck with Samson Ryan out for the week. Hard to pick as he'll be a slow burn at best.
afShort: Mature-aged key defender

afComment: Dewar played the first few games as an attacking half-back before a switch to the forward line saw him kick 14 goals from his next 8 games. His consistency is his main problem, with 5 games below 10 disposals, and 4 games with sub-40 scores. He'll need to develop his forward half pressure if he is to come in as a small forward, and at just 70kg will need some physical development over the preseason.
afShort: Offensive option at either end of the ground

afComment: Verrall was considered one of the best rucks coming into the draft before groin and hip injuries led to him sliding to the rookie draft. He is a highly talented scorer, with 6 games over 100, which he did playing some as forward and some in the ruck. In the final rounds of the season, he really came through with his ruck craft, monstering opponents by recording 36+ hitouts in 4 of the final 5 games. His only problem now is that he is stuck behind the best ruck duo in the comp at Melbourne, and it's hard to see when he might get a look-in.
afShort: Inconsistent but very high ceiling scoring for a ruckman

afComment: At 100kg and 197cm, Edwards has what it takes to compete with the best key forwards of the draft with elite breakaway speed especially for his size. Unfortunately his scoring potential isn't great, like most other key defenders, as shown by a 41 average in the NAB League and 29 in the U18 Champs. He is physically ready but will be given time to develop his football game so don't expect a debut this season.
afShort: Key defender physically ready to make the jump
